<SLUG> BC-FBO-TEXAS-HIGHSCHOOL-PLAYOFFS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALEDO SECURES FIRST STATE FOOTBALL TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC ZARATE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Give it too much room, and Aledo's defense is prone to
make a few mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Put their backs near the goal line, and it's another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Back-to-back sacks shut the door on Cuero with 1:32 remaining to
give the Bearcats the Class 3A Division I state title, 14-7,
yesterday at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Aledo (13-1) wins its first football championship in the
school's second title-game appearance. The first was in 1974. Cuero
(11-4) has three state titles, and was in its ninth final since
1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a bend-but-don't-break defense,'' Aledo coach Tim
Buchanan said. ``We put on a big pass rush there at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bearcats scored the go-ahead touchdown on running back Matt
Saunders' 2-yard run with 2:45 left in the game. Aledo executed a
5-minute, 50-second drive that covered 73 yards in 17 plays. The
Bearcats converted two fourth-down plays along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Cuero got its final opportunity when Derrick Buchanan returned a
short kickoff 35 yards to the Aledo 45. A 20-yard pass from Andrew
Heard to Albert Wade moved the ball to the Bearcats 25.
</P>
<P>
   After two incompletions, cornerback Will Sadler sacked Heard for
an 18-yard loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went inside, so I had to watch for anything coming out of
the backfield,'' Sadler said. ``I thought he was about to throw it,
but I got him.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Lucas Turner tackled Heard for a 7-yard loss on
fourth-and-28 at the Bearcats 43.
</P>
<P>
   Aledo got the ball back at midfield, and picked up a first down
to run out the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a double-team,'' Turner said of his sack. ``I went
inside of both of them, and ripped the quarterback. Their offense
was great. They'd make a big play, then we'd stick our heads in
there and make a bigger play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bearcats defense recorded four sacks, and six other tackles
behind the line. In the second half, Cuero's offense was limited to
50 yards and five first downs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them the best football team they'd see all year was
Cuero, and there was no doubt about it,'' coach Buchanan said.
``The defense won the football game.''
</P>
<P>
   Aledo outgained Cuero, 237-197. Quarterback Joel Laminack
completed 13 of 28 for 158 yards, with one interception. Wide
receiver Donald Hays caught five for 57. Running quarterback
Cameron Hill gained 33 yards on eight carries.
</P>
<P>
   After a scoreless first half, Aledo got on the board first with
3:51 remaining in the third quarter when Laminack ran the ball in
from the Cuero 34. Operating out of the shotgun formation, Laminack
took advantage of a huge hole up the middle for the touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Cuero cornerback Delrick Washington picked off Laminack's pass
at the Aledo 23 with 51 seconds left in the third, and Heard
connected with receiver Sean Cullen 47 seconds later for a 19-yard
score that tied the game, 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   After that, a long drive and stout defense earned Aledo the
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't really do anything special,'' Tim Buchanan said.
``It was a great team effort. You might just call it luck.''
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Zarate writes about high school sports for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 548-5419. Visit the
Star-Telegram's high school sports site on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com/sportszone) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
