<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-TEXAS-HIGHSCHOOL-PLAYOFFS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPHENVILLE SLIPS PAST CARROLL TO HIT 4A DIVISION II FINAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY PHILLIPS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Carroll quarterback Nathan Chandler perhaps had
the most astute reaction to Stephenville's 31-28 circus victory in
last night's Class 4A Division II semifinal game at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, Carroll's capable 6-foot-6 passer, also summed up the
firepower Stephenville's offense regularly has at its disposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense played great holding them to 31 points,'' Chandler
said. ``For Stephenville, that's great. We just had to score more
points to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Another game, another lesson learned too late.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Kelan Luker's 52-yard game-winning scoring pass to
receiver Cody Cardwell with 1:04 remaining was the deciding blow
delivered against Carroll's defense.
</P>
<P>
   With its victory, two-time state champion Stephenville (14-1)
earned its third meeting with La Marque (13-0) in a title game this
decade. The teams will meet 4 p.m. Saturday in the 4A Division II
Texas Bowl at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it'd be a war all the way through,'' Stephenville
coach Art Briles said of his team's first-ever game against
Carroll. ``This is a great win for the community of Stephenville
and a tribute to our program.''
</P>
<P>
   With Chandler and running back Clay McNutt (160 yards, four
touchdowns rushing) stretching Stephenville's defense to a limit
rarely seen this year, the Yellow Jackets overcame nine lead
changes and a crucial loss of possession with 2:43 to play.
</P>
<P>
   After McNutt's fourth touchdown run gave Carroll a 28-24 lead,
Luker (338 yards, four touchdowns passing) was sacked twice on his
team's ensuing possession. After the second sack, Stephenville
elected to roll the dice and try for a first down on fourth-and-17
at its own 35.
</P>
<P>
   But Carroll stopped the Yellow Jackets and took possession at
the 26, drove to the Stephenville 19 and went for a first down on
fourth-and-3. Stephenville linebacker Keith McCormick stopped
McNutt after a 2-yard gain, fulfilling Stephenville's hope for a
last possession.
</P>
<P>
   A Carroll field goal would have pushed the Dragons' lead to
31-24. But an inexperienced kicking game caused Carroll coach Tom
Rapp to go Vegas-style himself.
</P>
<P>
   It was a gamble Carroll might regret.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to kick a field goal, but we were too far \R36
yards\S,'' Rapp said. ``I've got two sophomore kickers and they
can't kick it that far.''
</P>
<P>
   Three plays later, Cardwell added to his already-growing lore.
</P>
<P>
   With 1:04 to play, Luker dropped back, waited and fired 52 yards
to Cardwell (12 catches, 287 yards, three touchdowns) for the
game-winning score.
</P>
<P>
   ``It couldn't have worked out any better,'' Briles said. ``You
play that out 10 times, it might work for you one or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throw it up, let him run under it, catch a touchdown. That's
about as simple as it gets. Cody's a different cat. We're just
thankful to have him.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll had one final drive of its own beginning with 58 seconds
to play, but it ended with four consecutive incompletions by
Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the fourth quarter, Stephenville's Clayton Harmon
sacked Chandler to end a Carroll drive _ a defensive stop that
proved crucial to the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Luker found Cardwell on the next Stephenville possession,
freeing himself from a defensive back for a 43-yard touchdown and
24-21 Yellow Jackets lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole game we had a chance to put it away but we didn't
execute,'' Chandler said. ``I threw too many bad passes, and that
hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   (Troy Phillips writes about high school sports for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7377. Visit
the Star-Telegram's high school sports site on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com/sportszone) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 0035EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
