<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7157 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-SENATORS-     12-13 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-SENATORS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES, KHA BIBULIN GET SWEET RE VENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANATA, Ontario _ Games in the regular season aren't supposed to
mean a whole heck of a lot in the NHL, a league where it seems
every team makes the playoffs regardless of how good or bad it is.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday night meant something a little more special for the
Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I'm sure they're going to be gunning for us,'' Ottawa
Senators Coach Jacques Martin said before the game. ``We gave them
a pretty good roughing up in the first game of the year, and I've
got to believe they'd like to get us back if they can.''
</P>
<P>
   They did, but it took 60 minutes of non-stop grit and sweat _
and a world-class performance from goalie Nikolai Khabibulin _
before the Coyotes could impeach the Senators, 2-0, at the Corel
Centre.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, which avenged a brutal 4-1 season-opening loss at
home to Ottawa on Oct. 11, kept the surging Coyotes (17-3-3)
unbeaten in 18 of their past 19 games. They are 3-0-1 since having
their franchise-record 14-game unbeaten string snapped in Edmonton
on Dec. 2. They are tied with New Jersey (37 points) for the best
record in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, you want to get a little revenge,'' said captain
Keith Tkachuk, who battled the flu all day but toughed it out and
was in the lineup. ``We didn't play our best tonight, but that
night, we played absolutely terrible. They took it to us that first
time and embarrassed us in our own building.''
</P>
<P>
   Not this time, though.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Jyrki Lumme scored the deciding goal, a one-handed
fling at a loose puck dug away from Ottawa goalie Ron Tugnutt early
in the second period. It was the lone goal of the contest until
fellow defenseman Teppo Numminen salted the victory with an
empty-netter with 48 seconds left to play.
</P>
<P>
   Khabibulin, meanwhile, who pitched his third shutout to improve
to 11-3-1, easily was the star of the game. As clutch as Lumme's
third goal of the season was, just about every one of Khabibulin's
42 saves was a virtual must if the Coyotes were to exact a little
revenge on the Senators and start their four-game trip on a
positive note.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the man,'' Tkachuk said of Khabibulin. ``He's absolutely
``the'' man.''
</P>
<P>
   Ottawa (13-10-3) had the Russian bear of a netminder turning
cartwheels in front of the goal, diving, sliding, spinning and
scrambling. At least a half dozen times, it looked as if the
Senators were on the doorstep of lighting the lamp. But each time,
Khabibulin slammed the door in their face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, he was the difference in the game,''
Ottawa's Martin said. ``We couldn't put anything past him, it
seemed, no matter how many shots or chances we had.''
</P>
<P>
   As seconds ticked off the game clock, and the Senators did their
best to keep up their attack, the Bulin Wall seemed to grow only
stronger and more impenetrable. Even when Martin pulled Tugnutt
with 1:13 left in regulation in favor of an extra skater,
Khabibulin didn't flinch or fail.
</P>
<P>
   Neither did the players in front of him, who quickly cleared the
puck out of the Phoenix zone time and time again when it mattered
most. In the end, center Jeremy Roenick moved it up along the
boards to Tkachuk, who spotted Numminen alone at the point. He
reared back on a slap shot and the ensuing blast went in off an
Ottawa defenseman for the insurance goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pretty good tonight,'' said Khabibulin, who hadn't
played since last Saturday in Calgary. ``I probably could have
played another period or so. But it wasn't just me. The guys did a
pretty good job in front of me, clearing the rebounds. It was
probably more of a team effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my confidence is pretty good right now. I know I can stop
the puck, and all I needed to do was work on consistency and the
mental aspects of things, and at the same time, work on my physical
shape so I don't get tired.''
</P>
<P>
   He was wide awake against the Senators. He had to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played a tremendous game,'' Coyotes Coach Jim Schoenfeld
said. ``It seemed to me it didn't matter how long the game was
going to go: Nik was kind of in a zone tonight, and nothing was
going to get past him.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 0049EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
