<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUNIOR YEARS GOOD TO SMITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANATA, Ontario _ Coyotes General Manager  &UR; Bobby Smith returned
to his hometown with a hero's welcome, having his No. 15 jersey
retired Friday night by his junior team, the Ottawa 67's, before
their Ontario Hockey League game against the Belleville Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who was accompanied by his wife,  &UR; Beth, and children,
 &UR; Ryan,
 &UR; Megan and  &UR; Daniel, played three seasons here in the late 1970s,
scoring 158 goals and 385 points. In 1977-78, he set an OHL record
for points (192) and assists (123) in a season.
</P>
<P>
   During the ceremony, Smith likened the moment to May 24, 1986,
when he was with the Montreal Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fortunate enough on that night to score the Stanley
Cup-winning goal,'' he told the crowd at the Civic Centre. ``But I
do not think any boy growing up in Canada or anywhere else has the
audacity to dream that one day he will play on his hometown team,
and one day that team will see fit to retire his jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith saved his most personal gratitude for his former coach,
 &UR; Brian
 &UR; Kilrea, still coaching the 67's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a kid who played hockey when I got here as a
17-year-old,'' Smith said, ``and three years later, I was a hockey
player. That might seem like a semantical difference to some, but
Brian knows what I mean. I could barely compete in the OHL at one
point, and three years later, I was ready to go head to head with
any team in the NHL. Brian, you know it. Thank you very much.'' &QL; 
Home again II &QL; 
Smith wasn't the only person to enjoy a nice homecoming. Rookie
defenseman  &UR; Bryan Helmer, who was raised in the small town of
Winchester, about 30 miles south of Ottawa, had nearly half of his
hometown watch him play Saturday night against the Senators at the
Corel Centre.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe not half. But more than 200 friends and family members
from Winchester (population 3,500) were in attendance. Playing in
nearby Albany, N.Y., for the past five years, Helmer could always
find time to pay his family a visit around the Christmas holidays.
This year, he wasn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   If defenseman  &UR; Gerald Diduck hadn't suffered a charley horse
last week, the general consensus was that Helmer probably would be
sent to Las Vegas of the International Hockey League for the fourth
time. Diduck played Saturday, leaving Coach  &UR; Jim Schoenfeld with a
tough decision. Which defenseman would be a healthy scratch?
</P>
<P>
   He chose  &UR; Deron Quint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of anything much more exciting than getting a
chance to play in an NHL game in front of all those people I know
for the first time,'' Helmer said. ``It's the kind of stuff you
dream about.'' &QL; 
Slap shots &QL; 
Center  &UR; Jeremy Roenick will play in his 700th career game Wednesday
night in Toronto in his and the Coyotes' final appearance at
storied Maple Leaf Gardens. The facility will close in the coming
weeks and make way for a new arena for the Leafs. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 0049EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981213.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7159 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UMASS-NORTHWESTER     12-13 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UMASS-NORTHWESTERNSTATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMASS SURGES INTO FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATCHITOCHES, La. _ Choo-choo! Next whistle-stop for the
Minuteman Express: Chattanooga, Tenn. All aboard!
</P>
<P>
   The University of Massachusetts football program, derailed last
season by the long, uphill struggle of a 2-9 campaign, continued
one of the nation's most stunning turnarounds Saturday, taking the
express route to the NCAA Division 1-AA championship game with a
41-31 semifinal victory over host Northwestern State before a
Turpin Stadium crowd of 10,424.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th-seeded Minutemen (11-3) earned a first-class berth in
next Saturday's title game in Chattanooga against top-seeded
Georgia Southern (14-0), which routed Western Illinois, 42-14, in
the day's other semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   It will be only the second UMass appearance in the Division 1-AA
championship game _ the other was a loss to Florida A&AMP;M in the
inaugural 1-AA playoffs in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to have a good shot next week, because I
don't think they thought this was the end all,'' said first-year
UMass coach Mark Whipple, who, from the moment he set foot on
campus in Amherst last June, established the national championship
as a team objective. ``We played well and we played hard and we
accomplished what we wanted to do this week, but there's still
something left. It wasn't like the euphoria that will be there next
week if we can get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   After trailing, 24-21, at the end of the third quarter, the
Minutemen generated the momentum they needed from their hardnosed
defense to steamroll Northwestern State (11-3) with a
fourth-quarter outburst of 20 unanswered points.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a good job of mixing it up,'' said Northwestern State
quarterback Brad Spangler, who completed 10 of 24 attempts for 242
yards and a pair of TDs but was twice intercepted and was sacked
five times. ``They were showing different things and doing other
things. Credit their defense.''
</P>
<P>
   UMass, which got perfect symmetry from a balanced offense that
rolled up 237 rushing yards and 237 passing yards, went on its
fourth-quarter scoring spree with the help of a defense that made
three critical big plays: an interception by linebacker Khari
Samuel that led, one play later, to Todd Bankhead's 49-yard
touchdown pass to Matt Jordan; a fourth-and-9 stand that led to a
decisive eight-play, 64-yard march capped by Marcel Shipp's 24-yard
scoring run; and a freakish fumble recovery by defensive end Chris
Price, who pickpocketed running back Tony Taylor at the
Northwestern 12. That turnover, one of four by the Demons, set up a
1-yard plunge by Bankhead that gave UMass a 41-24 lead with 58
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   After outscoring UMass in the second quarter, 21-7, to take a
21-14 halftime lead, Northwestern was limited to a 29-yard field
goal by Thomas LaToof with 3:44 left in the third before scoring on
a 45-yard desperation pass from Spangler to Nathan Black with eight
seconds remaining in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Khari's interception was the biggest play of the
game,'' said Whipple. ``I felt like we were letting it slip away
when we gave the ball back (after a failed fourth-and-6 from the
Demons 38). But that just gave us a big lift.''
</P>
<P>
   On the first play following the interception, Whipple called
``North 56 Reverse Pass,'' a pass play designed to go to fullback
Matt Jordan that the Minutemen had used to open the game. ``When I
sent in the play, Todd kind of looked at me from the huddle, like,
`What do you mean?''' Whipple said. ``And I was, like, `Just run
the damn play and throw it for a touchdown.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bankhead, who completed 17 of 30 attempts for 237 yards and two
touchdowns and rushed for two more scores on a pair of 1-yard
plunges, took the snap, faked a reverse handoff to Adrian Zullo,
put the ball on his hip as he looked downfield, then complied with
his coach's orders by hitting a wide-open Jordan for a 49-yard
touchdown that gave UMass a 27-24 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had run it on the first play of the game,'' Bankhead said.
``But I couldn't believe how wide open he was the second time
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as remarkable was the hardnosed rushing effort of Shipp,
who led the Minutemen by rushing 38 times for 190 yards, the most
gained this season by a Northwestern opponent. With the big day,
Shipp surpassed the 3,000-yard mark for his career.
</P>
<P>
   Shipp, who had been hampered by a nagging left knee injury, got
crisp blocking from his offensive line on an eight-play, 64-yard
march that he sustained by carrying six times for 53 yards,
including the 24-yard scoring burst that gave UMass a 34-24 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Shipp had expressed concern that his game might
be missing a spark, ``But  &UR; today &LR;  I felt like I found it,'' he said
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Price provided a spark of his own by coming up with his amazing
take-away, which set up Bankhead's second 1-yard TD plunge,
perfectly punctuating this incredible postseason journey with an
exclamation point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the 14 games we've played this year, we've not had one bad
game,'' said Whipple. ``We've not had one bad week of practice.
These guys have been extremely consistent, and it's been a good
ride so far.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 0050EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981213.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
