u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-SABRES-BOS     12-13 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SABRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASEK, SABRES STOP BRUINS' STREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Sometimes it just isn't your day.
</P>
<P>
   Like when you arrive at your favorite coffee shop in the
morning, buy your cup of brew, but the lid isn't attached tightly
enough and you spill it all over the car floor. Add to that, they
were out of your favorite newspaper and the clerk gave you back 65
cents change in pennies that you dropped in the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   When you pull out of the parking lot, you notice the traffic is
backed up 3 more miles than usual, the skies have just opened up,
it's raining harder than you've ever seen, and your wipers won't
work. Then you hit the accelerator instead of the brakes and you
rear-end another car 40 feet from your office garage.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, no matter what you do, it all goes wrong.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of bad fortune the Bruins experienced against
the Buffalo Sabres Saturday night at the FleetCenter as they
dropped a 4-1 decision, ending their unbeaten streak at eight games
(6-0-2). It was the first loss for Boston in nearly a month, the
last Nov. 14 to Dallas, and just its second loss in 14 games
(8-2-4).
</P>
<P>
   ``We made things go their way,'' said coach Pat Burns. ``We did
it to ourselves. They didn't do it to us. I give them full credit.
We didn't deserve to be on the same ice surface as them the first
20 minutes. It's disappointing. We got away with it last game
against Carolina. It was the same first period we played against
Carolina. But we didn't get away with it tonight. They're not a
great team. They're a good team. They have a great goaltender, but
they're a good team because they don't seem to care who scores or
how it's scored and that's why they're having success. We've played
well in our last stretch of games and it would be unfair to the
players to say we're doomed for trouble, but we've won games in the
last couple that maybe we shouldn't have won.''
</P>
<P>
   The barrage started just 4:09 in when a bad giveaway by one of
the Bruins' most reliable players set the tone for disaster. Rob
DiMaio, among the team's most conservative and consistent forwards,
dished a blind backhanded pass from the right circle in the
defensive zone right to Buffalo center Brian Holzinger. Not pausing
to say ``Thank you,'' Holzinger marched down the slot and wristed a
shot past goalie Byron Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't plan on giving a guy a breakaway right at the hash
marks,'' said a dejected DiMaio. ``There's no excuse for it. It's
stupid. It's a not-prepared-to-play play. I deserve the heat. I set
the tone for the game. I don't really know what to say. I was just
awful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' luck went from bad to worse as they surrendered a
pair of goals in the final minute of the first period, ballooning
the Sabres' lead to 3-0. With 50.1 seconds remaining, forward Dixon
Ward, along the right-wing boards, delivered a hard pass to center
Mike Peca in the slot. Peca was all alone and he made the Bruins
pay for it as he fired a shot past Dafoe from the right hash marks.
</P>
<P>
   Miroslav Satan scored his first of two goals with only five
seconds remaining, banging in a rebound of a wraparound by left
wing Michal Grosek. The Sabres had three goals on nine shots and
the Bruins' heads were spinning.
</P>
<P>
   Satan scored the fourth Buffalo goal on the power play at 13:07
of the second, a period in which the Bruins outshot the Sabres,
21-8, but had nothing to show for it. The Bruins peppered goalie
Dominik Hasek (36 saves) but couldn't get anything past him. Steve
Heinze had four shots in the middle period and defenseman Dave
Ellett three.
</P>
<P>
   Boston broke through the nearly impenetrable netminder at 7:50
of the third, ending Hasek's shutout streak at 146 minutes 5
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   P.J. Axelsson scored his third goal of the year and second in
the last two games when he fired the puck from the right boards in
front for Chris Taylor but it instead hit Zhitnik and deflected
past Hasek. DiMaio earned an assist, wiping out the possibility of
his early mistake holding up as the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a perfect example where you had to show up,'' said
Burns. ``It was a perfect example where you look at the standings
and say we had a chance to move ahead in this whole thing. We have
a chance to beat a team that's comfortable and playing well and
confident and so are we. We missed our chance and that's what
disturbed me the most.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
