<HEADER>
A7167 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-SABRES-HASEK-BOS &LR;      12-13 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-HASEK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASEK TRUE TO `DOMINATOR' TAG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins tried nearly everything against Dom-inik
Hasek Saturday night. According to coach Pat Burns, some Bruins
went the fancy route, Sergei Samsonov was actually ``dancing,''
while others tried to be ``bang bang picture perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Only P.J. Axelsson solved the riddle of Hasek. He simply whacked
a shot off a Buffalo player and under Hasek's legs in the final
period of a 4-1 defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't shoot, you're not going to score,'' Axelsson
said. ``You have to get some traffic in front of him and tip the
puck or get a rebound. You just have to get it on net because he's
an awesome goalie.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns approved of the Bruins' ``basic hockey'' of the final two
periods. But even that might not have been enough to overcome
Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't do it in the first period,'' Don Sweeney said. ``And
they capitalized on our mistakes. For the last two days, the
coaches have been telling us what to expect but we failed to go out
and do what we needed to do. We are disappointed in ourselves and
we'd better be motivated from this because we have a tough streak
coming up and we have to get back to the things that caused us to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins performed poorly in the first period, losing
concentration and surrendering possession easily. They had several
scoring chances in the second period but again were victims of
Hasek's gymnastics and whatever other tricks he has up his sleeve
or hidden in his pads.
</P>
<P>
   This was another Hasek highlight show. He ended up in all sorts
of strange positions while frustrating the Bruins. The most unusual
was a stop of Samsonov while in a sit-up position just outside the
crease late in the second period. After making the save, Hasek
appeared to improvise a half sit-up just to show he could do it
while keeping some sort of invisible barrier in front of the
Buffalo net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone talks about how great Dominik Hasek is,'' Bruins
goalie Byron Dafoe said. ``I looked forward to the match against
the best in the world, and we matched up pretty well. But it's
tough to go down 1-0 right off the bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was his usual self. In the second period we threw
everything at him, and he did what he's done his whole career. He
has an advantage right off the bat, and he's earned it. When you
are playing Buffalo, guys automatically think about Dominik Hasek
and he can be intimidating because of what he can do. I've seen
highlights where he goes down and guys miss the net, but you just
have to realize he is human.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek might well be a generic member of the species, but he is
proving that all goaltenders are not created equal.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the contest, the Bruins had textbook attacks. They
waited for Hasek to go to the ice, then attempted to lift the shot
over him. They screened him, sent shots in, waited for rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   But when the time came to convert, shots would go straight to
Hasek's glove like a magnet. When the Bruins awaited rebounds, the
puck stayed on Hasek like Velcro. Sometimes, Hasek seemed to just
wave his stick at shots and they would glide past the post.
</P>
<P>
   Axelsson proved that the unexpected move is the best way to go,
though it is doubtful the Bruins could have quadruplicated his shot
off a Sabre's skate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to come out and do better than that in the first
period,'' Axelsson said. ``We know we have to work for goals. And
you can't let Buffalo score three goals because it's tough to get
back. We'll have to be more ready for the next game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
