</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-NORTHDAKOTA-BENTLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENTLEY ONLY DOES HALF JOB, FAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ Bentley College used man-to-man defense
Saturday night against North Dakota State even though coach Barbara
Stevens considered going to a zone. No matter what alignment
Bentley chose, it might not have made much difference, as nearly
everything North Dakota State fired up went in.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 3-ranked Bison connected on 60 percent of their shots
(33 of 55) even though they made only two of their first seven
field goal attempts. North Dakota State's field goal percentage was
the best ever against Bentley as the Bison took a 98-70 win.
</P>
<P>
   The game was tied at 43 at halftime, then Bison outscored
Bentley, 55-27, in the second half before 1,800 at the Dana Center.
Bentley is no slouch, either, ranked No. 4 in the country at 9-2
entering the game.
</P>
<P>
   North Dakota State (9-0) made 31 of its last 48 shots, a 64.6
percent clip. And the Bison cashed in on 11 of 15 3-point tries
(73.3 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Fuller had 16 points for Bentley, which shot 41.8 percent
(23 of 55), with Jen Pemberton adding 15. Jayne Even had 20 for
North Dakota State and Amanda Gehrke 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stonehill played a matchup zone against North Dakota State and
held them to 36 percent on 3-pointers,'' Stevens said. ``Maybe we
were stubborn in not going to a zone, but I felt that would have
sealed our fate. We were more aggressive early, but then, when we
missed a couple of shots, they started to shoot well, and that put
the damper on us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disappointed with our defensive effort. We lost our
enthusiasm. You have to make sure to be able to weather some
storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little up-and-down now. In the past we were able to
handle these types of things, but then our team was looking around,
wondering where the next bullets would come from, and North Dakota
State was standing behind the 3-point line.''
</P>
<P>
   Bentley was ahead, 15-5, with 14:11 left in the first half, on a
fast-break layup by Pemberton. The Falcons had their largest lead,
14 points (19-5, with 12:45 left), when Pemberton made a layup.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was our hope that we would do that, get out to a quick
lead,'' said Stevens. ``We did it with a lot of transition baskets
and by getting the ball inside to Fuller.''
</P>
<P>
   Then North Dakota State got it to 9 points, 30-21, on a basket
by Brenna Stefonowicz, with 8:14 left. It was at 4, 41-37, with
2:35 left on a Theresa Lang 3-pointer. It was all even at 41 when
North Dakota State's Kiauna Burns canned a jumper from the foul
line with 1:10 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bentley was more aggressive and it had a nonstop defense, and
then late in the second half we were more aggressive with the ball,
always looking to drive,'' said North Dakota State coach Amy Ruley,
who has had five national champions (1991, '93, '94, '95, and '96).
</P>
<P>
   North Dakota State went up by 10, 56-46, when Jayne Boeddeker
hit from the paint. It was 69-54 when Anna Bogstad scored with 8:15
remaining. And it was 75-55 with 6:43 remaining when Burns canned
two free throws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
