<SLUG> BC-BOX-GATTI-ROBINSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON SURVIVES ACTION-FILLER SEQUEL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY _ A fight was scheduled Saturday night at the Mark
Etess Center and nuclear warfare broke out.
</P>
<P>
   For 10 rounds, lightweights Arturo Gatti and Ivan Robinson took
harsh measure of each other. Round after round, the Philly fighter,
Robinson, strafed the Jersey guy, Gatti, ripping open the left side
of his face but often paying a heavy price as Gatti doubled him
over with two-sided body attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Few men in boxing could have taken the punishment Gatti
absorbed. Fewer still would have stood up to the pounding to the
liver and ribs Robinson swallowed.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Gatti's face would suffer the more obvious damage,
but he would lose not from the blood on his face but from the
ferocity of his body attack, an attack that eventually compelled
referee Benji Estevez to deduct a point in the eighth round after
two warnings for low blows.
</P>
<P>
   That point would be the difference as Robinson won a unanimous
decision with judges Joe Pasquale and George Colon scoring the
bout, 95-94, while Jean Williams somehow had it a lopsided 97-92.
The Globe card had Gatti a 95-94 winner. Had the point deduction
not been made, the fight would have been a draw, which might well
have been the most fitting end to a rematch that did what few
thought possible _ produced more fireworks than the first meeting
Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't take nothing away from Arturo,'' Robinson (27-2)
said. ``He's a tough guy. He was a lot better than the first fight.
He was moving his head a lot. I couldn't hit him as much.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not, but he hit him plenty and a man can take only so
much. In the two fights, Gatti was struck in the face 840 times. No
one's head was made to take such abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Barely 90 seconds into the first round it was obvious Gatti's
talk of boxing more and avoiding hand-to-hand combat had been
forgotten in a hail of Robinson punches that left Gatti's left
cheek swelling and his battle plan in tatters.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly reverting to the toe-to-toe warrior he has always been,
Gatti began winging punches and Robinson answered again and again
as the crowd roared. Nothing changed early on but the shape of
Gatti's face and by the final seconds of the third round his left
eye was cut, blood was smeared across his face, and Robinson was
bombing him with both hands.
</P>
<P>
   Gatti was now a young man turning old in the middle of the ring
and Robinson's constant jab and following combinations were
accelerating the aging process. But by the fifth round, Gatti went
after Robinson's body and got it, paying the price of having his
left cheek and eye opened up like an overripe plum as a cost of
doing that dreaded business.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gatti continued to land to the body while Robinson
returned fire to the head and in the seventh round they exchanged
furious barrages. Gatti nailed Robinson with more than half (41) of
his 75 punches but still was outhit 2-1 (77 of 117).
</P>
<P>
   After two warnings for low blows, Gatti finally had the fatal
point deducted in the eighth but battled on, ripping at Robinson's
body and trying to find his chin until the bell sounded to begin
the final round. When it did, the two warriors walked to the center
of the ring and looked at each other for several seconds before
each leaned forward and touched foreheads.
</P>
<P>
   The real issue had been decided right there. Each had won what
they had come for, the other's respect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
