r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-THEATER-MANIA-2tak     12-13 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-THEATER-MANIA-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPSCALE CINEMAS POPPING UP LIKE CORN IN L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The war for the wallets of moviegoers in L.A.'s
San Fernando Valley goes ballistic this week.
</P>
<P>
   Two lavishly furnished and elaborately named new complexes _ the
six-screen Edwards Grand Palace Stadium Cinemas in Calabasas and
the Northridge Fashion Center All Stadium 10 _ will open Friday and
add more than 4,000 seats to the region's inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Both possess all the bells and whistles of new theaters with
colorful entrances, high-back ``love seats,'' steep aisles for
clear sightlines, wall-to-wall screens, massive snack bars and
digital sound. ``State-of-the-art everything'' brags the
promotional material for the Edwards facility.
</P>
<P>
   More impressively, both have been designed as key attractions
within upscale retail centers as developers nationwide scramble to
offer shopping and entertainment in the same location. The frenzy
to open shiny new facilities reached the Santa Clarita Valley,
where Edwards opened the Edwards Canyon Country Stadium 10 on Nov.
13.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, four more state-of-the-art complexes are coming to
the region in Valencia, Sherman Oaks, Burbank and Glendale. That's
an impressive turnaround from just a few years ago, when developers
shunned movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When malls were the hottest development going, they used to
shy away from incorporating theaters because they were perceived as
attracting juvenile delinquents at night and required a great deal
of parking,'' said Gordon Hodge, an analyst with Nationsbanc
Montgomery Securities. ``Now, it's become clear that anything that
brings in significant amounts of traffic is really appreciated, so
you're seeing retail developments with the theaters as the
anchor.''
</P>
<P>
   Up until a few years ago, many analysts believed the movie
exhibition business was headed the way of eight-track tapes. But
the business began reinventing itself in 1995 when AMC
Entertainment opened the nation's first ``megaplex,'' the 24-screen
Grand in Dallas, followed by eight more megaplexes in the next
year, including the Promenade 16 in Woodland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was simple _ offer moviegoers more bang for the buck by
giving them the option of multiple start times, enough concession
space to avoid long waits in line and put them in locations where
customers will have something to do before and after the film
rather than having to spend the evening in the car.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of blending moviegoing, shopping and eating in a single
location has now become a staple of retail development.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inclusion of movie theaters in any new development helps
ensure that project's success due to the additional generation of
customers,'' said Bill Boyd, senior vice president at commercial
broker Grubb &AMP; Ellis and a veteran in Valley real estate. ``Having
theaters extends the hours of a retail environment because they
keep more people at the location longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Affiliating with a retail development is as beneficial for the
retailers and restaurants as it is for operator of the movie
theaters _ they both enhance each other's success.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimated AMC's cash return on its investment topped
40percent during the first year of operation of megaplexes, an
impressive figure that enabled the chain to open even more
megaplexes.
</P>
<P>
   From AMC's success, analysts began to notice four key trends:
</P>
<P>
   _ Customers became more likely to show up outside new theaters
and then decide what movie to see.
</P>
<P>
   _ Customers began driving past older theaters to go to the new
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Snack-bar sales, the key profit component in the exhibition
business, were significantly higher at the new facilities.
</P>
<P>
   _ Older theaters began to resort to discounting just to keep
customers coming.
</P>
<P>
   Rivals like Edwards, Regal, Cineplex Odeon and Pacific began
shifting their strategy to opening new facilities in locations that
were ``underserved'' and started to replace older theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The Promenade 16 in Woodland Hills had been such a success that
Pacific opened one of the largest theaters in the country _ the
6,000-seat Winnetka 20 _ less than five miles away on a former
drive-in site. Ten months later, Pacific is opening a theater at
Northridge that's about a mile from the Winnetka 20.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler Wood, executive vice president and head film buyer for
Pacific, insists the move makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, the 6,000 seats at Winnetka are not
enough,'' Wood said. ``It's consistently in the top 10 grossers in
the country and has exceeded our expectations by a lot more than
anticipated. We're currently averaging 20 to 25 sellouts during the
weekend so we're turning people away.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Northridge theater, which will feature a three-story
lobby, half a dozen palm trees out front and a snack bar counter
more than 100 feet long, is part of a revamp of the mall's
northwest corner that will add 175,000 leasable square feet on
three levels by this summer. A Borders book store and Claim Jumper
restaurant already have opened; Ben &AMP; Jerry's and Juice Heaven have
agreed to open stores as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theater was part of the entire package to develop an
open-air atmosphere with entertainment, restaurants and retail,''
said Carol Jacobs, general manager of the Northridge Fashion
Center. ``We will definitely not have a problem finding tenants.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   As for the Edwards Grand Palace in Calabasas, it will open in
the geographic slot between four Woodland Hills theaters with 35
screens on the east and a pair of 2-year-old Mann eight-plexes in
Westlake Village and Agoura Hills to the west.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demographics in the area are very good,'' said Mark
Stoner, director of real estate for the Edwards chain. ``People
have good incomes and there are a lot of families. We like the
whole area and felt it was under-screened.''
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Palace will sit amid pricey stores like Gary's Island
and Cold Stone Creamery and will be nearly the final tenant to open
at The Commons shopping center, where most facilities debuted last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a beautiful upscale project that has the feel of a
French country villa,'' Stoner said. ``The city and the developer
limited us to six screens with 1,300 seats. If they had allowed us
to do a bigger theater, we probably would have.''
</P>
<P>
   Plenty more new theaters are coming, led by Pacific's 18-screen
replacement of its five-screen complex at the legendary Sherman
Oaks Galleria. Pacific will shut the site in February and install
4,000 stadium seats in its revamp.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards will open a 12-screen facility next spring in Valencia
with the added attraction of an adjacent Imax giant-screen.
Analysts say developers are increasingly considering the inclusion
of an Imax at movie complexes as a way of differentiating
themselves from rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Other new theaters in the region include a seven-screen Laemmle
in Pasadena, which will show art-house movies when it opens early
next year; an Imax at Universal Studios as part of an extensive
remodeling of its 18-screen Cineplex Odeon; a nine- to 12-screen
complex at a proposed Town Center development in Glendale; and the
addition of retail centers and a dozen new screens each to the
venerable Mann Chinese and Pacific Cinerama Dome sites in
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Hodge said the new-theater boom, which has been boosting the
nation's screen count by 7percent annually, should continue for the
foreseeable future. And he does not anticipate the market becoming
glutted with new theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it the retreading of the circuits,'' he said. ``They're
shutting down antiquated facilities as leases expire and replacing
them. There are still plenty of new 20-screen megaplexes that make
good investment sense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
