<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX MAKE PLAY FOR PADRES' HAMILTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette swung into
action almost immediately after arriving at baseball's winter
meetings late Saturday afternoon, offering a three-player package
for San Diego pitcher Joey Hamilton, according to an American
League executive.
</P>
<P>
   But indications Saturday night were that Hamilton is more likely
bound for AL East rival Toronto, which is looking to replace the
soon-to-be-departed Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette proposed sending pitcher John Wasdin, center fielder
Michael Coleman, and minor league lefthander Robert Ramsay to the
Padres, reeling Saturday from the loss of ace Kevin Brown to the
Los Angeles Dodgers. But the Blue Jays, according to the same
source, were offering pitcher Woody Williams, 25-year-old rookie
pitcher Carlos Almanzar, and another minor leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, 28, has won 40 games in the last three seasons for the
Padres, who may be in a rebuilding mode after losing free agents
Brown, Ken Caminiti, and Steve Finley.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton was awarded $3.25 million in salary arbitration last
season and can expect to climb to the $5 million range next season.
</P>
<P>
   Having lost Mo Vaughn and failing to sign Bernie Williams, money
is no object for the Red Sox, and Duquette has said he would prefer
to trade prospects rather than players on his big-league roster.
Duquette acknowledged Saturday that he talked to the Padres, but
did not go into detail.
</P>
<P>
   There was some thought that the Sox would inquire again about
San Diego outfielder Greg Vaughn, who hit 50 home runs last season,
but as of Saturday night that had not occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn is in the final year of a three-year, $14.865 million
deal under which he is due to be paid $5.75 million in 1999. Vaughn
is 33 and the Padres have Ruben Rivera waiting in the wings to
replace him.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who hits righthanded, would give the Red Sox a
legitimate cleanup hitter with Nomar Garciaparra a logical
candidate to assume Mo Vaughn's No. 3 spot in the order. The Red
Sox would still be short a lefthanded hitter, but that could be
addressed by the addition of a first baseman _ switch-hitting free
agent Greg Jefferies, perhaps, or Ryan Klesko of the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko is also being pursued by the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
Duquette said he has not yet talked to the Braves, but Atlanta is
willing to move the 28-year-old slugger, who is an adequate first
baseman.
</P>
<P>
   There were indications Saturday night that free agent pitcher
Tim Belcher could sign as early as Sunday. Belcher was on the verge
of signing a three-year, $16.5 million deal, and Duquette did not
rule the Red Sox out of the running. ``We've had an interest
there,'' he said. The Angels, who lost out in the Brown derby, are
a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Agent Scott Boras, who engineered the Brown signing, said the
Red Sox were still in the Belcher mix and that he intended to again
speak with Duquette. He confirmed that he has a three-year offer
for Belcher, but would not identify from whom, saying only there
were three or four teams in contention.
</P>
<P>
   According to officials with other clubs, the Sox have an
interest in 33-year-old Charlie Hayes, a third baseman by trade who
played 45 games at first base for the Giants last season. The
Giants picked up a $1.7 million option on Hayes, who filled in
nicely at first when J.T. Snow was hurt and also was used in a
platoon situation, but with Bill Mueller also available to play
third, Hayes could be expendable.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said he did not meet Saturday with the Seattle
Mariners, but there were rumors that in addition to first baseman
David Segui, the Sox could have interest in Russ Davis, who made 32
errors at third base last season before being moved to left field.
Davis, 29, has hit 20 home runs in each of the last two seasons for
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get some things done here,'' Duquette said. ``I don't
know how significant they'll be, but we'll get a few things done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
