<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILES-WASHINGTON-REAX14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton, Congress react to Lawton Chiles death
 &HT;    By Larry Lipman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ News of Gov. Lawton Chiles' death brought the House
Judiciary Committee's impeachment proceedings to a halt Saturday
afternoon and momentarily united its bitterly divided members,
including three from Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Chiles' death was announced to the committee by Rep. Robert
Wexler, a Democrat from Boca Raton, Fla., who called Chiles ``the
epitome of a fine and decent man, a throwback to the age when
partisanship didn't play the role it plays (now) ... this man rose
above party.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida's two Republican members on the committee, Bill McCollum
of Longwood and Charles Canaday of Lakeland, joined in praising
Chiles before the committee observed a minute of silence in his
memory.
</P>
<P>
   McCollum recalled spending a day with Chiles in Central Florida
last year in the aftermath of killer tornadoes that ripped through
the area and ``the great compassion he showed.''
</P>
<P>
   Canaday, whose father was Chiles' campaign manager during his
first Senate campaign in 1970, called him ``a good man. He was a
dedicated public servant. I didn't agree with him politically in
recent years, but I had the utmost respect for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Official Washington quickly reacted with words of praise for
Chiles, who spent 18 years as a senator.
</P>
<P>
   The White House issued a statement from President Clinton, on
the first day of his trip to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawton Chiles was a close friend of mine for many years,''
said Clinton, who twice invited Chiles to stay overnight at the
White House and watched two Superbowl games together. Earlier this
year, only days after the Monica Lewinsky scandal surfaced, Chiles
was Hillary Rodham Clinton's guest during this year's State of the
Union address.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called Chiles an ``indefatigable champion of Florida's
children and familes and a steadfast protector of the environment.
He displayed courage time and time again, most recently challenging
the nation's top cigarette makers and emerging victorious.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, a Floridian, said Chiles ``put
principle above partisanship and reason above rancor. He fought for
the uninsured, for infants, for the elderly and for minorities. His
legacy is long and his impact great. He was a great senator, great
governor, great Floridian and a wonderful friend. I will miss him
dearly.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., a Republican from Fort Lauderdale, Fla.,
was vacationing in Alabama. He said he was shocked to learn of
Chiles' death while watching the impeachment debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a close friend to all of us in Congress, both
Republicans and Democrats. ... I certainly was looking ahead to see
what his next career would be,'' Shaw said, noting that Chiles had
been a senator and governor. ``It's going to be a great loss as a
friend as well as a public servant.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mark Foley, a Republican from West Palm Beach, Fla., called
Chiles ``one of the legendary figures who will be remembered long
after his demise.'' Foley said Chiles cared about the people who
would would never be able to vote for him, children and the
disenfranchised.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Senator Connie Mack said he was saddened by Chiles'
death and paid tribute to Chiles' 40 years in public service.
``Through his service in the state Legislature, U.S. Senate and as
Florida's governor, Lawton Chiles touched the lives of many people.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
