<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7274 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILES-OBIT14-COX     12-13 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILES-OBIT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida Gov. Lawton Chiles dies at mansion
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Gov. Lawton Chiles, the ``Old He-Coon'' who
masterminded the state's $11 billion tobacco victory and spent his
political capital to buy children's health, died Saturday of an
apparent heart attack at 68.
</P>
<P>
   There were 24 days left in the job he said he liked the most.
Despite numerous job overtures, he still said he planned to retire
after a 40-year career in which he never lost an election for the
state Legislature, the U.S. Senate and finally, Florida governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This week he was concerned about getting up in the morning and
not having anything to do and not having anyplace to go,'' said
longtime confidant Mallory Horne, a hunting and fishing buddy. ``It
was almost a prophecy.''
</P>
<P>
   The man who earned the name ``Walkin' Lawton'' for a campaign
walk across the state, died during a daily workout at the
Governor's Mansion. An FDLE agent found his body shortly after 4
p.m. lying next to some exercise equipment. Chiles could not be
revived and was pronounced dead by emergency crews.
</P>
<P>
   He was to have attended a midafternoon reception at the mansion
for Florida Department of Law Enforcement agents and state aircraft
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Buddy MacKay was flown back from a stay in
Massachusetts on Saturday evening to be sworn in as governor.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, impeachment hearings came a temporary halt late
Saturday afternoon for a moment of silence. And from Jerusalem,
President Clinton issued a statement calling Chiles ``a statesman,
a role model, and one of the most respected public officials in the
latter half of the Twentieth Century.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov.-elect Jeb Bush, told of the news in Miami, remembered
something Chiles had once said: ``I didn't come here to stay. I
come to make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has made a difference and his mark on history is as deep as
his commitment and love for the people of Florida,'' Bush said.
``Our state has lost a legend who always stood up for those in
need, and who leaves a legacy of unequaled compassion for Florida's
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Scores of friends, aides and reporters gathered outside the
ante-bellum style Governor's Mansion, where white Christmas lights
twinkled incongruously amid the ivy-covered iron fence and from
holly wreaths decorating the second-floor balconies. Above the
portico, three flags _ the United States Flag, the flag from when
Florida joined the Union, and the Florida state flag _ all flew at
half mast.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart is with him,'' said Harold Lewis, a 45-year political
buddy from Lake Worth who Chiles reluctantly had to let go from his
administration last year because of questionable loans Lewis
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   In silence, they watched a hearse carrying Chiles' body as it
left the Governor's Mansion and turned onto Adams Street to be
taken to Tallahassee Memorial Hospital. Lewis saluted.
</P>
<P>
   Former Chiles general counsel Dexter Douglass and current
general counsel Dan Stengle shared a tearful embrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still alive,'' said Douglass, who helped Chiles win a $13
billion lawsuit against the tobacco industry. ``In all the
children, in clean government. All those things are still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's wife, Rhea Chiles, grieved privately inside the
Tallahassee mansion where the couple had lived for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's shocked but I think she's going to be OK,'' Stengle
said.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral arrangements will be announced later, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Chiles is the third Florida governor to die in office and the
first since Dan T. McCarty on Sept. 28, 1953.
</P>
<P>
   Chiles' death stunned friends who had seen him overcome numerous
health problems: depression (treated with Prozac), vision problems
(corrected by surgery) and a stroke-like attack. He had come back
fit and ready for political battle time each time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept himself in good shape,'' said state Sen. Tom Rossin
(D-West Palm Beach), who said Chiles had played tennis at his home
while a U.S. Senator. ``The fact he died next to exercise equipment
shows the kind of discipline he had.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiles had an easy-going manner but he proved a fierce political
adversary. He once called the state's lawsuit against the tobacco
industry for health care costs ``the best fight I've ever gotten
into.'' It produced $13 billion for the state over the next 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said, ``He displayed courage time and time
again, most recently challenging the nation's top cigarette
manufacturers and emerging victorious.''
</P>
<P>
   His fight to improve children's health is also a large part of
his legacy. Florida's infant mortality dropped 34 percent during
his tenure, which led the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida's children have lost their most powerful advocate,''
said Jack Levine, executive director of the Florida Center for
Children and Youth. ``He not only was responsible for millions of
children in this nation being healthier, but he was directly
responsible for thousands of child advocates with his inspiration,
his charisma and his character.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine and others had planned a Valentine's Day tribute to say
thanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts so much to not say those things to his face and now
say them to his memory,'' Levine said, his voice breaking. ``I know
he knew, but we needed to say it just one more time.''
</P>
<P>
   The news stopped impeachment hearings in Washington, where
Chiles was a Senator for 18 years. Rep. Robert Wexler (D-Boca
Raton) broke into the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have just been informed ... that our finest public servant,
Gov. Lawton Chiles, has died,'' Wexler said.
</P>
<P>
   Chiles was ``a throwback to the age when partisanship doesn't
play the role it plays'' and the ``embodiment of what's good about
America,'' Wexler said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill McCollum (R-Orlando) said he remembered the care and
attention Chiles took in touring storm damage earlier this year in
McCollum's district.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a good man and a good governor of Florida,''
McCollum said.
</P>
<P>
   The committee observed a moment of silence for Chiles before the
hearing resumed.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, even Chiles' fiercest political adversaries paid
tribute. Tom Slade, chairman of the Republican Party of Florida,
led the GOP effort to take control of the state Legislative but
could never beat Chiles. Slade called him ``a man who defined
public service.''
</P>
<P>
   They served in the state Legislature together in the 1960s and
once made up two-thirds of a sailing crew on a trip to the Bahamas
that Slade recalled fondly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawton, it was great walkin' with you,'' Slade said.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker John Thrasher (R-Orange Park) said ``the state has
lost a great man today, one who can never be replaced.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved being governor,'' said Stengle, Chiles' general
counsel. ``He loved it every day. It was his highest privilege of
his 40-year career to be governor of this state that he loved so
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
