</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILES-TIMELINE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chiles' political career
 &HT;    By Lynne Palombo and Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   1958 - A 28-year-old lawyer in Lakeland and a newcomer to
politics, Chiles runs for the state House against 10-year incumbent
Roy Surles. Knocking on every door in Polk County, Chiles beats the
odds and wins.
</P>
<P>
   1959 - Chiles rebels against the Pork Choppers, rural lawmakers
who divided the state spoils for themselves. Chiles would spend the
next seven years in the House fighting for open government.
</P>
<P>
   1966 - Wins a seat in the state Senate. Pushes laws requiring
lobbyists to register and forcing the Senate to meet in public.
Helps write the 1968 Constitution, which remains in place today.
</P>
<P>
   1970 - If walking his house district won him his first election,
Chiles reasons, maybe walking the entire state will win him a U.S.
Senate seat. He is challenged by ex-governor Farris Bryant and
Alcee Hastings of Fort Lauderdale and Joel Daves of West Palm
Beach. Voters love it; He defeats the favored Bryant in a runoff
after walking 1,003 miles.
</P>
<P>
   1971 - ``Walkin' Lawton'' is sworn in, beginning 18 years as a
U.S. Senator.
</P>
<P>
   1972 - Introduces measure requiring most government agencies _
including Congress _ to open most meetings and records. Measure
passes in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   1976 - As chairman of governmental affairs subcommittee, Chiles
expose abuses in military meat-buying and in federal furniture
purchases, getting more than 150 convictions.
</P>
<P>
   1982 - Successfully challenges Reagan administration cuts that
would have cost Florida $354 million for Coast Guard equipment and
operations.
</P>
<P>
   1985 - Admitted to Bethesda Naval Hospital for tests after
physican says Chiles has high blood pressure. Undergoes quadruple
bypass heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   1987 - Named chairman of the Budget Committee.
</P>
<P>
   1989 - Retires from Senate and becomes director of the Collins
Center, a public policy institution affiliated with the University
of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   1990 - Former U.S. Rep. Buddy MacKay persuades Chiles to run for
governor. Defeats incumbent GOP Gov. Bob Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   1991 - Pushed through creation of the Department of Elder
Affairs. Reached pact to end 19-year federal suit against the
prison system over prison conditions. Settles Everglades lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   1992 - Hurricane Andrew causes $30 billion in damages; Chiles
spends six weeks in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   1993 - Proposes cigarette tax to pay for new prison beds.
Establishes network of health care insurance alliances to help
small businesses and individuals.
</P>
<P>
   1994 - In a showdown with the Clinton administration over new
waves of Cuban exiles, he places National Guard on alert and
persuades administration to intercept refugees at sea. Stealthily
passes bill to make it easier for the state to sue tobacco, setting
off a wave of lawsuits against tobacco companies throughout the
nation. Wins reelection in one of the closest races in state
history. He becomes not only ``Walkin'' Lawton but the ``He-coon.''
</P>
<P>
   1995 - Sues cigarette makers despite overwhelming pressure from
lobbyists. Suffers a minor stroke-like attack caused by dehydration
during a fishing trip and is hospitalized for three days.
</P>
<P>
   1996 - Chiles defeats attempt to repeal legislation that allowed
tobacco suits. Forms a new Department of Children and Families
after dismantling the troubled Department of Health and
Rehabilitative Services.
</P>
<P>
   1997 - Settles landmark lawsuit against the tobacco industry for
$11 billion; amount later rises to $13 billion. Worried about
school crowding, Chiles forces the legislature into special session
to pay for more schools.
</P>
<P>
   1998 - Wins passage of legislation expanding health insurance
coverage to 256,000 children through federal money and tobacco
settlement cash. In his last act as governor, Chiles appoints Peggy
Ann Quince, the first black woman to the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
