<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7276 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-HISTORY14-COX     12-13 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HISTORY14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Andrew Johnson impeachment trial also partisan, Emory professor
says
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Senate Republicans believed they had the votes to doom
Andrew Johnson's presidency after his 1868 impeachment trial, the
only one in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   But Edmund Ross of Kansas shocked, dismayed and incensed his GOP
colleagues by voting against Johnson's impeachment, which failed 35
to 19 _ one vote shy of the two-thirds majority needed to remove a
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a man who despised Johnson and believed he was
absolutely wrong but concluded his obligation under the
Constitution rose above his hatred toward Johnson,'' Emory
University history professor Dan Carter said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ross was ruined politically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lesson a lot of moderate Republicans are probably
looking at right now,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, the prize-winning biographer of George Wallace and an
expert on Reconstruction, said there are more differences than
similarities between Johnson's impeachment trial of 1868 and the
travails of President Clinton today.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a Tennessee Democrat, was Abraham Lincoln's vice
president. He became the nation's 17th president when Lincoln was
assassinated on April 14, 1865.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson drew the ire of Republicans when he said Southern states
could be readmitted to the Union with little federal oversight.
</P>
<P>
   When Southern states failed to grant rights to newly emancipated
slaves, Congress exerted military control over the South. But
Johnson removed Edwin Stanton, secretary of war, without notifying
the Senate. The move was a repudiation of the Tenure of Office Act,
a law designed to prevent Johnson from firing appointees. For this
reason, the House voted 126-47 in support of articles of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnson was terribly wrong in terms of his politics,'' Carter
said. ``The Republicans were right. Something had to be done. Had
it not and had it been left up to Andrew Johnson, we wouldn't have
the 14th and 15th amendments to the Constitution,'' which granted
equal protection and voting rights to African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But the essence of the impeachment charges against Johnson came
down to his challenge of the constitutionality of the Tenure Of
Office Act. ``That's not the kind of issue that should have risen
to the level of an impeachment offense,'' Carter said. ``It's
something that should have been settled by the U.S. Supreme Court,
which did, in fact, later declare the act unconstitutonal.''
</P>
<P>
   The fundamental parallel between today's impeachment proceedings
and those of 1868 is that partisan politics is playing a big role,
Carter said. ``In both cases, you have a handful of swing votes in
the middle and both are called moderate Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   What few people recall, Carter said, is that the House voted
80-27 to condemn Johnson _ much like a censure _ before it moved to
impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 6, 1868, the House passed a resolution saying the House
``utterly condemns the conduct of Andrew Johnson'' for transferring
the ``gallant'' Gen. P.H. Sheridan from his duties in the South.
Sheridan had used aggressive military tactics to put down
disturbances in the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever raised the question back then of whether that was
constitutional,'' Carter noted. ``They just passed a resolution of
condemnation, or censure.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, unlike Clinton, never admitted he had done anything
wrong. The story goes, Carter said, that Johnson was having a
meeting when handed a vote that the Senate had failed by one vote
to impeach him. Johnson calmly read the message and then, without
changing expression, went on with his conversation.
</P>
<P>
   The issues at stake during the Johnson presidency were much
graver than those of today, said Carter, who describes himself as
no defender of Clinton's. ``With Johnson, the issues involved
fundamental questions on human rights and liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton, the arguments about perjury and obstruction are
serious, Carter said. ``But it's still fundamentally about private
consensual sexual acts.... To compare that to the fundamental
questions of impeachment during the Johnson trial really just
boggles the mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
