<DOCNO> NYT19981213.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7277 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MACKAY-INTERIM14-COX     12-13 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACKAY-INTERIM14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MacKay sworn as interim governor
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Under possibly the worst circumstances
imaginable, Buddy MacKay is finally the governor of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Not six weeks after Floridians handed him his third and likely
final defeat in a statewide election and with just 24 days left
until the man who beat him takes over, Kenneth Hood MacKay Jr.
becomes Florida's 42nd governor upon the sudden death of his
friend, Lawton Chiles.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay, 65, was in Cambridge, Mass., Saturday when Chiles'
staffers tracked him down with the news. He returned to Florida
immediately, and general counsel Dan Stengle arranged a hasty
swearing in _ a formality, he said, because the state Constitution
automatically makes the lieutenant governor the new chief executive
upon a governor's death.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a natural disaster, however, there is little governing
left for MacKay to do between now and Gov.-elect Jeb Bush's
inauguration on Jan. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's team is responsible for preparing the next year's budget.
The last Cabinet meeting of the year was last week. And Chiles
filled two Supreme Court openings _ one by himself, one in
consultation with Bush _ also last week.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay had not yet shared publicly his plans after Bush's
inauguration. He and his wife, Anne, own a small house in a quiet,
downtown Tallahassee neighborhood, but still consider Ocala their
home. Now, however, those plans most go on hold so MacKay can add
``caretaker governor'' to the list of offices he has held in nearly
three decades in public life.
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1953 has a governor died in office, and not since 1987
_ when Gov. Bob Graham resigned three days early to take his oath
for the U.S. Senate _ has a lieutenant governor stepped in for his
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's lieutenant, Wayne Mixson, though, served a term like
most second-in-commands in Florida history: notable only for their
near invisibility. For eight years, MacKay has been anything but.
</P>
<P>
   Chiles' thorniest, politically least savory tasks _
restructuring Florida's troubled welfare agency; overseeing the
financial reorganization of Miami _ often fell to MacKay to manage.
Insiders call him a ``policy wonk,'' a manager able and willing to
dig his hands into the messy innards of a problem _ quite the
opposite of Chiles' style of absorbing the big picture but
delegating the details.
</P>
<P>
   Outwardly, MacKay resembles his friend and predecessor: both
Florida natives, both University of Florida-trained lawyers, both
elderly, both silver haired, both thin and trim from regular
physical exercise.
</P>
<P>
   But the similarities end there. While Chiles was able to fire
off homespun witticisms (``The old he-coon walks just before the
light of day''), MacKay in public is wooden, often unable to convey
the passion he nevertheless feels.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, MacKay shared Chiles' fiscal conservatism, but
parted ways on social issues such as abortion and school prayer.
Despite his Old Florida roots in Ocala, MacKay has held
traditionally liberal views on everything from race relations _ he
helped found his own Presbyterian church when the one he grew up in
would not accept blacks _ to gay rights. Although born to a citrus
farming family, MacKay is an ardent environmentalist.
</P>
<P>
   But without MacKay, Chiles might never have been governor.
</P>
<P>
   It was MacKay who, having fallen a few votes short in his
attempt to succeed Chiles in the U.S. Senate in 1988, barely a year
later talked his friend out of his depression and his retirement to
return to public life as Florida's 41st governor.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two years, MacKay again tried to succeed Chiles,
and, last month, again failed.
</P>
<P>
   And so, after 12 years in the Florida Legislature, six years in
the U.S. House of Representatives and seven years and 341 days as
Florida's lieutenant governor, MacKay will once more serve the
state, this time for three and a half weeks in a job voters
overwhelmingly decided not to give him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say your prayers for Buddy MacKay,'' Chiles confidant Dexter
Douglass said, empathizing with the emotional task the next three
weeks will present. ``He just suffered a terrible loss tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
