<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7279 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-BANKS14-COX     12-13 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-BANKS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Local banks, thrifts say they'll be ready for Y2K
 &HT;    By Danielle Herubin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ For the past 21 months, Fidelity
Federal's Anita Mixon and 13 others have been testing the thrift's
computers to make sure time doesn't leave them behind on Jan. 1,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well at Fidelity Federal and other institutions,
computers will move smoothly into the 21st century; ATMs will
continue to dispense cash, your checks and payments will clear, and
bank and thrift computers will remember who you are, how much is in
your account and, of course, how much you owe.
</P>
<P>
   If not, hang on to your statements and receipts.
</P>
<P>
   The scene at Fidelity Federal is being repeated locally and
throughout the nation as financial institutions work to solve the
so-called Y2K problem. Though it affects all industries, Y2K's most
profound impact could be on banks, thrifts, credit unions _ and
their customers. Financial institutions rely on computers for
nearly everything they do, from processing checks to running ATMs.
If the computers aren't reprogrammed to recognize the new century
on Jan. 1, 2000 . . . well, you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Just how serious the problem could be depends on who is doing
the predicting.
</P>
<P>
   Most think there would be relatively minor inconveniences such
as an ATM that won't work or a credit card buy that won't be
approved. But others fear the nation's financial system _ tied
together by computer connections _ could collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Bank and thrift officials say they'll be ready, but they quickly
add there is a lot more work to be done.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has set a series of dates for
institutions to meet certain goals. By Dec. 31, they must prove
they have tested their internal, critical computer systems. By
March 31, they have to prove that every computer service they use
is Y2K ready. Then by June 30, every institution should have every
computer system tested.
</P>
<P>
   As of early November, nearly 5,800 institutions nationwide were
on schedule, 175 were lagging behind, and eight were showing
unsatisfactory progress, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
reported. The FDIC declined to identify the institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The banks are working very hard through their Y2K programs,
and the progress to date has been very good,'' said Lynn Fox, a
spokeswoman for the Federal Reserve Board of Governors in
Washington, D.C. ``We're optimistic that the majority will be
prepared and ready for the rollover.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Fed is preparing for some type of Y2K-related
problem: It plans to circulate an extra $50 billion in cash late
next year to ensure that paper money won't run short if there is a
run on institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Local institutions, large and small, have invested much time and
many resources in the effort.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank and its Charlotte-based parent, BankAmerica, say the
effort has been enormous. As of last month, about 3,300 employees
were going over 90,000 desktop computers and rewriting 200 million
lines of computer code from nearly 300 different software packages,
looking for any bug that could cause the system to go awry. The
bank, which bought Jacksonville-based Barnett Banks earlier this
year, is spending an estimated $550 million in its search for
glitches.
</P>
<P>
   West Palm Beach-based Fidelity Federal Savings Bank has spent
nearly $800,000 out of a $2.3 million Y2K budget in its search,
said Mixon, the thrift's vice president for information services.
It has turned up a smattering of software that wasn't ready, some
computer forms that wouldn't recognize the new century, and ATM
machines that needed a complete upgrading.
</P>
<P>
   Even Grand Bank of Florida _ which hasn't opened its first
account _ has seven people looking at the problem. William Haines,
who is in charge of Y2K fixes at West Palm Beach-based Grand, said
he has to make sure the bank's new equipment will state accurately
when CDs mature and loans are repaid. ``For a new bank, the burden
is proving that everything you buy . . . is Year 2000 compliant,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   No problem is too small.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Federal investigated its copiers, its fax machines and
its phone systems, and found they were ready, Mixon said. It even
looked at its heating and ventilating system. (They passed, too.)
</P>
<P>
   Fred Martin, president of the recently opened Independent
Community Bank in Tequesta, said forms the bank buys have to be
checked to make sure they aren't preprinted with the ``19'' prefix.
</P>
<P>
   All this work hasn't come without a cost _ already well into the
billions across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   New York-based Citigroup alone will spend about $925 million, it
estimated in a recent report to the government. And Chase Manhattan
plans to spend more than $360 million.
</P>
<P>
   Local institutions are opening their vaults, too. Fort
Pierce-based Harbor Federal Savings Bank estimates it will spend
just less than $1 million. North Palm Beach-based Community Savings
Bank said it is spending $1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is taking a big hit. Grand Bank says it will spend
less than $25,000 by the time its doors open on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Institutions will pass along those costs in higher fees, though
analysts haven't put a price tag on the amount consumers will bear.
But institutions already have been increasing fees to pay for the
Y2K costs and will continue to do so, said Kenneth Thomas, a
banking consultant in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the preparations, institutions also are required by the
government to create fall-back plans.
</P>
<P>
   Community Savings said it will change computer data companies if
they cannot satisfy the thrift that computers will be ready in
time, said Mary Lou Kaminske, senior vice president of operations.
``You make contingency plans,'' she said. ``We want to be able to
service our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   A group of banks in South Florida, including Union Bank in Fort
Lauderdale, is discussing sharing a new computer system to handle
deposits and other daily business transactions should things go
awry, said Grand Bank's Haines. He said his bank is considering
joining the group ``just in case.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Community, Fidelity Federal's Mixon said the thrift is
exploring switching computer companies should it come to that. ``We
have to feel comfortable by Dec. 31 (next year),'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the potential problems, there's no need to panic, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we have power, water and phones, we'll be able to
operate,'' Mixon said.
</P>
<P>
   And if all else fails, she said, bankers could take a lesson
from the past. They could get out their pens and ledgers and do
business by hand.
</P>
<P>
   The way they did on Jan. 1, 1900.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
