<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-BILLFANS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ESCAPING IMPEACHMENT ENEMIES AT HOME, CLINTON FINDS FRIENDS IN
ISRAEL
 &HT;    With MIDEAST IMPEACH and MIDEAST-PEACE.
 &HT;    For use on Monday, Dec. 14
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM Binyamin Blum stood waiting on the street at 1 a.m.
Sunday because he believed President Clinton needed a sign of
support.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year-old Israeli was one of a small group who came in
hopes of catching a brief glimpse of Clinton as his motorcade sped
into his hotel shortly after the president arrived from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the president and we don't want to see him get
impeached. We want to show our support,'' Blum said as he huddled
in the cold next to his American girlfriend. ``If he would run for
(Israeli) prime minister, he would win.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a joke, but it might be right.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is in trouble back home with a Congress considering his
impeachment. On Sunday, the first full day of his 3-day peace
mission, he appeared downcast after a tough closed-door session
with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. Last week, nine
members of the right-wing Israeli cabinet hinted they would have
preferred that Clinton stay away rather than come pressure Israel
to proceed with the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton is overwhelmingly popular with most Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, a Gallup Poll showed that, if they could, more
Israelis would vote for him to be their prime minister than either
Netanyahu or the leader of the opposition, Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's biggest peace group, Peace Now, had planned a laser
light show that would write ``Welcome'' across a field that
Clinton's helicopter would cross on Saturday night. But police
stopped it for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Special for Clinton'ht wing do not agree. Clinton has been a
target of the so-called ``settler movement'' _ those who oppose
pressure from Washington to halt Israeli settlements in Palestinian
territories. They and many other Isrhe peace plan that was signed
in Washington last October after Clinton mediated nine days of
Israeli-Palestinian talks at the Wye River Plantation in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Posters reading ``Clinton go home'' showed up on walls in
Jerusalem just days before he arrived.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hebrew daily newspaper Ma'ariv carried a headline in
English Sunday stating, ``Welcome, Mister President'' and a column
from the paper's editor, Yaacov Erez, stated: ``We all hope, save
for the radical fringes, that Clinton will be able to bridge the
abyss at out feet, exhibit his magic touch in his talks with
(Palestinian leader Yasser) Arafat and Netanyahu, and restore the
hope of peace to our chests.''
</P>
<P>
   One Israeli television station dedicated all-day coverage to
Clinton's visit Sunday. It showed not only his press conference
with Netanyahu, but First Lady Hillary Clinton's visit to a school
and daughter Chelsea Clinton standing amid praying Orthodox Jews at
the Western Wall, sacred in Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   In the flower shop that prepared the white roses and fruit
baskets for Clinton's hotel room, the clerk is trendy 22-year-old
Liz Eliav, who wears black leather pants and supports Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   She thinks Clinton is pushing the peace process too hard in an
effort to compensate for his domestic political problems. But, she
likes him anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has such a charm when he speaks, he has such warmth and
kindness,'' Eliav said. ``When he came here (for Rabin's funeral),
he did it for kindness. It's an honor to the Jewish people.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
