<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Monday, Dec. 14. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-CLINTON (Jerusalem) _ Combative and stone-faced,
President Clinton flatly denied on Sunday that he had committed
perjury, as he reluctantly interrupted his efforts to rescue the
Middle East peace plan to address an impeachment vote he said he
cannot control. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   DIABETES-CHILDREN (New York) _ A look at an alarming new health
trend: the sharp increase in the number of youngsters with Type 2
diabetes, also known as adult-onset diabetes, an incurable and
progressively damaging disease that can cause kidney failure,
blindness and poor circulation, which, in turn, can lead to
amputation. Doctors long believed the disease occurred only during
middle age or later. Although there have not been any national
surveys documenting the rise of this form of diabetes in children,
several small-scale studies have found that such cases have more
than tripled in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-UDALL (Undated) _ Morris Udall, a former U.S. congressman
and Democratic Party presidential candidate, has died at age 76.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ With the full House returning for a vote
on impeachment this week, President Clinton on Sunday rebuffed
Republican calls for him to admit to lying under oath and said
flatly that he had not committed perjury. He deflected calls for
him to step down. ``I have no intention of resigning,'' he said.
``It's never crossed my mind.'' Unable to escape the constitutional
crisis engulfing his presidency, the president fielded questions
about his fate in Jerusalem, where he had flown to try to revive
the Middle East peace process. Back home, leading Republicans said
he could save the nation from an impeachment trial by stepping
down.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-REPUBS (Washington) _ In a surprising shift of political
calculations, many prominent Republicans now say that the party's
march toward impeachment would cause no lasting and political
damage. Republican Governors, state party leaders and strategists
around the country _ many of whom had complained that their party
had badly mishandled the scandal all year long _ said in interviews
that the stakes are far lower than they were in the fall because
there is no looming election. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-REACT (Canton, Ohio) _ Residents talk about impeachment
at the local newstand. By Michael Winerip.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-GIANTS-BRONCOS (East Rutherford, N.J.) _ Giants vs. Broncos.
By Bill Pennington.
</P>
</TEXT>
