u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-UPDATE-HNS &LR;      12-13 0056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-UPDATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  Sunday, December 13, 1998
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Editors: &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
IMPEACH-UPDATE(Washington and Jersusalem) _ A story will move at 9
p.m., CDT, Sunday. By DAVID IVANOVICH and NANCY MATHIS. Questions,
call Jake Doherty at 713-220-7674. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 1811EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981213.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7424 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-IMPEACH     12-13 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-IMPEACH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UNDECIDED REPUBLICANS EDGE TOWARD IMPEACHMENT AFTER CLINTON
AGAIN DENIES LYING
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM President Clinton on Sunday stood hard by his
insistence that he did not commit perjury and asked members of the
House to look to their conscience, their constituents and the
Constitution and choose censure over impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ''Apparently, somewhere around three-quarters of the American
people think that's the right thing to do,'' Clinton said during a
press conference with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   But undecided Republicans indicated they were leaning toward
voting for impeachment after Clinton said again that he didn't lie
under oath.
</P>
<P>
   One, Rep. Bob Ney of Ohio, said Clinton ``hurt himself very
clearly'' with his repeated assertion on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jay Dickey of Arkansas, another undecided Republican who
joined Ney on ABC's ``This Week'' program, said Clinton's Sunday
denial ``just kind of leaves us in a vacuum again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Two simple words, 'I lied,' would have gone a long way,''
added Rep. Rick Lazio, another undecided Republican from New York.
Lazio, one of more than a dozen lawmakers accompanying Clinton on
his Mideast trip, made his comments on CNN's ``Late Edition.''
</P>
<P>
   The odds are now ``fairly strong'' that the House will vote to
impeach Clinton, Democrat Rep. Charles Schumer of New York conceded
on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   The full House is expected to take up four articles of
impeachment on Thursday. A majority vote of 218 on any of them
would send it to a trial in the Senate, where two-thirds of those
lawmakers are needed to convict and remove the president from
office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has ruled out admitting perjury as a way to mollify
Capitol Hill critics who say his refusal to acknowledge lying under
oath has undercut his repeated apologies for misleading public
statements about his involvement with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no intention of doing that,'' Clinton said Sunday. ''I
did not commit perjury...I could not admit to doing something that
I am quite sure I did not do.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the remarks in response to repeated questions on
the Lewinsky matter during the 30-minute joint press conference
with Netanyahu. The two leaders held some four hours of closed door
talks on how to get the imperiled Israeli-Palestinian peace process
back on track, but there was no apparent breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's three-day visit here is the fourth of his presidency
in search of a way to advance the deeply troubled peace process.
One of his first acts upon arrival was to call key Democrats on the
House Judiciary Committee to discuss impeachment prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were a couple of committee Democrats. I'm not precisely
sure who they were,'' said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps two dozen House Republicans are regarded as undecided on
the impeachment articles, and their votes could determine whether
Clinton becomes only the second president in U.S. history to be
impeached by the House.
</P>
<P>
   This week's looming House impeachment votes have cast a sobering
pall over the administration, and it was apparent Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   His expression ranging from glum to grim, Clinton staggered
through the press conference, which was dominated by
scandal-related questions from both Israeli and American reporters.
At one point, Netanyahu took the unusual step of interrupting an
Israeli reporter to admonish him to ask about peace talks, not
impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ''May I ask a favor,'' Netanyahu said. ''The president has come
here on a very clear...voyage of peace, and I believe that it would
be appropriate also to ask one or two questions on the peace
process.''
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee has sent to the full House two
articles of impeachment alleging that Clinton committed perjury
once during a sworn deposition in the Paula Jones sexual harassment
suit and again during grand jury testimony concerning his
relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said on Sunday that even if he is impeached by the House
and there is a Senate trial, he will fight rather than step down.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no intention of resigning,'' Clinton said in response
to a question. ''It's never crossed my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has admitted wrongdoing in the Lewinsky matter,
said on Friday that he would accept the official disgrace and
public opprobrium of congressional censure a non-binding
declaration that he had brought dishonor to his office through
inappropriate conduct.
</P>
<P>
   He reiterated on Sunday his hope that the House would opt for
censure over impeachment. The president obliquely alluded to his
high job approval ratings in opinion polls they have remained above
65 percent nationally through most of the year as evidence that the
public has essentially endorsed that approach.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders, led by Speaker-to-be Bob Livingston of
Louisiana, have said they will not allow a censure vote on the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   But House Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri said
Democrats will try to bring it up anyway. When they are ruled out
of order, he said, Democrats will use a parliamentary maneuver to
force a vote on whether the censure measure should be brought up as
an alternative to the articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Making a direct appeal to lawmakers, Clinton urged them to
reject partisan arm-twisting and instead to ''vote his or her
conscience, based on the Constitution and the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Clinton, ''I think it's important that they be free to make
this decision and that they not be put under any undue pressure
from any quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House, however, has been quietly waging its own
campaign to win over undecided Republicans. By Sunday, nearly every
undecided Republican had been contacted by members of Clinton's
cabinet, his lawyers or other senior administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   ''We talked to most, if not all, of the members of Congress who
are in the process of making up their mind,'' said Lockhart. ''That
will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he has spoken personally with some House
Republicans who requested conversations with him on the subject,
but he said it was not his role to actively lobby House members on
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have talked to those, a few, who said they wanted to talk to
me. Otherwise, I have not,'' Clinton said. ''I don't think it's
appropriate for me to be personally calling people. Unless they
send word to me that there is some question they want to ask or
something they want to say, I don't think it's appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the White House campaign, Clinton conceded that the
outcome of this week's House votes remained in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know what's going to happen,'' said Clinton. ''It's
out of my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
