<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S DO MORE TO REFORM SOCIAL SECURITY THAN REMOVE THE WAGE CAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: The latest bad idea to ``save'' Social Security is
removal of the payroll tax's wage cap, which has tremendous
political appeal because it represents a tax increase that would
hit only the most highly paid workers.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bad idea because it's proffered without any recognition
of the need to make the payroll tax more progressive. This makes it
nothing more than a money-grubbing revenue-enhancement scheme,
because Social Security taxes already generate far more income than
is needed to finance benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Excess Social Security revenue, as has been noted in this space
ad nauseam, is spent by the Treasury, and the trust fund gets an
IOU in return that Uncle Sam must redeem when income falls short of
outgo.
</P>
<P>
   What sort of reform would justify unlimited Social Security
taxation? How about a system that exempts the first $5,000 or so of
income? This would protect wage earners at the bottom of the
ladder, for whom Social Security taxes are egregiously regressive.
Counting the employer's contribution, these poor souls are burdened
with a 12.4 percent tax on their first dollar of income.
</P>
<P>
   For a society that prides itself on fairness and compassion for
the economically disadvantaged, imposing taxes this regressive on
struggling low-income workers borders on a criminal abuse of
government's taxing power.
</P>
<P>
   Removal of the wage cap probably would go a long way toward
generating enough extra revenue to finance such an exemption. If it
fell short, the current annual surpluses could be tapped to make up
the difference.
</P>
<P>
   For those who would like to take reform a step further or in
another direction, an interesting proposal was offered last week by
Alvin Rabushka, a Hoover Institution senior fellow who's best known
as a pioneering proponent of the flat-rate tax.
</P>
<P>
   Rabushka outlined his plan in an essay in The Wall Street
Journal, calling not only for an end to the wage cap, but also an
extension of the Social Security levy to dividends, interest and
capital gains income. Using 1996 Internal Revenue Service data,
Rabushka estimates this would boost annual tax proceeds by more
than $130 billion.
</P>
<P>
   One part of Rabushka's plan is to use some of the extra revenue
to finance a privatization effort. If workers are allowed to divert
part of their Social Security tax to individual savings accounts,
this would reduce Social Security tax income. Any such loss,
however, could be more than recouped, he said, by removing the wage
cap and expanding the base.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of exempting a certain level of income from Social
Security taxes, though, Rabushka's proposed reform would link the
Social Security changes to a flat-rate income tax with liberal
exemptions. This, he says, would create the progressivity needed to
make the overall system more fair to lower-income workers.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is to say Rabushka's plan is the best of the reform
proposals on the table. It is to say, however, that tax-policy
proposals are worth discussing only if they transcend the greedy
tendencies of Washington's tax-and-spend crowd.
</P>
<P>
   If the aim of a tax proposal is simply to bleed more money from
productive taxpayers rather than create a more equitable system, no
American should dignify such initiatives with serious discussion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
