r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      12-13 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ERA OF THE INFERIOR COPY LOOMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: The fervidness of research into mammalian cloning is
matched only by the controversy over cloning's moral and social
implications. And the debate is sure to be made hotter by the
success of Japanese scientists in producing eight identical calves
from a cow's cells collected in a slaughterhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the cloned creatures died at birth or shortly after, but
the other four survive, in apparent good health. So once again the
central question is brought into sharp focus:
</P>
<P>
   If a procedure once thought fantastical can be carried out
almost routinely in other animals, what _ if anything _ is to
prevent its being repeated in human beings?
</P>
<P>
   The obvious answer, of course, is that nothing is likely to
prevent it. Not proscriptions of law or religious teaching. Not, it
would appear, any practical impediment. And not, certainly, any
voluntary restraint.
</P>
<P>
   For the governing ethic (if it's to be called that) of our time
seems to be that if something can be done, then it follows
naturally that it must be attempted. Certain things may be
impossible. But nothing is unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   It was this dissonance between possibility and principle that
chilled scientists engaged in wartime nuclear research, when they
realized they had not merely solved an elegant riddle of physics;
they had unlocked a force that could threaten the future of
humanity itself.
</P>
<P>
   Not all people, not all scientists, not all societies, however,
are animated by such scruples.
</P>
<P>
   In ancient Egypt, when Pharaoh died, it was custom for some of
his beasts and his essential servants to be entombed with him, to
accompany him for his comfort and convenience in the next world.
</P>
<P>
   A bizarre notion, you say. And yet today, people of sufficient
means and madness may have their corpses cryogenically preserved,
to await the future discovery of some cure for the diseases that
claimed them.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago a man told me _ someone who may have been in a
position to know, and who swore it was truth _ that Walt Disney's
head was preserved in an underground storage vault in Kansas City,
on the chance it could someday be rejoined to a serviceable body.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds far-fetched. But in any case, the newspaper I write
for was owned then by the Disney company. So, for reasons I trust
you understand, I didn't mention this in my column.
</P>
<P>
   The issue now, however, is cloning, which strikes me as being
only slightly less bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   It raises the possibility that adult human beings, as they saw
time shortening and their run moving toward its end, might give
issue to children who would be precise physical copies of
themselves, or perhaps even to multiples of such copies.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, some time in the not-too-distant future, that surely
will be done. And it will afford a kind of immortality, I suppose,
but immortality of a cheap sort _ cheap in the same sense that a
mechanical photocopy of a work of art is less valuable than the
hand-created original.
</P>
<P>
   All that can be said with fair certainty is some of us will not
be interested in being duplicated.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the body of experience that is responsible for
most of who we are could not be transmitted or replicated in our
clones. The genetic cargoes might be the same. But we would be only
strangers who, because of the differences in ages, wouldn't even
look a thing alike.
</P>
<P>
   Our outcomes, too, would be different _ a mercy, since most of
us know our own mistakes so well.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike those cloned calves in Japan, the copies of us
probably wouldn't even be suitable for table.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
