<HEADLINE>
HERE'S A SUGGESTION FOR A HOLIDAY GIFT FOR YOUR BOSS: NOTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Want to know what to get your boss for the holidays?
</P>
<P>
   The most career-savvy answer is nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago I read about a Maryland woman who gave her
boss one of her kidneys. It wasn't a holiday gift, but it set
office ethicists pontificating about the mixed messages sent when
subordinates give gifts _ especially lavish ones _ to their bosses.
</P>
<P>
   The kidney donor's boss was touched and grateful. Neither he nor
the donor said they considered in the slightest what consequences
such a gift would have on their workplace relationship. Theirs is a
sincerely lovely story.
</P>
<P>
   But an informal Wall Street Journal survey found that many
bosses get the creepy crawlies when their employees give them
gifts. The bosses said they worry that the giver is fawning over
them or expecting future favors.
</P>
<P>
   Others admit they worry about their abilities to judge gift
givers fairly in future personnel matters, especially if the gifts
were good ones. Mostly, though, the bosses said they don't have
time to acknowledge gifts, and they certainly don't need them.
</P>
<P>
   There may be a few numskulls out there who'll give you favors in
exchange for a nice gift. Mercifully, those loonies are rare. Most
will see through misguided gift-giving.
</P>
<P>
   Many others will feel just a little uneasy, especially if they
don't reciprocate in kind, at even the most modest, cleanly
motivated gift.
</P>
<P>
   If you simply can't get through the holidays without giving
gifts to supervisors, please consider alternatives to a bottle of
booze, a tie, a box of candy, golf balls or any other merchandise
item.
</P>
<P>
   How about making a donation to a favorite charity in the boss's
name? You could write the check to your own favorite philanthropy,
but you might score more gratitude points if you direct it to the
boss's pet project.
</P>
<P>
   Even better, you could write your manager a nice note, telling
why you enjoy working for him or her. If you can't do that
sincerely, you probably have no business giving a gift at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 1823EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
