<SLUG> BC-IMPEACHMENT-VOTES-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC HOUSE MEMBER REMAINS UNDECIDED ABOUT IMPEACHMENT VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Pat Danner fumbles in her purse and pulls out
a white, plastic card.
</P>
<P>
   This is a U.S. representative's voting pass, the one she inserts
in a slot at her seat on the House floor every time she's called to
make a vote in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The options are always the same: The green button for yes, the
red for no, the yellow button for abstain.
</P>
<P>
   Which color Danner pushes this week, though, isn't clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honest to God could swear on a witness stand that I do not
know how I'm going to vote,'' the Missouri Democrat said last week.
</P>
<P>
   She was preparing for the upcoming, historic _ and
too-close-to-call _ roll call on the impeachment of the 42nd
president of the United States, Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may not even decide until I put that card in the slot.''
</P>
<P>
   Forces keep tugging her in opposing directions. Phone callers to
her congressional offices are split on the question. People she
meets in her 6th District, which stretches from Kansas City north
to the Iowa border, tell her one thing, then another.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, she met with two groups in St. Joseph. One urged
impeachment, the other the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hearing impeach, don't impeach, impeach, don't impeach,''
said Danner, who is among a handful of Democrats and perhaps two
dozen mostly moderate Republicans whose positions are not known.
``No matter what I do, people are going to think I didn't vote
their view.''
</P>
<P>
   Her district flops from one party to the other in elections:
Republican Kit Bond for Senate, Democrat Mel Carnahan for governor,
Republican John Ashcroft for Senate, Democrat Bill Clinton for
president.
</P>
<P>
   Danner may be on the fence, but other lawmakers from Kansas and
Missouri are not. Rep. Vince Snowbarger, a Kansas Republican,
favors at least three counts of impeachment. Fellow Republican
Reps. Todd Tiahrt and Jim Ryun of Kansas also back some impeachment
articles.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, Rep. Karen McCarthy opposes impeachment. Rep. Ike
Skelton won't say where he stands.
</P>
<P>
   With the president's fate hanging in the balance, Danner is
feeling the heat.
</P>
<P>
   These days, she awakes often during the night, fretting about
the vote. She opens her eyes to see the yellow numbers from her
digital alarm clock projected through a prism on her bedroom
ceiling. 2:06 ... 3:37 ... 5:14. Danner is getting familiar with
the middle-of-the-night television lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Her matching living-room couches are crowded with briefing
papers, articles and books. A graduate of a speed-reading course,
Danner doubts that she can get through it all.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, she said, is the toughest she's had to cast since she
was elected to Congress in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing else comes close,'' Danner said.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, a simple majority of 218 votes on any of the four
impeachment articles is needed to send the measure to the Senate.
The full House will meet Thursday to begin weighing the articles.
</P>
<P>
   Already five Republicans, who hold a 228-206 edge over Democrats
in the House, have stated publicly that they oppose impeachment. On
the other side of the aisle, about half a dozen conservative
Democrats, including Danner and possibly Skelton, are possible
votes for it.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest bloc, however, is the cadre of moderate Republicans
who remained undecided heading into the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Both Danner and Skelton broke party ranks in October when they
voted with 29 other Democrats to authorize the impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the first time Danner had stepped away from her
party. A member of the ``Blue Dogs,'' a group of conservative
Democrats known for seeking bipartisan solutions to tough problems,
Danner is seen as an independent thinker.
</P>
<P>
   On this issue, she asserts that her vote will be a matter of
conscience, not something dictated to her by party bosses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listen to what people say, but I make up my own mind,''
Danner said.
</P>
<P>
   During an interview over lunch Thursday, Danner offered her most
passionate arguments for the do-not-impeach position. She openly
fretted about the effect of an impeachment trial on the Senate,
where more routine business could be backlogged for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd cripple government for a year,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court could be similarly affected. Chief Justice
William Rehnquist would oversee the Senate trial, forcing the court
to also delay its work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know for what time period we'd be looking at,''
Danner said. ``No one really knows how all of this would work.''
</P>
<P>
   She expressed concerns over how a prolonged impeachment trial
would affect Clinton, who faces an array of international problems
ranging from the activities of Iraqi strongman Saddam Hussein to
the world economic crisis to Russia's internal turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   In what might be another hint at how she will vote, Danner said
Republican leaders should allow members to vote on a congressional
censure, a formal reprimand. GOP leaders so far have resisted,
insisting on a straight up or down vote on impeachment. But if a
compromise censure option is made available, the ability to pass an
impeachment measure might falter.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, Danner bridled at the notion of the president
having a relationship with a subordinate, a practice that raises
questions of sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've certainly seen what happens in the military, even if you
have an affair that is very old, many years in the past,'' she
noted. ``It can destroy your military career.''
</P>
<P>
   Her vote on the impeachment inquiry in October is viewed as a
sign of her deep dissatisfaction with the president's actions.
</P>
<P>
   The issue, Danner said, is deeply serious in some ways and
sublimely ridiculous in others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the yin and the yang,'' she said. ``That's what makes it
so difficult.'' MORE
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ it so difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Danner is undecided, she has received few lobbying
calls from fellow Democrats. Vice President Al Gore didn't contact
her when he was in Kansas City recently, although he discussed how
Danner might vote with other Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   House Democratic Leader Richard Gephardt hasn't phoned, nor has
Clinton, although a lobbyist close to the president left a
telephone message. Danner didn't call back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like I needed to be lobbied by a Washington
attorney,'' Danner said.
</P>
<P>
   The president did reach out in another way, though. In
September, the White House extended a prized state-dinner
invitation to Danner, her first, when Czech President Vaclav Havel
visited Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Danner remembers the night vividly. She and her husband were
seated separately. Danner was directed to Table 14 in the East
Room.
</P>
<P>
   When she arrived, she looked over the place cards at her
circular table. Henry Kissinger. Kurt Vonnegut. The wife of the
Czech leader. And finally, Mr. President and to his immediate left,
The Honorable Pat Danner.
</P>
<P>
   During a long evening of dining on scrumptious creations that
meld together in Danner's memory, she had the president's almost
undivided attention. Havel's wife, who sat to the president's right
and spoke little English, spent most of her time talking to the
multilingual Kissinger.
</P>
<P>
   Danner and Clinton talked about children, family, Arkansas and
how people around Little Rock sometimes top their barbecue
sandwiches with cole slaw.
</P>
<P>
   But Washington business, including the Lewinsky matter, never
surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it would have been inappropriate,'' Danner said. ``He
is a delightful dinner companion. You wouldn't have thought there
was one thing wrong in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The congresswoman thinks the seating arrangement was
intentional. The president knew she might be a swing vote on
impeachment. So, did it work?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever my vote may be, it won't be based on knowing him, but
on the evidence as I see it,'' Danner said. ``He has his job to do,
and I have my job to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
