<SLUG> BC-CRITICS-FILM-AWARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES CRITICS HONOR `PRIVATE RYAN' 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ It's Oscar time in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   In a vote that could foreshadow next year's Academy Awards, the
Los Angeles Film Critics Association on Saturday night named
``Saving Private Ryan'' best picture of the year and Steven
Spielberg, who made the film, best director.
</P>
<P>
   The best actress award was a tie: Fernanda Montenegro, for the
Brazilian drama ``Central Station,'' and Ally Sheedy, who played a
once-famous photographer living as a recluse in the independent
drama ``High Art.'' Ms. Montenegro, one of Brazil's foremost stage
actresses, plays a bitter elderly woman who takes a motherless boy
under her wing.
</P>
<P>
   Named best actor by the 49-member group was Ian McKellen for his
role as the ``Frankenstein'' director James Whale in the
independent film ``Gods and Monsters.''
</P>
<P>
   Best supporting actor was also a tie: Billy Bob Thornton, for
his role as one of three men in ``A Simple Plan'' who find a downed
airplane with a fortune in cash, and to Bill Murray for two quirky
roles, a businessman in the comedy ``Rushmore'' and a low-rent
lawyer in the drama ``Wild Things.''
</P>
<P>
   The supporting actress award went to Joan Allen, who plays a
woman who transforms herself in the comedy-drama ``Pleasantville.''
</P>
<P>
   The association gave the best screenplay award to Warren Beatty
and Jeremy Pikser for the political satire ``Bulworth,'' in which
Beatty starred and directed.
</P>
<P>
   The best foreign film prize went to the Danish drama ``The
Celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the next 10 days critics groups from New York, Chicago
and Boston weigh in with their choices in advance of the Academy
Awards. Oscar nominations are to be announced on Feb. 9, and the
awards given on March 21.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the National Board of Review named ``Gods and
Monsters'' and its star, McKellen, as best film and actor. Ms.
Montenegro was also named best actress, while the director's award
went to Shekhar Kapur for the historical drama ``Elizabeth.''
Supporting actress and actor awards were voted for Christina Ricci
for ``Buffalo 66,'' ``The Opposite of Sex'' and ``Pecker,'' and to
Ed Harris for ``The Truman Show'' and ``Stepmom.''
</P>
<P>
   While these groups sometimes foretell the Academy Awards, their
choices are not always followed. Last year, for example, numerous
critics groups named the police drama ``L.A. Confidential'' as best
film. But the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences voted in
favor of James Cameron's ``Titanic,'' which swept the Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts the race this year is not entirely predictable,
although ``Saving Private Ryan'' is viewed as almost certain to get
a nomination. Other films in the Oscar running include ``The Truman
Show,'' ``Life Is Beautiful,'' ``Pleasantville,'' ``Elizabeth,''
``Shakespeare in Love,'' ``A Simple Plan,'' ``Gods and Monsters''
and ``The Thin Red Line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 1834EST &QL; 
