<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Monday, Dec. 14 and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Mary Downes on the national-foreign desk at (206) 448-8158.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SEAHAWKS (Seattle) _ The Seattle Seahawks host the San Diego
Chargers.
</P>
<P>
   By Clare Farnsworth. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN (Seattle) _ Column from the Seahawks-Chargers
game.
</P>
<P>
   By Laura Vecsey. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL-BROWN (Nashville) _ The $105 million contract between
pitcher Kevin Brown and the Los Angeles Dodgers has most of Major
League Baseball in an uproar, from the commissioner's office to the
Houston Astros GM, who blames the Brown contract on his team's
decision to drop out of the Roger Clemens sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   By Tyler Kepner. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-COLUMN-OWEN (Seattle) _ It is sometimes called Cape Cod
Turkey, or Down East Turkey. But it has no legs or feathers. Its
image appears on bank notes in Nova Scotia as well as on the seal
of the Colony of Massachusetts. Today, Atlantic cod have virtually
vanished from the Grand Banks due to overfishing and are equally as
scarce at Seattle's Pike Place Market. What are mainly sold here
are Pacific or ``true'' cod, which are smaller and lack the
slightly sweet taste of the Atlantic variety.
</P>
<P>
   By John Owen. (Story will move in the ``d'' category.)
</P>
