<HEADER>
A7476 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-PEACE     12-13 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-PEACE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON, SEEKING TO RALLY ISRAELIS BEHIND PEACE INITIATIVE,
URGES ACCEPTANCE OF PALESTINIANS
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM President Clinton used a Hanukkah message Sunday to
try to rally the Israeli people around a badly listing
U.S.-brokered peace plan, urging them to accept the Palestinians as
their legitimate neighbors with the right to embrace their dignity
and pursue their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   He assured Israelis that the Palestinians were poised to
renounce, ''finally and forever,'' their calls for the destruction
of Israel at a meeting Clinton is to attend in
Palestinian-controlled Gaza on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will witness the reaffirmation of their commitment to
foreswear fully, finally and forever all the provisions in their
charter that called for the destruction of Israel,'' Clinton told
reporters during a joint press conference with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ''To see this happen,'' said Netanyahu, ''would be a welcome and
positive development.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu stopped short, however, of saying whether the gesture
would persuade him to renew Israeli troop withdrawals from occupied
West Bank territories.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Netanyahu called on Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to
retract earlier pledges to declare a Palestinian state by May 4,
unless a comprehensive Israeli-Palestinian peace accord is
completed before then.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one can seriously expect Israel to hand over another inch
of territory,'' Netanyahu said, ''unless and until such an
unambiguous correction is made.''
</P>
<P>
   As Netanyahu talked tough, Clinton went directly to the Israeli
people, with a nationally televised speech, to ask them to maintain
faith in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of his appeal lay Clinton's assertion that the
peace process can't move forward in an atmosphere of continuing
suspicion and antagonism from both sides in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must approach the task ahead without illusions, but not
without hope, for hope is not an illusion,'' Clinton said in a
speech on the first night of the eight-day Jewish observation of
Hannukah. ''The idea of peace and security in the Promised Land
must keep hope alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Clinton and Netanyahu are in precarious leadership
positions that may limit their ability to solve one of the world's
most intractable problems. Clinton faces House impeachment votes
later this week. Netanyahu, who narrowly survived a no-confidence
vote in the Israeli parliament last week, may soon face another.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Sunday's lofty rhetoric were difficult talks between
Netanyahu and Clinton. During his three-day mission, Clinton is
trying to salvage the peace process in the face of escalating
street violence, an almost daily exchange of recriminations between
Palestinians and Israelis and a failure of both sides to keep
promises they made at the White House just six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   After 18 months of stalemate in a peace process that began in
earnest five years ago, Clinton brought Netanyahu and Arafat
together in October at the Wye River Plantation retreat in rural
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Nine torturous days later, the men emerged for a White House
signing of a set of agreements aimed at moving forward toward
so-called ``final status issues'' _ those contentious matters, such
as the future control of Jerusalem and the question of Palestinian
statehood, that must be resolved before the parties can construct a
comprehensive Mideast peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   First, though, the Wye accords have to be implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, for instance, promised to withdraw Israeli troops
from an additional 13 percent of the Israeli-occupied West Bank, a
move that would put roughly 40 percent of the territory under the
full or partial control of the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Israel completed the first phase of that withdrawal last month.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu suspended further withdrawals, however, in the face of
growing anti-Israeli unrest by Palestinians, who have hurled rocks
at Israeli troops in recent weeks, protesting what they see as
Israel's failure to release Palestinian prisoners as promised at
Wye.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu counters that Israel has released a number of
Palestinian prisoners mostly charged with petty crimes or larceny
but that it will not, and never agreed to, release accused
terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   The issue was among several discussed Sunday during about four
hours of talks between Clinton and Netanyahu, and it will be on the
agenda Monday when the president meets with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to return Monday night to Jerusalem, where he is
to meet again with Netanyahu on Tuesday to try to nail down some
gains from this visit, his fourth to Israel since he took office
six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can make this peace, believe me, you can do this,''
Clinton said in a televised speech delivered before several
thousand Israeli high school students, college students and
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
