<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7490 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BULLDOGS-GATECH14     12-13 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BULLDOGS-GATECH14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ga. Tech scores overtime victory against Bulldogs
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS of Jason Collier
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With emotions running the gamut from despair to
exhiliration, with Bobby Cremins cradling his head deep in his
hands in the early going and leading the crowd in cheers at game's
end, Georgia Tech staged one of the greatest comebacks in the
175-game history of its series with Georgia and grabbed an 84-79
overtime victory.
</P>
<P>
   Reminiscent of the 62-61 game Tech won in Alexander Memorial two
seasons ago by coming from 11 points down in the final four minutes
to grab the win from the Bulldogs' jowls, Tech found itself on the
wrong end of a 65-50 score with 8:06 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But Jason Floyd, who had a horrendous day shooting, hit on a
drive and after a free throw by Georgia's G.G. Smith, freshman
guard Tony Akins hit a 3-pointer and got another basket on a drive
and T.J. Vines hit a 3-pointer and the Bulldogs' advantage was
66-60.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the Bulldogs edged their lead to 72-65, but Floyd
made a 3-pointer, Indiana transfer Jason Collier, playing in his
first game, hit another 3-pointer and followed that with a layup.
Akins calmly sank two free throws to throw the game into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   In the extra period, Tech broke on top on a layup by Collier and
another Akins' drive and the Jackets did not trail again.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been coaching here 18 years and that's one of the most
unbelievable games I've ever coached,'' said Cremins, who was
waving his arms widly in the game's final seconds, begging the
crowd of 8,128 for support. ''I thought it was over. I was hoping
we weren't going to get embarrassed. I didn't want to lose it by 15
or 20 or 25. The kids just dug down deep. It was absolutely no
coaching.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a great game to win and a tough game to lose and it
looked as if Cremins and Georgia coach Ron Jirsa were verbally
sparring at the end, but Cremins laughed it off, saying, ''I like
Ron. Ron does a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   The 7-0 Collier was magnificent in his coming-out party, scoring
22 and grabbing 11 rebounds in 42 minutes. But as good as Collier
was, Akins was the man of the hour with 24 points and seven
assists. The ball and the game were in his hands, both in
regulation and overtime and the 18-year-old didn't disappoint. ''I
love having the ball late,'' he said. ''I dont' know if I'm
supposed to or not, but I love it. I wasn't nervous. I was more
nervous at the start. I'm very comfortable at the free-throw
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Collier looked equally at ease, although he admitted he wasn't
in game shape after a year's layoff mandated by the NCAA for a
transfer. He looked exhausted midway through the second half and
came up short on four shots in a row. But he recovered, scoring
nine of his 22 in the final four minutes of regulation and
overtime. ''I'd had the flu for the last week and lost some weight
and then lost some more studying for exams and I was exhausted,''
he said. Collier, whose father played at Tech from 1973-76, says he
didn't envision a first game like this. ''I didn't know I'd do this
well. But ever since high school, I always played well in front of
Coach Cremins. I've heard all about the Tech-Georgia rivalry all my
life. I understand what it means, especially to my dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
