<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7510 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALL-BANKS-THRIVING-     12-13 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-BANKS-THRIVING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TINY FINANCIAL INSTITUTIONS THRIVE IN MIDST OF GIANTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THOUSAND OAKS, Calif. -- In the summer of 1996, Anthony
Kourounis made this pitch to his orthodontist as his son was
getting his braces done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Norm, I'm kind of looking at forming a new bank,'' said the
former banking executive.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't an offbeat idea. His orthodontist had been involved in
starting two other banks. Today, the orthodontist is a shareholder
who sits on the board of 10-month-old California Oaks State Bank,
along with Kourounis, the former mayor of suburban Thousand Oaks in
Southern California and seven other folks with longstanding roots
in the area.
</P>
<P>
   That's just fine with Kourounis, who believes that local folks
can do a better job of serving local needs than big banks
headquartered elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the major banks specifically address the needs of a
specific community,'' said Kourounis, president of California Oaks.
``You sacrifice the client base in the interest of efficiency.''
</P>
<P>
   His belief that small financial institutions can better serve
locals is shared by other entrepreneurs in California and
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   From 1993 to 1997, the number of new banks and thrifts increased
from 68 to 200, according to the American Bankers Association in
Washington. There were 84 in the first half of 1998. In California,
12 new institutions were formed this year, up from seven in 1997.
There are 25 state applications pending.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the backdrop for this spate of new entrants is a
consolidating industry: The total number of banks and thrifts has
dropped from 13,220 in 1993 to 10,712 today nationally, largely
thanks to mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for this divergent trend: As banks and thrifts merge,
they may leave certain areas underserved or anger pockets of
customers who don't like differences in services, products and
personnel. Smelling an opportunity, small banks and thrifts are
popping up.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunity arises especially when an out-of-town buyer swoops
in and purchases regional banks with deep roots in a community.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get an out-of-town bank buying an in-town bank, the
(merged bank) might not serve all parts of the market. So niche
players arise,'' said Keith Leggett, senior economist for the
American Bankers Association. ``A lot of banking is still
relationship building. Small businesses especially will look at
someone who understands the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   He said new community banks and thrifts tend to be small and
``high touch,'' industry jargon for plenty of personal service.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with a bigger institution is the tendency to take a
cookie-cutter approach to areas with temperaments as different as
Los Angeles and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big banks have to put people into a round hole and if you're a
square peg, you don't fit,'' said James ``JP'' Gough, director for
strategic planning and mergers and acquisition in banking at
Deloitte &AMP; Touche in Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   In San Diego County in the early 1990s, he said, many banks were
acquired or had collapsed. These institutions had provided small
business loans, jobs and charitable funds to the community. When
the remaining players became bigger, the frequency of start-up
businesses dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (the smaller banks) disappeared, no more local banks were
willing to bet on small local businesses. The local guy can't
compete with the big guy on credit,'' he said. ``Big banks want
your balance sheet to be perfect. (In effect), you have to
demonstrate that you don't need the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Add this to the formula -- at any given point 25 percent of an
institution's customers aren't satisfied -- and enterprising new
bankers have enough on their plate to lure away business.
</P>
<P>
   And lure they do. Gough has known bankers to go door-to-door
dropping off business cards, although for former banking executives
the more common way is to take clients from the previous employer
who downsized or retired them.
</P>
<P>
   In Kourounis' case, his first taste of a big bank merger came
when First Interstate bought his employer in 1994. The former
senior vice president at First State Bank of the Oaks moved to
First Interstate, as vice president of corporate banking for the
Western region.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Wells Fargo came a-courting and married First
Interstate. But this time, he had reservations about changing jobs
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't sure that's where my heart was,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kourounis and his wife discussed the possibility of starting a
new bank. They gave themselves six months to gauge interest and
ability to raise capital.
</P>
<P>
   In three months, they got enough positive feedback to give it a
shot. They put together a board of directors from the community,
not venture capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   They needed $5 million to start, but were able to raise $5.7
million in four months from 450 shareholders. The 10 directors put
$1.2 million in the pot.
</P>
<P>
   Kourounis' secret weapon is personal service and accessibility.
He recognizes that he can't compete with the big institutions when
it comes to the technology race, such as the number of ATMs.
</P>
<P>
   But he argues that big banks charge fees with a lower level of
service -- if you have to pay fees anyway, why not get personal
service for which you paid, he asks rhetorically.
</P>
<P>
   Since California Oaks opened in February, assets have reached
$26 million with 2,100 accounts, helped by ads, marketing and
word-of-mouth recommendations. But ultimately, Kourounis believes a
personal touch made the difference -- such as a children's play
corner next to the new accounts section.
</P>
<P>
   As head of a 17-employee operation, customers are sometimes
startled to hear him answer the phone. When asked why, he simply
says: ``It was my turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, customers can talk to the president directly. They can
even order him around, as one client stranded at the Sacramento
airport did.
</P>
<P>
   She needed the bank to wire money to a credit card account so a
rental car company would accept the card. In half an hour, it was
all set up.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't have to call a branch manager who needed to get
approval,'' said Kourounis, who handled the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   California Oaks hopes to build its success on a good reputation.
It seems fitting that its operations are growing in an office that
echoes with the ghosts of banks past, as a symbol of new life.
</P>
<P>
   The office started out as the regional headquarters for First
Federal Savings of Santa Monica, which was bought by Home Savings
of America. Most recently, it was the home of Long Beach Savings,
which also was purchased by Home Savings.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby are buildings that at one time or another housed branches
of American Savings Bank, Coast Savings, Great Western and Home
Savings. They were all bought by Washington Mutual.
</P>
<P>
   California Oaks' only locally based rival is Los Robles Bank,
which is also headquartered in the Conejo Valley, northwest of Los
Angeles County. The area's other banks are branches of Wells Fargo,
Sanwa and Bank of America.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the California Oaks' slogan: ``We have our roots where
others have their branches.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 1929EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981213.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
