</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BLACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRAIG BLACK, 66, MUSEUM CURATOR, EXPERT ON VERTEBRATE
PALEONTOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Pa.)  (rl) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Craig Call Black, a retired museum administrator who was an
authority on ancient life forms, died on Dec. 5 at Presbyterian
Hospital in Albuquerque, N.M. He was 66 and lived in Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications from lymphoma, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Black conducted vertebrate paleontology research in France,
Greece, Tunisia, Algeria and South Africa, as well as in Kenya,
where he collaborated with the anthropologist Richard Leakey.
</P>
<P>
   Black was born in Beijing, where his father was teaching
pediatrics. He received a bachelor's degree in 1954 and a master's
degree in 1957 from Amherst College, and a doctorate in biology in
1962 from Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   He began his museum career in 1960 as an assistant curator at
the Carnegie Museum of Natural History in Pittsburgh. He was
appointed curator of vertebrate paleontology in 1962 and later was
director of the Carnegie Museum for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   From 1982 to 1994, Black was the director of the Natural History
Museum of Los Angeles County.
</P>
<P>
   He was appointed by President Reagan to the National Museum
Services Board in 1982 and then to the National Science Board,
which made him chairman of its committees on international science
programs, global environment and biodiversity.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, President Bush named Black to the Environment for the
Americas Board. He was also a past president of the American
Association of Museums.
</P>
<P>
   Black is survived by his wife of 12 years, Mary Elizabeth King,
an anthropologist; a daughter, Lorna B. Walsh of Albuquerque; a
son, Christopher A., of Portland, Ore., and two grandchildren. He
is also survived by a former wife, Constance Hockenberry Black, of
Pittsburgh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 1940EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981213.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7529 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      12-13 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOVERNMENT TO TAKE OVER NIPPON CREDIT BANK IN JAPAN
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government said that it would take over Nippon
Credit Bank, the nation's 14th-biggest lender, in the second bank
nationalization in as many months.
</P>
<P>
   The swiftness of the action surprised even the bank, and
analysts saw the takeover as the clearest signal yet that the
government was serious about cleaning up Japan's banks, which have
more than $600 billion in uncovered bad and risky debt.
</P>
<P>
   SUN AND ORACLE CHALLENGE MICROSOFT
</P>
<P>
   In a direct challenge to Microsoft, Sun Microsystems and Oracle
plan to announce an agreement Monday that will let businesses gain
access to database software without using an operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Adding momentum to the movement to share software freely, IBM
plans to make available the original programmer's instructions for
a new e-mail program.
</P>
<P>
   BUILDING A SPANISH EMPIRE
</P>
<P>
   Offering a combination of salsa and merengue music aimed at
listeners 18 to 34, the Spanish-language radio station WSKQ-FM,
which promotes itself as Mega 97.9, has dominated the metropolitan
New York market. The success of the station, one of a dozen across
the nation owned by Spanish Broadcasting System, which is run by
Raul Alarcon and his son, Raul Alarcon Jr., is testimony to the
power of the expanding Spanish-speaking audience as
English-language formats become increasingly fragmented.
</P>
<P>
   A LIGHTER TONE AT BRILL'S CONTENT
</P>
<P>
   Steven Brill, the chairman and editor in chief of Brill's
Content, the media-watchdog monthly, has lost his editor, Michael
Kramer, and may have lost some of what even Brill says is the
sometimes overly heavy feel of his magazine.
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH PROMOTES ITS STOCK
</P>
<P>
   Bell South has become more aggressive in promoting its stock
than it has been at any time at least since passage of the
Telecommunications Act of 1996, leading some analysts to think the
company is getting set to use its elevated shares to make a bid for
a new long-distance phone company.
</P>
<P>
   GE OF BRITAIN IN MERGER TALKS
</P>
<P>
   General Electric of Britain says it is in ``intense'' merger
talks with a number of global companies and expects a decision
soon.
</P>
<P>
   SUPPLY LINES OF COPIER WARS
</P>
<P>
   As Canon, Xerox and Hewlett-Packard churn out ever-more
sophisticated digital copiers and undertake expensive advertising
campaigns that promote each product's features, the key to
domination may be lining up the best distribution network. That has
serious ramifications for Ikon Office Solutions and Danka Americas.
</P>
<P>
   YEAR 2000 LIABILITY CASE IS FILED
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, a federal court has been asked to rule on
whether normal business liability insurance covers a software
company that is sued for selling products that cannot cope with the
year 2000 problem.
</P>
<P>
   EFFECT OF INTERNET DAY TRADERS
</P>
<P>
   Online day traders, investors who rely on quick market
fluctuations to turn a profit, are starting to have an effect on a
few high-technology stocks.
</P>
</TEXT>
