<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7531 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-SAINTS14-     12-13 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-SAINTS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Chemistry' helps Falcons find formula for seventh-straight win
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ The Atlanta Falcons made a lot more history on
Sunday, which has become the norm in this magical season. But all
the big numbers that added up to a 27-17 victory against the Saints
are not as important as the intangibles that make up the winningest
team in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Jamal Anderson (27 rushes for 148 yards) set a Falcons record
with his 10th game of more than 100 yards; Chris Chandler threw for
345 yards, his best game with the Falcons; Terance Mathis caught
six passes for a team-record 198 yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   The offense got 504 yards, a season-high, against a Saints
defense that last surrendered a touchdown at home on Oct. 11 and
held three straight opponents to a field goal each. The Falcons'
defense allowed the Saints 216 yards _ the fourth straight game an
opponent has been held to less than 245 _ and gave up only a field
goal.
</P>
<P>
   The only other time the Falcons (12-2) won this many games was
1980, the same year they won their only NFC West title. They can
sew up a second _ and a bye in the first round of the playoffs _ if
San Francisco (10-3) loses tonight to Detroit or if Atlanta wins
next Sunday at Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   What matters most, though, was the sight of free safety Eugene
Robinson putting his arm around Chandler as the two walked off the
field, the defensive quarterback hugging the offensive quarterback,
and whispering in his ear: ``Way to throw the ball, man. You were
great.''
</P>
<P>
   All around them in the Superdome, teammates were tossing gloves,
wristbands and bandanas to some of the many Atlanta fans who
watched the Falcons win their seventh straight game overall and
eighth straight against the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   There is an aura surrounding this team, a chemistry, a
camaraderie, something much bigger than any individual record.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give a guy a pat on the back. That's the kind of
stuff nobody talks about,'' said Robinson, who recovered a fumble
to set up Atlanta's first touchdown and later had one of three
Atlanta interceptions. ``We've really got chemistry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably one of the reasons we're doing as well as we
are,'' assistant head coach/defensive coordinator Rich Brooks said.
``Because these guys really are playing as a team, and that's hard
to accomplish in the era of free agency and big-money players vs.
little-money players, and guys changing teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Some things did go haywire for the Falcons. Chandler had an
interception and fumble returned for touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   But Atlanta's defense made sure New Orleans (6-8) rarely had a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the Saints' first five possessions ended in turnovers.
The Falcons reversed their recent trend of falling behind early by
taking a 14-0 first-quarter lead on a 1-yard run by fullback Bob
Christian, and a 62-yard pass to Mathis, who suffered a busted lip
on he play.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very physical football game, which is the way we
expected it would be,'' coach Dan Reeves said. ``I thought our guys
did a really good job of coming out and being physical from the
start. If you enjoy hard-nosed football, you had to enjoy that
one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saints' defense pulled them back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie nickel back Fred Weary returned his second interception
of the game 63 yards for a touchdown to cut Atlanta's lead to 14-7
with 1:25 left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints' new ``Bear'' defense, which basically features a
defender opposite every Atlanta lineman plus blitzing linebackers,
caused occasional problems, because Chandler was harassed most of
the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   When the Saints blitzed early in the third quarter, linebacker
Keith Mitchell leveled Chandler, and linebacker Mark Fields
returned a fumble 36 yards to pull cut the lead to 17-14.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler re-sprained the ankle he injured two weeks ago late in
the third quarter and had to be helped from the field. He returned,
but not long after that, Christian, an immensely valuable part of
the offense, suffered what is believed to be a season-ending knee
injury early in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The final big play came when Chandler hit Mathis on a post
route, and Mathis made a nice move on Saints strong safety Chad
Cota to complete a 63-yard touchdown play for a 27-17 lead with
6:50 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what you do against a defense that is attacking you,''
Chandler said. ``You attack back with routes like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson rushed five times for 49 yards to run out the final
3:06 against a defense that a week ago held the Dallas Cowboys to 8
rushing yards.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis, though, was the big-play man.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, team president Taylor Smith hugged him, whispering,
``You were great man. I loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Falcons, there has been a lot of that going around.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
