<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7539 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PRESIDENTSFOLO-HN     12-13 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PRESIDENTSFOLO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
MELBOURNE, Australia _ The aftermath of America's loss at the
Presidents Cup was predictable. After getting outplayed for three
days, the U.S. players summarized the story by saying they got
``outlucked,'' too.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several members of the losing American team thought it was bad
karma that cost them more than their own play. It was an excuse
quickly pooh-poohed by the victors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask the golfing gods,'' said Tiger Woods when asked about the
smashing performance by the International team. ``We played some
pretty good golf. But when a team holes out from 40 feet or chips
in or makes it from the fairway, what are you going to do? It just
happened to be that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans were pounded 20{ to 11{ by an International team
that got classic efforts from unlikely sources like always-smiling
Japanese player Shigeki Maruyama and from thoroughbreds like Greg
Norman and Steve Elkington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a lack of heart or a lack of desire or a lack of
determination on our part,'' said Mark O'Meara. ``We just got
outplayed. Whether it's been the Ryder Cup or the Presidents Cup,
the other team has risen to the occasion recently.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara and his teammates also pointed to the team's collective
bad putting as a culprit for the poor showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did we putt bad?'' O'Meara said. ``I don't know that we putted
bad. But we could have putted better.''
</P>
<P>
   To an International team that will never forget what happened in
1996, when Fred Couples made a staggering 30-foot putt to win the
Presidents Cup, the U.S. explanations weren't reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's sour grapes,'' said Frank Nobilo, who went 2-2
in his matches. ``When the same thing happened to us, nobody said
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Elkington: ``We didn't say that when Fred Couples rolled
it in from two counties away last time. We made those shots (this
time), and they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Internationals didn't appreciate U.S.
players saying that when they make incredible shots, it somehow
doesn't involve as much luck as when it happens to somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, this isn't the start of a Ryder Cup-style dislike
between the teams in the Presidents Cup, because the competition
over the weekend was fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard-fought on both sides. But it also featured high
respect from both teams toward each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``That U.S. team is a mighty team,'' said International captain
Peter Thomson. ``But we feel that now we're just as mighty.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the blowout results, the singles competition on the
final day was purely for entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   On a personal level, Woods won the battle, even if his team lost
the war. He went against Norman in a classic test of youth against
experience. It was the first time the pair had played together in a
tournament situation. And it was worth the wait.
</P>
<P>
   The Cup had long since been decided, but Woods and Norman took
it upon themselves to put on a riveting show.
</P>
<P>
   It ended with Woods sinking a six-footer for par to tie Norman
on the par-4 18th and earn a 1-up victory in their match in the
singles competition of the Presidents Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ended up being a great finish,'' said Woods. ``It was a
good way to end it. I played well all week, and our team played
well. Just not well enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to have that opportunity to play against one of
the game's best. He birdied five holes in a row on me, so I had to
kind of hang in there through that, and I squeaked it out at the
end.''
</P>
<P>
   The pairing of Norman and Woods was hyped throughout the week.
Unfortunately for the Americans, it lost some luster when they were
outplayed in the first two days during foursomes and fourball play.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the singles, the Internationals were ahead 14{ to 5{.
They won the first two matches in singles to secure the required
16{ points for victory.
</P>
<P>
   As Couples said about the rest of the proceedings: ``It was fun.
But it was just sort of anticlimactic.''
</P>
<P>
   The American players were waylaid early in the tournament. But
the fact that the International team won the Cup for the first time
wasn't all bad news for the U.S. team, captain Jack Nicklaus said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every sporting event, somebody's got to win and somebody's
got to lose,'' said Nicklaus. ``This week, we got beat by a better
team. They played some of the most unbelievable golf. I think if
you get the television tape of this tournament, there's no need to
make a highlight film. It was a highlight film all the way through.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in America used to think we owned the game. We didn't even
invent it. But to put a squad together like Peter (Thomson) did and
have them root for each other and win together is very, very
special.
</P>
<P>
   ``We walked away from Royal Melbourne with a new Presidents Cup
champion. And I think the game of golf is better because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the U.S. took another international hit. They now have
lost the last Ryder Cup, Presidents Cup, World Cup and Dunhill Cup.
</P>
<P>
   And they had a hard time believing it themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't overconfident,'' Mark Calcavecchia said. ``But it
never really dawned on me that we could lose. And the amazing thing
is that it wasn't even close. If it was one or two points'
difference, you might say it was a putt here or there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they all played well, and I don't think anybody on our
team played really outstanding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
