<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-SIDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS SPOIL BRONCOS-DOLPHINS SHOWDOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ No doubt, the Miami Dolphins are
disappointed. In 1985, the Dolphins ended Chicago's perfect season.
And with a 13-0 record and a Monday night game at Miami looming, it
appeared Denver was heading for a similar South Florida ambush.
</P>
<P>
   And then the Broncos played the New York Giants yesterday. Final
score: Giants 20, Broncos 16. End of undefeated season. No more Big
Game in Miami between a 14-0 Denver team playing a Dolphins team
contending for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be lying if I told you we had no regrets about finally
losing and not being undefeated anymore,'' Denver linebacker Alfred
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a chance to separate ourselves from the rest of the
league for years and years and years,'' Denver safety Tyrone
Braxton said. ``It's disappointing, it's depressing. We still
realize that our ultimate goal, which is to win the Super Bowl, is
still in front of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver's loss means that the 1972 Dolphins will remain the NFL's
only undefeated team. Miami finished 17-0 that season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought Denver had a shot and I was looking forward
to that game in Miami,'' former Dolphins coach Don Shula said in a
statement released after the Giants' victory. ``Their loss just
underscores how difficult it is to go undefeated.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver's loss also ended a the Broncos' chance at more history.
The NFL record for regular- and post-season victories is 18; Denver
had tied that record with last week's victory over Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knew it was going to end some time. They've done an
unbelievable job, winning a Super Bowl and then starting this year
13-0,'' Giants coach Jim Fassel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to win 18 in a row,'' said Denver quarterback John
Elway, who was limited to 180 yards passing and no touchdowns. ``It
would have been nice to break that record of winning 19 in a row,
but obviously there's a reason why somebody can't break through
that 18 barrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our goals was to have a perfect season. Our main
concern is we want to start playing better football. The last two
weeks, we've started slow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 2011EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
