<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-UNDEC-LEACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSMAN GETTING AN EARFUL FROM IMPASSIONED VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa)  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-CENSURE, IMPEACH-REPUBS,
IMPEACH-DOCTRINE, IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON, IMPEACH-LEGACY,
IMPEACH-JACKSON, IMPEACH-REACT, IMPEACH-OPINION,
IMPEACH-UNDEC-LEACH, IMPEACH-UNDEC-JOHNSON, IMPEACH-UNDEC-PORTER,
IMPEACH-UNDEC-REDMOND) 
(rl) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa _ The telephone would not stop ringing in the
office of Jim Leach, the longtime congressman from Iowa. And even
in this mild-mannered Midwestern state, the calls were full of
passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a plain witch hunt,'' Joan Nielsen, a 68-year-old woman
from Center Point, wanted the congressman to know. ``They are out
to get the president no matter how they could get him. He has done
a very good job of governing, and I feel that it would be a
detriment to the country to impeach him.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Renee Lancaster, a 42-year-old former teacher
from Hiawatha, pressed just as vehemently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton has lied,'' Ms. Lancaster said. ``I believe he's a
criminal. He should never have been in office.''
</P>
<P>
   All week long and into the weekend the calls spilled into the
office of Leach, who has remained publicly uncommitted on whether
President Clinton should be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other uncommitted Republicans, Leach represents a
district that is a melange of political views, from the liberal
powerhouse of Iowa City, home of the University of Iowa, to the
moderate and conservative views of people in working-class
Davenport and business-minded Cedar Rapids. Leach's aides said the
electorate is composed of equal numbers of Republicans, Democrats
and independents.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, hundreds of calls and thousands of e-mail
messages have poured into Leach's offices in Washington, Davenport,
Iowa City and Cedar Rapids _ 10 times the usual volume. A little
less than two-thirds have favored impeachment. Bill Tate, Leach's
longtime administrative assistant, said ``the tenor of the calls is
increasingly angry about his not making a public pronouncement.''
</P>
<P>
   As the judiciary committee debated and then voted on the
articles of impeachment, the phone rang insistently in Leach's
Cedar Rapids office.
</P>
<P>
   ``To impeach the president over this thing,'' sputtered a
78-year-old man from Marion who said he was disgusted with the
impeachment process. ``I've been a Republican most of my life and I
can damn well assure you that a lot of people won't vote Republican
again.''
</P>
<P>
   A 54-year-old woman named Jan from Anamosa was practically
writhing with anger. ``I cannot believe as an American citizen the
perversion and the twisting of the Democrats,'' she said. ``It just
sickens me. I have sat here and I have wept.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there was this handwritten missive received over the
fax machine: ``Mr. Leach. Please do not vote to impeach, I don't
want it and the country does not want it! Take Mr. C to court after
his term!''
</P>
<P>
   The writer, possibly concerned about sounding overbearing,
finished off with a smiley face and a wish for ``Happy Holidays''
underlined with a squiggle.
</P>
<P>
   Leach's press secretary, Douglas Wagner, who was fielding many
of the calls while the congressman was in Washington, said that as
the week wore on the ratio of people supporting or rejecting
impeachment did not seem to change. But he said that the calls were
becoming more urgent each day and that he had never before heard
constituents respond with ``this kind of consistent intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, Wagner said, there would be a flurry of calls when
something dramatic was happening _ a member of the committee
delivering a particularly sharp-tongued speech, the president
issuing his Rose Garden apology, an article of impeachment being
approved. And any time one of the local newspapers wrote a story
about Leach's decision, as the Cedar Rapids Gazette did on Friday,
the phones would ring even more.
</P>
<P>
   Leach, who has represented eastern Iowa for 22 years, has a
reputation for being careful, deliberative and not easy to
pigeonhole. As the ranking Republican on the House Banking
Committee, Leach led hearings on Whitewater. But he also voted
against Newt Gingrich for speaker of the House in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there is no love lost between him and the White
House, perhaps unlike some of the other `swing' Republicans,'' said
Bruce Nesmith, a political science professor at Coe College in
Cedar Rapids. ``On the other hand, he has had his problems with the
Republican leaders in the House.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Leach has issued only a two-sentence statement calling
the impeachment matter ``a trauma for the country that demands
enormous caution.''
</P>
<P>
   Will all the calls from impassioned voters make a difference?
Wagner was circumspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's people that would say the representative is there to
vote the people's will and there are those who say the
representative is there to vote his conscience,'' he said. ``As a
practical matter it is impossible to take polls on everything, so I
guess he feels more of the latter.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Leach's staff is paying attention, struck that so many in
and around this city of about 110,000 have such strong opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Riley, a Lutheran minister who was sitting near the
Christmas gingerbread house in the Lindale shopping mall here, said
he did not expect that the Senate would ultimately find the
president guilty of impeachable offenses. But he wanted Leach to
support impeachment anyway, to scare Clinton and show him that
``he's not a sovereign king, but he's subject to the
Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Hutchins, a retired electric company supervisor who
favors censure, not impeachment, said Leach should have tried early
on to prevent the explicit sexual revelations of Clinton's affair
with Monica Lewinsky from reaching the eyes and ears of ordinary
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little disappointed as a Midwesterner,'' Hutchins said,
``that Leach did not come out and say, `Hey, we don't need all
this. It's too much detail.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
