<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7571 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-EMBASSIES-ALERT-NY     12-13 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-EMBASSIES-ALERT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBASSIES ALERT AMERICANS IN PERSIAN GULF TO THREAT OF ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUWAIT _ U.S. embassies in four Persian Gulf countries warned
Sunday of a ``strong possibility'' that terrorists might attempt an
attack against one or more U.S. targets in the region in the next
month.
</P>
<P>
   The warning, issued to Americans in Kuwait, Saudi Arabia,
Bahrain and the United Arab Emirates, was unusually precise, and it
was backed up by a show of particular concern. In Bahrain,
headquarters of the U.S. Fifth Fleet, the embassy said that about
1,000 U.S. military personnel have been put under curfew and told
not to gather in large numbers at public places.
</P>
<P>
   The statements called on Americans in the region to ``remain
alert to any suspicious activity and take precautionary steps to
reduce the profile and vulnerability of any United States
facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   They said the U.S. government had information indicating ``a
strong possibility that terrorist elements are planning an attack
against U.S. targets in the gulf, possibly in the next 30 days.''
</P>
<P>
   At least 45,000 Americans, including about 9,000 soldiers,
sailors and airmen, live in the four Persian Gulf countries, and
their security has been a major concern of U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
   The last attacks in the region, in Saudi Arabia in 1995 and
1996, killed 24 Americans, including 19 servicemen.
</P>
<P>
   In October, all U.S. missions in Saudi Arabia closed for four
days to review security after receiving information that the U.S.
Embassy in Riyadh was under threat of a terrorist attack. That move
followed the Aug. 7 bombings of U.S. embassies in Nairobi, Kenya,
and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, in which 224 people were killed and
5,000 injured.
</P>
<P>
   The latest U.S. warnings do not say who might carry out a new
terrorist attack. But the warning in Saudi Arabia does reiterate
standing U.S. concerns over the threats that the Saudi dissident
Osama bin Laden has issued against Americans in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden has been indicted for alleged involvement in a number
of attacks on Americans, including the bombings of the U.S.
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania. His operations in Afghanistan were
the targets of a U.S. cruise-missile attack, following the embassy
attacks, that U.S. officials cast as a pre-emptive raid.
</P>
<P>
   In all four of the countries in which the warnings were issued
Sunday, U.S. military forces maintain a significant presence.
</P>
<P>
   About 5,000 airmen are based in Saudi Arabia, most of them in
the remote desert sites to which U.S. military operations in the
kingdom were transferred after the 1996 bombing in Dhahran.
</P>
<P>
   About 3,000 U.S. servicemen are in Kuwait, most of them also at
remote sites.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of Navy personnel are based in the United Arab
Emirates, but its port of Jebel Ali is a frequent stopping point
for crews and Navy vessels that patrol the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Among the four gulf countries, it has been in Bahrain that U.S.
servicemen have been most visible, but curfews like the one imposed
Sunday have also been ordered in the past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
