<SLUG> BC-BBO-BBNOTES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Astros `stunned,' `outraged' at demands of Clemens' agents
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ The Houston Astros have decided they can't
afford Roger Clemens but would not resign quietly Sunday, club
general manager Gerry Hunsicker delivering a final salvo at
Clemens' agent in what has become one of the most peculiar
attempted transactions is the game's history.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Astros were a leading candidate to fulfill Clemens'
requested trade from Toronto, the club terminated talks when Alan
and Randy Hendricks, Clemens' Houston-based agents, demanded the
five-time Cy Young winner's contract (worth $16.1 million over the
next two years) be restructured for an additional season at a cost
of $27.4 million. That would bring the three-year value of the deal
at $43.5 million, and with an average annual payout of $14.5
million, would rival the monster $105 million deal Kevin Brown
agreed to with Los Angeles Saturday, which will pay him $15 million
per season.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, who also had to pull out of the Randy Johnson
bidding when it grew too high, were simply offended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, we were absolutely stunned and really outranged
at the demands represented by the agent (Saturday) when they
conveyed the terms they were looking for,'' Hunsicker said. ``At
this point, we're not in a position financially to consider this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we were, the talent that we'd potentially have to give
up, in addition to the talent we'd have to trade to accommodate his
restructuring into our payroll would leave us with a team that I'm
not sure Roger Clemens would be interested in being a part of.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Texas, Colorado and the New York Yankees still in
contention and if the Rangers are now the front-runner, the process
is hardly simpler. Though the Blue Jays are pursuing a trade (no
personnel was finalized with Houston), the Hendricks are treating
the financial end almost as if Clemens is a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's oneups-manship, is what is is,'' Hunsicker said.
``Certainly, we're not in a position to compete with some of the
madness that has taken place in some corners of the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the border
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays continued to act as if Clemens will be gone soon
when the team acquired San Diego pitcher and Atlanta resident Joey
Hamilton in a four-man deal. The Blue Jays sent back right-handed
veteran Woody Williams, right-handed reliever Carlos Almanzar and
minor league outfielder Peter Tucci, the club's first-round draft
pick in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we trade Roger, we want to make sure we maintain a
competitive ballclub,'' said Toronto GM Gord Ash. ``We believe in
Joey Hamilton, we've added another starter to the front end of the
rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, who had drawn interest in the past from the Braves,
was 13-13 last season with a 4.27 ERA in 34 starts, working 217
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Remaking the Mets
</P>
<P>
   Making their fourth major acquisition of the offseason, the New
York Mets signed outfielder Rickey Henderson to a $1.8 million
deal, giving the club a potent lead-off hitter as the Mets try to
close the gap in the NL East. New York will be Henderson's sixth
team. He hit .236 but scored 101 runs and walked 118 times in
Oakland last year. He joins Bobby Bonilla, Armando Benitez and
Robin Ventura as new Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Incidently, he will wear No. 24, the first Met assigned that
number since Willie Mays in 1972. New York officials reported the
immortal Kelvin Torve wore No. 24 for a few games in 1990-91 but
that he had been issued the number ``inadvertently.''
</P>
<P>
   Table for two
</P>
<P>
   Bob Gebhart has to pay up. The Colorado general manager was so
certain the Braves would swoop in at the last moment and sign free
agent Kevin Brown that Gebhart wagered a dinner with Atlanta GM
John Schuerholz that Brown would wind up a Brave. Schuerholz
countered with five sets of golf clubs. Brown's record signing came
and went without so much as a call of inquiry from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
