A7601 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXCOL-COLUMN-LAD     12-13 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXCOL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOXING LOSES AN ORIGINAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boxing lost a true wonder when it lost Archie Moore.
</P>
<P>
   The former light heavyweight champion, known for a his big
punch, ring savvy and delightful wit, died in San Diego at what was
believed to be 84 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Consider just a few of his deeds:
</P>
<P>
   He had a record 141 knockouts, according to The Boxing Record
Book. That's more FIGHTS than all but a few boxers have amassed in
their careers.
</P>
<P>
   He fought for 27 years, from 1936 to 1963. He began his pro
career only eight years after Jack Dempsey's last fight and ended
up in the ring with Cassius Clay (now Muhammad Ali). And his career
wasn't like that of Roberto Duran or Larry Holmes today: He was a
remarkably capable fighter until near the end, at 49.
</P>
<P>
   He was the only one to have fought both Rocky Marciano and Ali.
He almost stopped Marciano before he was knocked out himself in the
ninth round in 1955 but was much too slow to cope with Ali and fell
in four in 1962. He was 48 in that fight.
</P>
<P>
   I once asked him who was better, Marciano or Ali. Always a
diplomat, he just smiled and said, ``They were both good.''
</P>
<P>
   He defended the light-heavyweight title, which he won at 39 by
outpointing Joey Maxim in 1952, 11 times over a span of 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   He had engaged in 169 bouts over the span of 17 years before he
got that opportunity to fight for the championship _ his first
title shot. That's perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of the principals in one of the greatest fights ever.
He got up from four brain-jarring knockdowns _ three in the first
round _ to stop Yvon Durelle in the 11th in a title defense.
</P>
<P>
   As the story goes, after the fourth knockdown, his wily manager
Doc Kearns had him wave to his wife, whom he was told was sitting
behind Durelle, when all the while she was sitting elsewhere.
Durelle, believing Moore was waving at him, became unnerved in a
turning point in the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing historian Bert Sugar rates Moore the greatest light
heavyweight and 23rd best fighter of any weight in his ``The 100
Greatest Boxers of All-Time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He epitomized the light-heavyweight division,'' Sugar said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore had his disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   He had to wait so long for his shot at the title principally
because he was African-American and so talented. He had to fight
Maxim for only $800 to get his opportunity finally. He spent a lot
of time on what was called the ``Black Circuit,'' fighting other
top African-American fighters who shared a similar fate.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, a natural light heavyweight who weighed no more than 206
pounds in any fight, never claimed the one prize he so wanted: the
heavyweight title. He lost to Marciano in 1955 (at 41) and Floyd
Patterson the following year in his only two opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   He always saw the Marciano fight as the one that got away. Years
later, Moore said that had referee Howie Kessler simply wiped off
Marciano's gloves after the champ went down in the second round
instead of yanking his arms _ which helped pump life back into him
_ Moore might've won the title.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, Moore never complained.
</P>
<P>
   The media loved him because he loved to talk and because of what
he had to say. He was a self-promoter long before Ali. Television
analyst and former sportswriter Larry Merchant tells the story of
how Moore used to write long, engaging letters to the writers as a
way of marketing himself. And he was always armed with one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   One example is the discrepancy in his age. Moore's mother said
he was born in 1913; he said he was born in 1916. Moore's
explanation?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've given this a lot of thought,'' he said, ``and have
decided that I must have been three when I was born.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, he was a lovable, witty and well-respected
character. More than anything, though, he was a fighter's fighter _
even without the heavyweight crown.
</P>
<P>
   He accomplished more after the age of 39 than all but a few
boxers have in their entire careers. If there was ever a
one-of-a-kind figure in this sport, Moore was it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Archie, to me, was the forerunner of fighters who were
appreciated outside the ring as well as in the ring,'' veteran
trainer Angelo Dundee told the Associated Press. ``He was slick, he
was smart, he was his own PR man.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media loved him because he gave them something, plus he
could fight like hell.''
</P>
<P>
   __ New champ: Here's a prediction: Fernando Vargas of Oxnard,
Calif., who easily beat Yory Boy Campas on Saturday to win the IBF
junior middleweight title, will turn out to be the best of the 1996
U.S. Olympic fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Show me a weakness. The 21-year-old has all the physical tools
and the poise of a much more experienced fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Against Campas, he demonstrated that a significant edge in
natural ability can more than compensate for lack of experience. It
was a masterful performance, particularly for such a young fighter.
</P>
<P>
   __ Title town?: With Vargas and IBF junior-lightweight
titleholder Robert Garcia, Oxnard has two world champions.
</P>
<P>
   Few COUNTRIES have two world champions.
</P>
<P>
   __ Enough: Arturo Gatti, who lost another tough decision to Ivan
Robinson in Saturday's main event, has given boxing fans enough
thrills.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't need to take any more punches.
</P>
<P>
   __ Next up: New WBC super featherweight champion Floyd
Mayweather faces tough Angel Manfredy, Saturday on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   Manfredy's most impressive performance was his victory over
Gatti, whose straight-ahead style is the antithesis of
Mayweather's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I land 50 percent of my punches. Gatti gets HIT with 50
percent of the other guy's punches. You're going to see a
completely different fight. I'm ready,'' Mayweather said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayweather has his sights set on Naseem Hamed.
</P>
<P>
   __ Country Club: Michael Carbajal is expected to pull out of the
Dec. 17 card at the San Fernando Valley site because of the flu.
</P>
<P>
   If so, the former junior flyweight champ will act as color
commentator on the Spanish-language broadcast of the fight on
Channel 22.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it could be a wild night. On the undercard, unbeaten
Tiffany Logan, 200 pounds, will face 300-pound Michelle Lockhart in
a most unusual women's bout.
</P>
<P>
   Logan is promoted by Magic Johnson, who is co-promoting the
card.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Kelley faces Jorge Cocas Ramirez in the main event.
</P>
<P>
   __ Canceled: The Retired Boxers Foundation's awards benefit that
was scheduled for this month was canceled for lack of money.
Founder Alex Ramos said he won't give up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 2102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
