r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      12-13 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLLOCK, LING AND TRUE, BUT NARY A SCROD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It is sometimes called Cape Cod Turkey, or Down East
Turkey. But it has no legs or feathers.
</P>
<P>
   Its image appears on bank notes in Nova Scotia as well as on the
seal of the Colony of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   It is at the center of debate between world historians, vendors
at Seattle's Pike Place Market and tourists who return home wearing
T-shirts reading: ``I Got Scrod in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they did. Maybe they didn't. The menu probably promised
small cod (or scrod), but the kitchen might have delivered fillets
of pollock instead.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes you don't know who to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Columbus didn't discover America. As he searched for spices and
gold, he was preceded by Norsemen and Basques who were fishing for
cod. It was probably the cod fisheries that led England to
establish colonies on this continent.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Atlantic cod have virtually vanished from the Grand Banks
due to overfishing and are equally as scarce at the Pike Place
Market. What are mainly sold here are Pacific or ``true'' cod,
which are smaller and lack the slightly sweet taste of the Atlantic
variety.
</P>
<P>
   Ling cod is an inferior product, purists insist.
</P>
<P>
   The Pike Place fish purveyors don't actually get into fistfights
with their customers on this subject, but they might if they didn't
have to keep their fists ready to receive or deliver flying fish of
the salmon variety known as kamikaze kings.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Intermediate Eater, well, my ancestors from Scotland
and Wales didn't come here for codfish. They were looking for big
bucks. Matter of fact, they're still looking.
</P>
<P>
   One way to save big bucks is to cook up a batch of cod cakes.
They taste almost as good as the much more expensive Dungeness crab
cakes when prepared like this:
</P>
<P>
   True Cod Cakes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup minced onion
</P>
<P>
   Canola oil
</P>
<P>
   3 slices white bread
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters pound true cod fillet
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Tabasco sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet saute the celery and onion in 1 tablespoon
oil until soft, then dump into a bowl and rub the skillet clean
with a paper towel.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a food processor, toss in the bread and hit the
button until you have coarse crumbs. Put two-thirds of the crumbs
in with the onion and celery and save the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Next put the cod into the processor bowl. Hit the button with
short bursts until the fish is minced. Don't lean on the button or
you will have a fish paste and that ain't pretty. If you do not
have a food processor, you can tear the bread into crumbs and mince
the fish with a sharp knife. It will just take a bit longer.
</P>
<P>
   OK, add the fish to the bowl with the onion, celery and crumbs.
Add the egg (or equivalent egg substitute), the mayo, Tabasco,
lemon juice and salt. Moosh everything around until blended. Then
divide the cod mixture into four parts and plop them onto waxed
paper. Pat them into patty shape and then refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   When you are ready to cook, heat a thin layer of canola oil in
the skillet. Sprinkle some of the reserved crumbs over the four
fish cakes then lift each up with a spatula and plop into the pan,
crumb side down. Cook over moderate heat until bottom is browned.
Place more crumbs over the top sides of the patties, then with a
spatula flip them upside down into the pan. Continue to cook 3 or 4
minutes, until the patties are browned on the bottom, then serve,
with quarters of lemon on the side for squeezing. This will serve
two.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a New England recipe that is even more popular than one I
spotted for Parker House Codfish Tongues.
</P>
<P>
   Creamed Cod Columbus
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds true cod fillets
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup butter
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup flour
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 cups low-fat evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sliced, fresh mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 green pepper, seeded and cut in slivers
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup sweet red pepper, seeded and cut in slivers
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon canola oil
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   Cayenne pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a saucepan and stir in the flour. When you
have a smooth paste, slowly add the milk and stir-cook until the
sauce thickens. Hold the sauce over very low heat.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a skillet and saute the pepper slices and
mushrooms for about three 3 minutes. Add the veggies to the sauce
with the sherry plus salt, pepper and cayenne to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Place the cod fillets in a microwaveable dish. Cover with waxed
paper and microwave at full power for about 5 minutes, depending on
the thickness of the fish.
</P>
<P>
   When the fillets can be flaked with a fork, place portions in 4
ramekins or dinner plates. Cover the fish with the warm sauce.
</P>
<P>
   See, you didn't have to get scrod in Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
