</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IMPEACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THOSE MISSING MAGIC WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, Dec. 14: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to duty and self-preservation, there is no
question as to what the content of President Clinton's next speech
should be. The question is whether Clinton will have the strength
and wisdom to deliver it in the days before the House of
Representatives votes to impeach him. The 20 or so Republican
moderates who will decide that vote want to hear the president say
that he lied under oath, in those words. But when he spoke Sunday,
Clinton did not come close to saying the magic words. He has time
to speak them between now and the House vote on Thursday. We hope
that he will, but the odd passivity of the president and his legal
team provides little foundation for such a hope.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his advisers have yet to understand that petulance
is not a strategy, even when the opposition is behaving with
partisan malice and distorting the Constitution. Robert Livingston,
the designated speaker, pondered for days about whether to lead the
House toward an honorable compromise around a censure resolution.
But he backed down rather than face his tough-guy whip, Tom DeLay.
If a future speaker cannot defy ``The Hammer,'' as DeLay likes to
be known, imagine how hard it is for Republican moderates on the
back benches. That is why they were on the Sunday talk shows
imploring Clinton to offer the concession that would provide the
political cover for a vote against impeachment. As Rep. Scott Klug
of Wisconsin said on ``Meet the Press,'' there will be no leniency
from this political court unless it hears ``an admission of guilt
from the president.''
</P>
<P>
   That admission would not be necessary if the House vote was
conducted strictly on constitutional principle. As Lloyd Cutler, a
Clinton defender, said on ABC, this president's ``low crimes'' do
not meet the constitutional standard for impeachment. But politics
and human nature enter into this matter as well. Clinton did lie
repeatedly, in plain sight, while under oath. In the language of
Lawyer World, where Clinton seems to live, it might be possible to
label such behavior as ``ambiguous'' and get away with it. But in
the world of political reality, there has never been a Congress,
Democratic or Republican, that would be willing to extend mercy and
at the same time sign up as historic endorsers of multiple,
bald-faced lies.
</P>
<P>
   By refusing to bargain with the House, Clinton seems to be
betting that the Senate will not remove him. It could, in fact,
impose the kind of censure that Livingston is refusing to allow the
House to consider. But whatever happens in Congress, Clinton's
defiance and his willingness to gamble on a Senate showdown look a
lot like the behavior that got him into this mess _ irresponsible,
self-destructive and dangerously out of place in the Oval Office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 2146EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981213.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7651 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      12-13 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ACROSS THE RIVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At a diet breakfast in New York last week with
Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon, I asked why Yasser Arafat
had been acting so confidently and provocatively lately.
</P>
<P>
   Since October's Wye accords, and following the anger on the
Israeli right about Prime Minister Netanyahu's West Bank
withdrawals, the Palestinians have:
</P>
<P>
   (1) escalated their warnings about a unilateral declaration of
statehood by May 4, which would scuttle negotiations begun in Oslo,
Norway;
</P>
<P>
   (2) incited riots with complaints that Israel was releasing from
jail _ supposedly against the Wye agreement _ ordinary Palestinian
criminals, not inmates with what Sharon calls ``blood on their
hands'';
</P>
<P>
   (3) and fuzzified their pledge to revoke Israel-must-die
provisions of the Palestinian ``covenant,'' hinting that a vote of
the leadership rather than the full membership was all that was
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon's response about Arafat's attitude was curious: ``He's
looking across the river.'' Pressed to explain, the white-haired
``last of Israel's founding generals'' focused instead on what
Clinton could do during his visit to Israel and Gaza to get the
Palestinians back on track.
</P>
<P>
   We will see on Monday night one specific fruit of President
Clinton's visit: Most members of the Palestinian National Council,
as a gesture of gratitude to the U.S. president for bolstering
their sense of statehood, will raise their hands to remove the
offensive language from their organizing document. This will be a
Clinton achievement, reassuring Jews to whom such writings have
meaning, and he deserves full credit for it.
</P>
<P>
   On the Palestinian incitement to violence based on the prisoner
release: It will be a test of Clinton's mediating credibility for
him to step up to that unequivocally in Gaza. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright has already noted that Israel was keeping its
Wye promise on prisoners; if Clinton bears witness on that
pacifying point in his Gaza speech, it may dampen violence planned
for after his departure.
</P>
<P>
   But what of the Palestinians' May 4 ``deadline'' for a final
agreement or else? That word carries worrisome overtones and
Israelis do not react well to ultimatums. Will Clinton lean on
Arafat not just to cool it for a week or so but to publicly drop
that threat, as Sharon urged in the Oval Office last week? Will
Clinton choose to be eyeless in Gaza, or will he see the need to
make plain to all Palestinians that such gun-to-the-head
negotiating undermines the cause of peace?
</P>
<P>
   This is a proper moment for Clinton to be in the Middle East.
Set wag-the-dove cynicism aside; if his trip can show Arafat that
America supports genuine land-for-peace reciprocity, the nation is
better served than with the president holed up in the White House
talking to paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Labor opposition must decide soon whether it will try
to save or scuttle the ``process.'' If it chooses to join the
discontented far right, it might bring down Netanyahu's government
_ but would end all negotiations for six months. In a campaign,
both major parties would surely seek to ``out-security'' the other.
In making peace afterward, a victorious right could ultimately
deliver the soft-line left, but it doesn't work the other way
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arik,'' of all people, is becoming the most unifying force in
Israel. He actively seeks a unity government with Labor; if that
doesn't fly, he eyes a coalition with a potential amalgam of the
Likud left and Labor right. (Impossible? Look, if the House can
impeach Bill, Bibi can embrace Dan Meridor.)
</P>
<P>
   But what drives Arik to alienate far-right followers and reach
across political lines? He says he sees the urgency to create a
climate that will draw another million Russian Jews to Israel,
helping secure the state demographically.
</P>
<P>
   Now let me guess what he meant by ``looking across the river.''
If Arafat gets a state with the borders he demands, he will then
look across the Jordan River. King Hussein is gravely ill; his
Hashemite clan is outnumbered by Palestinians. Jordan and Palestine
might soon ``federate,'' but under Palestinian leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan borders on Iraq. With the formation of Greater Palestine,
a truck could start out in Baghdad and roll unvexed to within a
mortar's range of Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder most Israelis want to keep a protective territorial
presence within the West Bank of the Jordan River.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
