<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
CLINTON LAUNCHES EFFORT TO SAVE MIDEAST PEACE PACT
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By NANCY MATHIS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
JERUSALEM _ President Clinton called on Israelis and Palestinians
Sunday to stop provocative actions and adhere to the Wye River pact
if peace is to come to the troubled region.
</P>
<P>
   But Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, during a
strikingly negative assessment of Palestinian compliance, demanded
that Yasser Arafat renounce his intentions to declare a Palestinian
state next year or Israel will halt further land concessions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton launched a three-day effort to salvage the Wye River
Memorandum that called on Israel to withdraw troops from portions
of the West Bank in return for security guarantees from the
Palestinian Authority. The United States is still trying to arrange
a three-way meeting among Clinton, Netanyahu and Arafat to revive
the faltering accord.
</P>
<P>
   The provisions of the pact have been frozen as both sides,
facing internal political opposition, increased the rhetoric.
Palestinian youths repeatedly have clashed with Israeli soldiers
over the issue of prisoner releases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each side has serious political constraints; I think we all
understand that. Provocative pronouncements, unilateral actions can
be counterproductive, given the constraints that each side has,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in the end, there has been a fundamental decision made to
deal with this through honest discussion and negotiation. That is
the only way it can be done,'' Clinton added. ``It cannot be done
by resorting to other means when times get difficult. And again, I
say the promise of Wye cannot be fulfilled by violence or by
statements or actions that are inconsistent with the whole peace
process. Both sides should adhere to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent two hours behind closed doors with Netanyahu and
his delegation as they made their assessment of the Wye River
accord. Today, Clinton will do the same with Arafat during an
unprecedented visit to the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Netanyahu accused the Palestinians of doing nothing
to comply with the terms of the Wye River pact and offered a harsh
assessment of the accord so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret to say that none of these conditions have been met,''
Netanyahu said at a brief news conference with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister criticized the Palestinians for Arafat's
comments that they will declare a state on May 4 and make eastern
Jerusalem the Palestinian capital. He called the act a ``gross
violation'' of a previous agreement to settle such issues as
statehood during final status talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Arafat and the Palestinian Authority must officially and
unequivocally renounce this attempt. I think no one can seriously
expect Israel to hand over another inch of territory unless and
until such an unambiguous correction is made,'' Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
   The second phase of Israeli troop redeployment is scheduled for
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu also accused the Palestinians of inciting violence and
accused the Palestinian Authority of downgrading its security
cooperation with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   He also was dismissive of the Palestinian National Council
session scheduled today in which it will affirm removal of charter
provisions calling for Israel's destruction. Clinton is to observe
the vote and speak to the council.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that today (Monday) the Palestinian Authority will
once and for all live up to at least one of their obligations,''
said Netanyahu, who was referring to the vote.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official said that the United States does not
share Netanyahu's views on Palestinian compliance and that both
sides complied with the first phase of the Wye accord.
</P>
<P>
   During the first phase, Israel withdrew its troops from 2
percent of the 13.1 percent of the West Bank that it agreed to turn
over to Palestinian control. The Palestinian Authority in turn took
steps to crack down on security as a step toward combating
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said that renunciation of
the statehood declaration was not a condition in the Wye accord.
However,she also said that ``unilateral actions and unilateral
statements generally are not helpful to the atmosphere of having
the Wye process go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The main issue that must be dealt with is the question of
violence, Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive issues, such as prisoner releases, need ``to be
resolved at the table and not out in the streets,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech broadcast throughout the nation, Clinton later spoke
to 3,000 Israeli young people and reaffirmed the U.S. commitment to
Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the Wye River Memorandum, Clinton agreed to come to
the Middle East to speak on the peace plans to both Israelis and
Palestinians. He called on the youths to consider what future they
wanted and suggested that peace was the only alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, there have been setbacks; more misunderstandings,
more disagreements, more provocations, more acts of violence,'' the
president said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel Palestinians should prove in word and deed that their
intentions have actually changed, as you redeploy from land on
which tears and blood have been shed, and you are right to feel
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Palestinians feel you should acknowledge they too have
suffered and they too have legitimate expectations that should be
met and, like Israel, internal political pressure that must be
overcome. And they are right, too,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton visited
to the gravesite of former Prime Minister Yatzhak Rabin, who was
assassinated in 1995 by a Jewish extremist opposed to the peace
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton placed a smooth oval stone from the Wye River on Rabin's
tomb. Leah Rabin, the prime minister's widow and Hillary Clinton
placed flowers on the grave.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also lit a candle for the first night of Hannukah, the
Jewish festival of light, which began Sunday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 2152EST &QL; 
