<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7655 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-UPDATE-HNS &LR;      12-13 1408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-UPDATE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
CLINTON HAS `NO INTENTION' OF RESIGNING
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
By NANCY MATHIS &QL; 
and DAVID IVANOVICH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
JERUSALEM _ A grim-faced President Clinton said Sunday that he has
``no intention of resigning'' as the House prepares this week to
debate four articles of impeachment lodged against him.
</P>
<P>
   The president's adamant refusal to consider stepping down came
as the head of the House Judiciary Committee added his voice to
those calling for Clinton's resignation. Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill.,
said Sunday that resignation would be an honorable way to end the
11-month scandal and save the nation ``a lot of turmoil and
tumult.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Rep. Robert Livingston, R-La., has taken his most
significant step so far as the incoming speaker of the House by
declaring over the weekend his intentions to fight censure and to
vote to impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, appearing subdued as he fielded questions while
standing beside Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, said
resignation has ``never crossed my mind.'' And when asked directly
whether he would step down, Clinton said: ``I have no intention of
resigning.''
</P>
<P>
   The president also denied he committed perjury, which accounts
for two of the four charges against him, when he made misleading
testimony about his relationship with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, Netanyahu and their delegations spent more than two
hours discussing the troubled Middle East peace process on the eve
of Clinton's historic visit to Palestinian-controlled territories.
</P>
<P>
   But questions about impeachment and the sex scandal dominated
the news conference as Clinton also called on House members to
``vote their conscience'' and vowed not to lobby any members. And
he suggested that Republican leaders are refusing to allow a vote
on censure because they think it would pass.
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday will begin debate on articles of
impeachment for only the second time in American history. In 1868,
Andrew Johnson was impeached by the House but acquitted by the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment, a form of indictment, requires the Senate to hold a
trial to determine whether a president should be removed from
office. Following House Judiciary Committee action, Richard Nixon
resigned in 1973 rather than face impeachment by the House.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he was not surprised by the House Judiciary
Committee vote to forward four articles of impeachment to the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been obvious to anyone who is following it for
weeks that that vote was foreordained,'' Clinton said. ``And now it
is up to the members of the House of Representatives to vote their
conscience on the Constitution and the law, which I believe are
clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde urged Clinton to consider resignation as ``a quick and
radical solution to the dilemma that we have,'' in order to avoid
the impeachment vote and subsequent trial in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could really be heroic if he did that,'' Hyde said. ``He
would be the savior of his party. He would be welcomed around the
country at groups who would love to hear him speak. It would be a
way of going out with honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde was just one of a number of Republican lawmakers who fanned
out on the airwaves Sunday to call for Clinton's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just hope that the president would put the American
people ahead of his own ambitions and resign,'' House Majority Whip
Tom DeLay, R-Sugar Land, said on NBC's Meet the Press. Majority
Leader Dick Armey, R-Irving, appearing on Fox News Sunday, said if
he were in Clinton's predicament he would have resigned long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee Democrats and Clinton's attorneys maintained
the impeachment charges are unwarranted because, while the
president has admitted wrongdoing, the events to do not rise to the
level of removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's defenders called his answers to questions about his
relationship with Lewinsky misleading and maddening but steadfastly
maintained the president did not lie.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment counts charge Clinton with committing perjury
when he gave a deposition in the Paula Jones sexual harassment
lawsuit and when he testified before a grand jury. Clinton denied a
sexual relationship with Lewinsky, contending their affair did not
fit a definition of sex as provided by attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, especially moderate members who hold Clinton's fate
in their hands, have repeatedly called on him to drop his
legalistic answers and admit to lying under oath. The issue is
critical because the perjury articles are considered to have the
best chance of passage in the House.
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton said he has no intention of making such an
admission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer is, no, I can't do that because I did not commit
perjury,'' he said, pointing to arguments by White House Counsel
Charles Ruff and four former federal prosecutors who contend the
misleading statements made by the president do not qualify as
perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said those witnesses ``when through the law in great
detail and explained that this is not a perjury case. And there is
no credible argument on the other side. So I have no intention of
doing that. Now, was the testimony in the deposition difficult and
ambiguous and unhelpful? Yes, it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu attempted to help Clinton as he urged reporters to ask
questions about the peace process but to no avail. The White House
for weeks has limited Clinton's exposure to reporters. The
president last spoke on the issue on Friday as he again pronounced
his ``profound remorse'' for his actions and offered to accept a
censure as an appropriate punishment.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans, led by Speaker-elect Bob Livingston, R-La.,
are refusing to allow a censure resolution to be brought to the
floor as an alternative to impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you ought to ask them whether they're opposed to it
because they think it might pass, since, apparently, somewhere
around three-quarters of the American people think that's the right
thing to do,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., arguing
Republicans are ``obsessed'' with the notion of impeaching the
president, said on NBC's Meet the Press that Democrats on Capitol
Hill will push a procedural motion that will at least raise the
censure issue. But few Republicans, even those opposed to
impeachment, are likely to buck their party leadership and back the
Democrats on a procedural motion.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers insist a vote on impeachment can't be
dictated by the polls. ``Look, if Jesus Christ had taken a poll, he
would never have preached the gospel,'' Hyde said in an appearance
on ABC's This Week.
</P>
<P>
   The White House this weekend stepped up its efforts to get the
American public involved in the impeachment issue. Clinton
supporters contend people are busy with the holiday season and
unaware at how close Congress is to considering removing Clinton
from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the American people do have a say in this,'' said Joe
Lockhart, the White House spokesman. Referring to polls showing
most Americans oppose impeachment, Lockhart said that a ``small
group of people in the nation's capital ``are saying, `well, no, I
don't think the American people are right.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Craig, Clinton's lawyer, this weekend urged people to
call or write their lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told reporters Sunday that he would not be calling
members to lobby them to oppose impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a question of whether each member will simply vote his or
her conscience based on the Constitution and the law. I don't know
what's going to happen. That's up to them. It's out of my hands,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he would be available to any member who wants to
ask him questions but ``otherwise, I think it's important that they
be free to make this decision and that they not be put under any
undue pressure from any quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Several undecided Republicans said Sunday that Clinton had not
helped his cause by holding firm to the position that he did not
commit perjury.
</P>
<P>
   If the president had said publicly he committed perjury, ``it
would have helped us all,'' Rep. Jay Dickey, R-Ark. said on ABC's
This Week. ``It would have helped the nation for him to agree with
all of us that he did lie under oath.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Nancy Mathis contributed to this story from Jerusalem, and David
Ivanovich contributed from Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
