<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-UPDATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  Sunday, December 13, 1998
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Editors: &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SHUTTLE-UPDATE(Washington and Jersusalem) _ A story will move at 9
p.m., CDT, Sunday. By MARK CARREAU. Questions, call Jake Doherty at
713-220-7674. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 2157EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981213.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7661 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHUTTLE-UPDATE-HNS &LR;      12-13 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-UPDATE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
SHUTTLE CREW PREPARES FOR RETURN TO EARTH AFTER SUCCESSFUL MISSION
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By MARK CARREAU &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Feeling triumphant over their success at joining the
first components of the new international space station, the
Endeavour astronauts undocked from the fledgling outpost on Sunday
to prepare for their return to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The two components _ the $300 million, American-built Unity
module delivered by Endeavour and the $240 million, U.S.-financed,
Russian-developed Zarya module _ will circle the Earth uninhabited
until a shuttle crew returns with more equipment in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been an awesome experience,'' Endeavour commander Bob
Cabana told mission control. ``We've come a long way. We look
forward to seeing you build on this success.''
</P>
<P>
   Cabana supervised the shuttle's rendezvous with the already
orbiting Zarya module, the linkup of the two modules, three
spacewalks to distribute the electrical power, activate flight
control computers and install communications gear. He led an
American/Russian crew into the modules for the first time to
prepare them for future construction teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``This mission could not have gone any better,'' said Frank
Culbertson, NASA's space station program manager for operations.
``We've set a tremendous standard. It will be difficult to better
this mission, but we're going to have to try.''
</P>
<P>
   All told, the complete assembly of the new station will require
36 shuttle flights and nine Russian rocket launches over nearly six
years.
</P>
<P>
   With pilot Rick Sturckow at the controls, Endeavour was nudged
from the station's docking port on Sunday at 2:25 p.m., CST, as a
set of docking latches and springs between the two spacecraft were
released.
</P>
<P>
   For the next hour, he steered Endeavour in a graceful circle
around the outpost, allowing other shuttle crew members to film and
photograph it in detail from a distance of about 450 feet. NASA
engineers will scrutinize the imagery and use it to train future
assembly crews.
</P>
<P>
   With the operation complete, Cabana and Sturckow maneuvered
Endeavour slowly away.
</P>
<P>
   Endeavour is scheduled to land at the Kennedy Space Center in
Florida on Tuesday at 9:56 p.m., CST. Before returning to Earth,
the astronauts planned to deploy small experimental satellites
developed by Argentina and the U.S. Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   The station's first two modules now span a length of 76 feet
with a combined mass of about 35 tons. A pair of 38-foot solar
arrays for generating electricity jut from either side of the
Russian power and propulsion module, giving the complex a birdlike
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Following Endeavour's departure, ground control teams planned to
reorient the two modules into a stable, fuel efficient posture.
Unity will point to the center of the Earth and Zarya to deep space
as they sweep around the Earth at an altitude of 248 miles. The
modules will spin around their long axis once every 30 minutes to
regulate temperature variations.
</P>
<P>
   Once a week, ground controllers will reactivate Zarya's
propulsion system and update its guidance systems.
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling station will not have its own life support systems
and living quarters until the arrival of the already tardy Russian
service module. Russian economic difficulties have delayed its full
assembly and testing by 15 months, a factor that forced NASA to
postpone by a year its plans to begin the new station's orbital
construction with Endeavour's mission.
</P>
<P>
   Late this year, NASA funneled $60 million to the Russians in
exchange for more laboratory space on the new station to spur
completion of the service module. Currently slated for launching in
late July, the service module is undergoing testing and the
installation of final components at its production plant in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. confidence that the service module can successfully
complete its prelaunch, computer software testing has been
bolstered by the combined performance of the Zarya and Unity
modules, said Randy Brinkley, NASA's space station program manager.
The modules rely on an interplay of Russian software and American
flight control computers.
</P>
<P>
   If the service module's schedule holds, the station's first
resident crew, an American commander and two Russian cosmonauts,
should arrive in January 2000 for a three- to five-month stay.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, next year should be an active one for the new
station. NASA plans shuttle missions to the outpost in May, August,
October and December. Ten long spacewalks are planned to stow
equipment, check out the service module, add exterior truss work
and giant solar arrays to generate the electricity for a future
American laboratory module.
</P>
<P>
   The spacewalks and performance of the shuttle's robot arm will
be crucial to the success of those missions, just as they were on
Endeavour's
</P>
<P>
   Astronauts Jerry Ross, America's most experienced spacewalker
ever, and Jim Newman, conducted three successful spacewalks
spanning 21 hours, 22 minutes. Their efforts routed electrical
power from Zarya to Unity, afforded NASA's Mission Control Center
in Houston a vital satellite link and freed a pair of jammed
guidance system antennas on the Russian component.
</P>
<P>
   In all, an unprecedented 162 spacewalks will be needed to
construct an orbiting laboratory spanning an area equal to the size
of two football fields placed side-by-side. Sixteen countries are
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three down, 159 to go,'' said NASA's Greg Harbaugh, who
supervises the planning for the station's Extra-Vehicular Activity,
or spacewalk effort. Those involved consider the number of
spacewalks a wall that must be scaled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a great start,'' said Harbaugh. ``We certainly
have a long way to go. But so far, so good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 2201EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
