<SLUG> BC-PUERTORICO-VOTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATEHOOD BACKERS FALL SHORT IN PUERTO RICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODR I GUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN _ Statehood supporters, hoping to win a referendum that
would propel this island nation toward becoming the United States'
51st state, came out in full force Sunday but fell short of their
dream by about 4 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   With 99 percent of the votes counted, the ``none of the above''
option adopted by the procommonwealth Popular Party was ahead, with
50.2 percent, compared with 46.5 percent for statehood. Turnout was
high with more than 80 percent of the registered residents heading
to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar nonbinding referendum in 1993, commonwealth status
beat out statehood by 49 to 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Until last week, polls had shown statehood leading slightly, but
the Popular Party's campaign picked up momentum.
</P>
<P>
   The party had urged a ``none of the above'' vote because it
objected to the ballot's commonwealth description, which was
written by the statehood party and suggested Congress could revoke
Puerto Ricans' US citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has asked Congress to abide by the result of
the referendum, but it was unclear what kind of message a ``none of
the above'' victory would send to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the numbers, prostatehood Governor Pedro Rossello
insisted his cause had won. Standing before a crowd of tens of
thousands of flag-waving Puerto Ricans, Rossello said statehood was
victorious because ``none of the above'' is not a status option.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, it is clear that statehood won. Today, the people spoke
and they say they want a change.'' He said he would take the
results of the election to Washington, minus the votes for ``none
of the above.''
</P>
<P>
   His words sparked controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a travesty if he tries to bring Congress these
false figures,'' said former Governor Rafael Hernandez Colon, who
backs commonwealth status.
</P>
<P>
   Under such status, Puerto Rico is a US territory with local
autonomy. Its 3.9 million residents can't vote for president or
Congress, which alone can change Puerto Rico's political status.
</P>
<P>
   Voters trying to resolve the century-long debate on whether that
status ought to be changed also had the choices of independence or
a ``free association'' form of independence with US treaty ties.
Those options and a commonwealth as defined on the ballot garnered
about 3 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign for ``none of the above'' started slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello decided in September to hold a locally sponsored
plebescite, when it seemed that Congress would not authorize one.
</P>
<P>
   The Popular Party planned a boycott, but realizing that
statehood might win, pushed the government to include a fifth
choice for voters that said ``none of the above.'' Supporters of
independence joined forces with them, making it a multiparty
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The Popular Party spent a little more than $2 million on its
campaign, compared with about $10 million spent by the prostatehood
New Progressive Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the only way we could democratically participate,''
said Sila M. Calderon, mayor of San Juan who is a proponent of the
status quo. She said the ballot's definitions of the options were
confusing and contained wording that would scare people from voting
to remain a commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commonwealth is perfect for us,'' Calderon said. ``It gives us
a union with the US and allows us to maintain US citizenship, which
we cherish, but also allows us to maintain our own identity, our
fiscal autonomy, our language, and our Olympic team.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, nationalism is high among the residents of this tiny
Caribbean island.
</P>
<P>
   On a Sunday, when Puerto Ricans would normally spend their
morning in church, then watch sports on TV or play games with their
children, most people headed to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   They streamed into schools where they voted in booths that
resembled a bygone era, refrigerator-size cardboard boxes covered
by thin plastic curtains. There, they marked an ``X'' in pencil on
paper ballots.
</P>
<P>
   America Ortiz Vega, 58, a housewife who lives in San Juan, left
the polls at Sacred Heart University feeling positive that
statehood would lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been a commonwealth for 46 years and it's been good. Why
change it?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As she walked away, she bumped into a friend, ``Here I am, ready
to vote for column five,'' the friend said, flashing five fingers
for the ``none of the above'' option.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like the statehooders say. Statehood won't bring more
wealth to the island. American companies won't come here because
they will have to pay corporate taxes,'' said Olga Ramirez Muniz,
44, a secretary for the Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez was speaking of a congressional act that gives US
companies huge tax breaks for investing in Puerto Rico, but
Congress will phase out these tax breaks by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   As Ramirez spoke, a Toyota sped by with a procommonwealth poster
taped to the back window that read, ``Este pueblo se respeta'' _
this country we respect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
