<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7666 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-CLEMENS-HN     12-13 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CLEMENS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Toronto Blue Jays general manager Gord Ash said
trading Roger Clemens wouldn't be Rocket science; he didn't say
anything about Economics 101.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Astros could do without that lecture, and they decided they
could do without the five-time Cy Young Award winner if it meant
drastically altering the team's financial structure. General
manager Gerry Hunsicker officially put an end to the Astros'
participation in the Clemens sweepstakes by announcing Sunday that
the club has halted its pursuit of the 36-year-old righthander.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Astros and Blue Jays never reached an agreement on
players, the biggest deterrent to striking a deal was Clemens'
insistence on a restructured contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``This came from an official qualification from Roger's agent
that any trade involving Roger would necessitate a restructuring of
his current contract,'' Hunsicker said. ``Philosophically, we're
opposed to that, but more importantly, the agents did give us the
terms they would be looking for and we were shocked; we were just
stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a situation where it's hard enough agonizing over the
talent that you may have to give up to trade for a player like
this. But in addition, you have to restructure his contract as if
he were a free agent on the open market and pay him what the elite
pitchers who have just signed over the last month are commanding.
Economically, there's just no way that we can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources say Clemens, who already is under contract for $16.1
million over the next two seasons, asked for a new three-year deal
worth $43.5 million with a fourth-year vesting option worth an
additional $15 million. The deal called for a $12 million signing
bonus to be spread over the life of the contract, not to mention
the usual list of perks such as hotel suites when the team is on
the road, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker informed a gathering of national media members of the
Astros' intentions during a news conference Sunday at the baseball
winter meetings, an address that angered Clemens' agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's inappropriate and unprofessional,'' said Randy
Hendricks, one of Clemens' Houston-based representatives. ``For
them to respond to me through a news conference is third-rate and
unprofessional.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are believed to have been willing to part with
outfielder Derek Bell and righthanded pitcher Scott Elarton in a
package to acquire Clemens, but had they met Clemens' salary
demands, the club would have been forced to dump other
high-salaried players to stay within their budget.
</P>
<P>
   Said Hunsicker: ``Quite frankly, I think Roger would agree _ if
he understood what we'd have to do to make room for him _ even
after trading away the talent to secure his services, he wouldn't
be happy with the team we would be left with. Unfortunately, this
looks like the end of the Houston Astros' involvement in attempting
to trade for Roger Clemens.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who has won back-to-back Cy Youngs and American League
pitching triple crowns, asked the Blue Jays to trade him earlier
this month based on a handshake agreement with former team
president Paul Beeston, who told Clemens he would trade him if the
pitcher no longer viewed the club as a contender.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 12 teams originally expressed interest in Clemens,
but the number had dwindled to five as recently as Friday. Some
clubs were turned off by the fact they had to not only reach an
agreement with the Blue Jays on players but also strike a new deal
with Clemens' agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unusual,'' Hunsicker said. ``Philosophically, we're
opposed to this, because this is a player who is already under
contract, and we're attempting to trade for that player. In
addition to that, the player is suggesting that he also must have
his contract restructured. That's the first time I've ever been
involved in something like that, and quite frankly, I can't think
of another circumstance that I can remember where this has
happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you compete for someone's services in the free-agent
market, you understand the parameters; it's an open market, and you
can choose to compete or not to compete. When you're trying to
trade for a player, it normally comes down to whether you can
satisfy the club that currently has his services. But this has
become a combination of both; it's kind of like having your cake
and eating it, too. You're not a free agent, but you want to be
treated like a free agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Having found it too costly to acquire a proven No. 1 pitcher _
the Astros also pulled out of the running for Randy Johnson (four
years, $52.4 million from the Diamondbacks) last month _ the Astros
likely will enter next season with their current cast of players.
Hunsicker added All-Star third baseman Ken Caminiti earlier this
offseason, and he hopes to shore up the bullpen with a righthanded
reliever and bolster the bench with another righthanded hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been a very magical moment if we could have made
this trade, but I had a lot of misgivings about what we were going
to have to give up,'' said Astros manager Larry Dierker, whose
highest annual salary as a player was $130,000. ``It's not really
bothering me too much from a competitive standpoint that we keep
the players that we were going to trade and that we don't have
Roger, because I still think we're going to have a very good club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a little disappointed that we got this far down the
road and kind of got our hopes up and that the money issues were
going to be so dramatic and have such an impact on us that we just
couldn't make any sense out of it. It's one thing, I guess, if
you're the Yankees, but we're already headed for over-budget land
even without him (Clemens). I think we have a chance to win our
division, and I think we have a chance to get into the playoffs
again.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Clemens, the deep-pocketed Rangers and Yankees would
appear to have the best chance of satisfying his demands, along
with the Orioles and Rockies _ two teams that missed out on their
chance to sign a No. 1 starter when Kevin Brown brokered a
seven-year, $105 million contract with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to find out in the days and weeks to come what
kind of power he (Clemens) has,'' Dierker said. ``There may be some
teams that are better contenders than the Blue Jays that will also
meet these terms. But you're reducing the potential teams down to a
very small number, and I think the Blue Jays might have a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Later on Sunday, Ash said: ``There has been a lot of interest in
Clemens since (the Astros' news conference). A lot of clubs thought
it was a foregone conclusion that he would wind up in Houston, and
they were just sitting back and waiting to see what happened. Roger
has demanded a trade, but that doesn't mean I have to trade him for
two cans of Diet Coke.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
