<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SYSTEM IN CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Now begins one of the gravest tests of the American
political system and of the men and women who occupy positions of
public trust.
</P>
<P>
   With the support of lawmakers from only one party, the House
Judiciary Committee is sending to the House floor four resolutions
to impeach the president of the other party, imperiling not only
President Clinton but also the ancient assumptions that so often
have kept Congresses in the past from resorting to this fateful
step.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the president and the Congress together are
exposing the entire political system to enormous danger.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the House Judiciary Committee has finished its work,
the strains the president put on the system _ his willingness to
have a sexual affair with an intern and then to maneuver to hide it
_ are being joined by strains the Congress is putting on the system
by pushing forward with impeachment in a highly partisan fashion.
</P>
<P>
   For a political system formed in a public revolt in the 18th
century and dependent on public consent to survive through the 21st
century, this is a situation of considerable risk.
</P>
<P>
   While scholars and commentators are viewing the contention in
the capital as a constitutional crisis, a titanic struggle between
branches of government, this year-end struggle is thrusting
Washington to the brink of a broader political crisis, one brewing
for years that has been muted recently only by the beguiling
background music of a robust economy.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when public impatience with Washington is at alarming
levels, Republican lawmakers are pushing Congress to take a step
the public opposes in response to presidential comportment the
public deplores.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's votes finally stripped from the proceedings the
personalities, the points of order and personal privilege, the
haggling over language, the disputes over due process, and revealed
the challenge that Clinton and the Republican Congress have hurled
at the political system that has sustained and rewarded them all.
</P>
<P>
   In an age when public alienation can be measured to
decimal-point authority, when the charcoal line that separates
public lives from private concerns has been smudged, when the
intrusive light of the media is shined into the darkest corner,
Washington is taking an extraordinary gamble. By a ratio of 2 to 1,
Americans believe the House Judiciary Committee has not paid enough
attention to what the American people think about impeachment,
according to a Newsweek poll being published in its editions
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can feel the anger pulsating at what Congress is doing,''
says Susan J. Tolchin, a George Mason University professor of
public policy who has written a book about public alienation from
politics. ``And though the American people are pretty slow to boil,
they may get very, very angry. The great public alienation appears
not to trouble either the Congress or the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's misdeeds, in the White House with Monica S.
Lewinsky and twice in sworn testimony, are, as Republican
Representative Bill McCollum of Florida put it, an
``extraordinarily serious matter,'' one that undermines public
trust in Washington at a critical time. But the public is also
telling Washington that proceeding with impeachment will be
remembered in history, as Democratic Representative Charles E.
Schumer of New York put it, ``as something that America is not
proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment is a serious remedy, reserved for serious maladies
in the system. It has been contemplated seriously only three times,
and this is the first time it is being considered amid worries that
the remedy may itself contribute to the malady.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily lawmakers are chary of even tossing around the notion
of impeaching a president. Fifteen years ago, Representative Mickey
Leland, a maverick Democrat from Texas and ferocious critic of
President Ronald Reagan, asked the House to impeach Reagan for
ordering the invasion of Grenada. A day later, House Speaker Thomas
P. O'Neill of Massachusetts, who had played a critical role in
bringing Richard M. Nixon to the brink of impeachment in 1974, took
Leland aside and told him ``how we handle matters when we are in
disagreement with the president _ how it is that you don't respond
by trying to impeach the president on matters like this.''
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the White House sex scandal, Democratic
Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York used the phrase
``crisis of the regime.'' It was a reference to the president's
behavior with the onetime intern and to the White House's effort to
thwart the investigation of independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr.
Now, with the House only days from an impeachment vote on the
floor, that crisis has spread. The crisis of the regime has become
a crisis of the entire system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
