<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7675 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      12-13 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT ASSERTS HE BROKE NO LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER   AND CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, speaking even as Republican
lawmakers said he might spare himself from impeachment if he
confessed to perjury, said Sunday he had not broken the law and so
he could not admit to doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not commit perjury. ... I could not admit to doing
something that I am quite sure I did not do,'' Clinton said during
a news conference in Jerusalem, where he is trying to revive the
stalled Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The president also said he would not resign, even if the House
votes later this week to send impeachment charges to the Senate.
His comments came as a leading Republican, Representative Henry
Hyde, chairman of the House panel that approved impeachment charges
against Clinton last week, called on the president to step down,
and House majority whip Tom DeLay said Clinton should ``consider''
leaving office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no intention of resigning,'' Clinton said. ``It's never
crossed my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Without invoking his name, the president also took aim at
Republican Representative Bob Livingston, speaker-elect of the
House, for announcing that he would fight a Democratic effort to
censure Clinton rather than impeach him. Under the Constitution,
Livingston said Saturday, the House may impeach or not impeach the
president, but it has no authority to censure.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton suggested that House leaders oppose censure ``because
they think that it might pass, since apparently somewhere around
three-quarters of the American people think that's the right thing
to do.'' A vote of censure would allow the House to condemn
Clinton's behavior without moving to eject him from office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton commented on impeachment at a joint appearance with
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, where the Israeli leader
met little success in urging reporters to set aside impeachment and
``to ask one or two questions on the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Clinton's first press conference since the House
Judiciary Committee voted Friday and Saturday to send impeachment
charges to the full House, and it marked the second time since
Friday that Clinton spoke publicly about the charges while turning
aside Republican pleas that he admit to perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four impeachment charges approved by the Judiciary panel,
one accuses Clinton of lying in a civil deposition about his
relationship with Monica S. Lewinsky, and one accuses him of lying
to a grand jury about the affair. The two others charge the
president with obstructing justice and misusing the powers of his
office to interfere with witnesses and investigators in the
Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   As the House prepares to vote on impeachment as early as
Thursday, Clinton's fate rests with 20 or so Republican lawmakers
who are undecided on whether to approve the charges, sending them
to the Senate for trial. Some of those lawmakers said Sunday that
Clinton's refusal to admit to perjury might give them a reason to
vote for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president hurt himself very clearly this
morning,'' said Representative Bob Ney, Republican of Ohio,
referring to Clinton's comments in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not getting leadership from the White House. If it is,
it's negative leadership,'' said Representative Jay Dickey,
Republican of Arkansas, who appeared with Ney on the ABC television
program ``This Week.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, who has said he will vote for impeachment, said some
Republicans would vote against impeachment if only Clinton ``would
say the magic words that he did lie to the grand jury.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are some Republicans who would feel different if
he were to admit to his wrongdoing. ... It's hard to forgive
somebody when they don't admit they've done wrong,'' Hyde said on
the CBS program ``Face the Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde also called on Clinton to resign in order to end the
impeachment process. ``He could really be heroic if he did that,''
Hyde said. ``He would be the savior of his party. He would be
welcomed around the country at groups who would love to hear him
speak. It would be a way of going out with honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Delay, who as whip is responsible for counting votes for the
House Republican leadership, said that the upcoming vote ``is too
close to call'' and ``could be a 50-50 chance for impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   While the White House has encouraged business executives and
political allies to call undecided lawmakers on the president's
behalf, both Clinton and DeLay said they were not directly lobbying
House members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have talked to those _ a few _ who said they wanted to talk
to me,'' Clinton said in Jerusalem. ``Otherwise, I have not. I
don't think it's appropriate for me to be personally calling
people, unless they send word to me that there is something they
want to ask or something they want to say.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said he had given ``difficult and ambiguous and
unhelpful'' testimony in a deposition connected to the Paula Jones
sexual harassment suit,but that the House Judiciary Committee was
wrong in finding on Friday that his words amounted to perjury. He
noted that four legal experts who testified on his behalf before
the committee, two of them Republicans, agreed that he had not
committed perjury.
</P>
<P>
   In an odd coincidence of history, President Richard M. Nixon
visited Israel just one month before the House Judiciary Committee
voted on articles of impeachment against him in 1974. Like
Clinton's visit, Nixon's was meant to promote the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   There are profound differences between the Clinton and Nixon
visits. Nixon's fate was essentially sealed when he came to Israel,
and Clinton's clearly is not. But Hemi Shalev, a columnist for
Ma'ariv newspaper, cited a statement made by the late Israeli Prime
Minister Golda Meir during Nixon's visit that could be said of
Clinton today:
</P>
<P>
   ``The president was here, but his thoughts were very far away.''
</P>
<P>
   During his news conference Sunday, Clinton promised a ``prompt''
decision on whether to free Jonathan Pollard, a former US Navy
intelligence analyst who pleaded guilty in 1986 to spying for
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, during peace talks in Maryland, Netanyahu had asked
for leniency for Pollard, who is serving a life sentence. Clinton
promised to review the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have instituted the review that I pledged to the prime
minister,'' Clinton said Sunday. He said he had instructed White
House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff to seek the advice of all relevant
intelligence and security agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu said that Pollard is serving ``a very, very heavy
sentence, and since he was sent by us on a mission ... we hope that
on a purely humanitarian appeal a way will be found to release
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
