<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-STARLET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEETING A GENUINE STARLET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The best 2-year-olds in the prolific Bob
Baffert barn might be a pair of fillies.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Excellent Meeting, ridden by Kent Desormeaux, won the
$400,000 Hollywood Starlet by eight lengths, just missing the
record for the 1 1/16-mile stakes and becoming the first to sweep
the major 2-year-old filly races at Del Mar, Santa Anita and
Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   John and Betty Mabee's Excellent Meeting laid claim to the
national division championship that's expected to go to Mike
Pegram's Silverbulletday, who beat her in the Breeders' Cup
Juvenile Fillies at Churchill Downs after running fourth behind her
at Del Mar.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are just two exceptional fillies,'' said Baffert,
declining to take sides.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert hopes 2-year-old colts Exploit and Prime Timber will get
him to the May 1 Kentucky Derby, which he won the past two years.
But he concedes the fillies are ahead of the colts because they're
better seasoned.
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday is 6 for 7 after racing mostly in Kentucky in
1998. Excellent Meeting is 4 for 7 after her dominating victory
over front-running Lacquaria in the Starlet.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent Meeting ($3) was clocked at 1:42.14, about one-fifth
of a second slower than Serena's Song's winning time in 1994.
Serena's Song _ who went on to earn the 3-year-old fillies'
championship _ had been the only winner of Santa Anita's Oak Leaf
Stakes to also take the Starlet.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert's first Starlet victory came a day after he watched Hal
Earnhardt's Premier Property suffer a fatal breakdown following the
colt's third-place finish in the Hollywood Futurity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You not only feel for the horse, you feel for the owner,''
Baffert said. ``The next day, I win the Starlet; I've got other
horses. But for (Earnhardt), he had a nice horse, he had his family
here, he's dreaming of traveling and seeing the horse run, and then
suddenly that's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Sunday, Corey Nakatani rallied Tuzla ($3.20) from an
unaccustomed last between horses and wore down Sonja's Faith and
Emile Ramsammy to win the $100,000 Dahlia Handicap, making the
filly 4 for 4 on the Hollywood Park turf.
</P>
<P>
   Tuzla's owner, television writer-producer David Milch, was asked
which of his ``NYPD Blues'' characters the winner of 8 of 15 is
like.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a lot prettier than Sipowicz, but she shows the (same)
trait that she keeps on coming,'' Milch said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: As the meet's final, six-day week begins Wednesday,
Garrett Gomez will lead the jockeys by two wins (over Alex Solis)
and Neil Drysdale will lead the trainers by three (over seven
others). . . . Mass Cap and Hollywood Gold Cup runnerup Puerto
Madero is expected to head the Native Diver Handicap Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 2224EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981213.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7679 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-     12-13 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
LIKE Mike Tyson, life bites. This is our profound thought for the
holidays.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the most complicated negotiation of the gift-giving season,
the Astros might have met Toronto's price, and they might have met
Roger Clemens' price, but not both.
</P>
<P>
   So the Astros, once thought to be the hometown favorite in this
auction, withdrew Sunday from the bidding for the five-time Cy
Young Award winner. There are many ways to look at this
development, none of them happily.
</P>
<P>
   As fans, we are disillusioned. Isn't home where the heart is?
Isn't love supposed to find a way? Roger loves Houston; he lives
here. He grew up in the neighborhood, educating his fastball at San
Jacinto College and the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And the Astros, politely dabbing at the drool on their chin,
surely wanted to bring Clemens home again. But think of Toronto as
the in-laws, looking for a hefty dowry. Think of Alan and Randy
Hendricks, his Houston-based agents, as Roger's guardians, whose
goal is to provide security for future generations of the Clemens
clan.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Roger won 20 games with only six losses for the Blue
Jays and for the 10th time since 1986 struck out more than 200
batters. No pitcher in either league has been so dominant for so
long. He is powerful enough to fire the ballclub for failing to
make the moves necessary to qualify as a contender.
</P>
<P>
   You can see the fans choosing sides. The Astros are disenchanted
that Roger required a raise above his present $8 million salary to
pitch in a stadium 30 minutes from his house. Some fans will
wonder, ``How can Houston bid for the Olympics but not afford Roger
Clemens?''
</P>
<P>
   As Daisy said to a lovesick Jay Gatsby, ``Haven't you heard?
Rich girls don't marry poor boys.'' (Gatsby hit it big, but Daisy
didn't wait.)
</P>
<P>
   In material things, the Astros were poor once. But they have won
their division two seasons in a row, and year after next they move
into their palatial new digs on the right side of the railroad
tracks. Still, you never forget how it felt to be poor, surviving
on a low-revenue team's budget.
</P>
<P>
   So a perfect match doesn't get made, and the Rocket will take
his Hall of Fame talent to another town. This assumes, of course,
that there is a club out there that can give up the package of
players the Blue Jays want and pay Clemens the going rate for a
franchise pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible this is what Toronto had in mind all along? Its
best shot at keeping Roger is to price him out of the market. Based
on the talent it is said to be demanding in return, Toronto wants
to become a separate country. The money is altogether another
issue.
</P>
<P>
   The bar was not only raised but launched into orbit when Arizona
signed Randy Johnson and the Dodgers hooked Kevin Brown. These
contracts were so humongous, they changed the language. When
players talk about Randy Johnson money, they mean a contract
averaging $13 million a year. Of course, this amount is trumped by
Kevin Brown money, $15 million per.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros were willing to go as high as $11 million for Johnson
because doing so did not involve giving up Christmas. They had
acquired Randy in a midsummer deal for three minor-leaguers, and no
other players would be involved.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Johnson signed with the Diamondbacks, who lost 97
games in their first season. As they say, winning isn't everything.
Randy's home is in Phoenix, and so were the millions. Two out of
three isn't bad.
</P>
<P>
   No team likes to see a big one get away. But Clemens represents
a deeper hurt because he provides more than wins and strikeouts and
box office. Without a doubt, he would have been treated as family,
Nolan Ryan with a temper.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, the year he won his first Cy Young Award, Roger led the
majors with 24 wins, was the winning pitcher in the All-Star Game
and carried the Red Sox into the World Series. In 1990, he became
the first pitcher ever to be ejected from a playoff game when he
expressed his disapproval of a missed call in terms that offended
umpire Terry Cooney.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he was talking to himself, as he often does, letting
off steam. If he cursed, at least initially, he did so in a generic
way. What he said to Cooney, several witnesses testified, was:
``I'm not (expletive deleted) talking to you. Keep your (expletive
deleted) mask on.'' But Cooney jawed back, and the dialogue quickly
went downhill from there.
</P>
<P>
   With a lineup that included Mark McGwire and Jose Canseco, the
Oakland A's swept the Red Sox in four games without hitting a home
run. This is greatness.
</P>
<P>
   After an investigation by the commissioner's office, including
testimony by a lip reader, Roger received a short suspension at the
start of the next season and a $10,000 fine. No one ever denied
that Clemens is a competitor. How sad that he won't be competing in
his hometown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 2225EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981213.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7682 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-     12-13 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
LIKE Mike Tyson, life bites. This is our profound thought for the
holidays.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the most complicated negotiation of the gift-giving season,
the Astros might have met Toronto's price, and they might have met
Roger Clemens' price, but not both.
</P>
<P>
   So the Astros, once thought to be the hometown favorite in this
auction, withdrew Sunday from the bidding for the five-time Cy
Young Award winner. There are many ways to look at this
development, none of them happily.
</P>
<P>
   As fans, we are disillusioned. Isn't home where the heart is?
Isn't love supposed to find a way? Roger loves Houston; he lives
here. He grew up in the neighborhood, educating his fastball at San
Jacinto College and the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And the Astros, politely dabbing at the drool on their chin,
surely wanted to bring Clemens home again. But think of Toronto as
the in-laws, looking for a hefty dowry. Think of Alan and Randy
Hendricks, his Houston-based agents, as Roger's guardians, whose
goal is to provide security for future generations of the Clemens
clan.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Roger won 20 games with only six losses for the Blue
Jays and for the 10th time since 1986 struck out more than 200
batters. No pitcher in either league has been so dominant for so
long. He is powerful enough to fire the ballclub for failing to
make the moves necessary to qualify as a contender.
</P>
<P>
   You can see the fans choosing sides. The Astros are disenchanted
that Roger required a raise above his present $8 million salary to
pitch in a stadium 30 minutes from his house. Some fans will
wonder, ``How can Houston bid for the Olympics but not afford Roger
Clemens?''
</P>
<P>
   As Daisy said to a lovesick Jay Gatsby, ``Haven't you heard?
Rich girls don't marry poor boys.'' (Gatsby hit it big, but Daisy
didn't wait.)
</P>
<P>
   In material things, the Astros were poor once. But they have won
their division two seasons in a row, and year after next they move
into their palatial new digs on the right side of the railroad
tracks. Still, you never forget how it felt to be poor, surviving
on a low-revenue team's budget.
</P>
<P>
   So a perfect match doesn't get made, and the Rocket will take
his Hall of Fame talent to another town. This assumes, of course,
that there is a club out there that can give up the package of
players the Blue Jays want and pay Clemens the going rate for a
franchise pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible this is what Toronto had in mind all along? Its
best shot at keeping Roger is to price him out of the market. Based
on the talent it is said to be demanding in return, Toronto wants
to become a separate country. The money is altogether another
issue.
</P>
<P>
   The bar was not only raised but launched into orbit when Arizona
signed Randy Johnson and the Dodgers hooked Kevin Brown. These
contracts were so humongous, they changed the language. When
players talk about Randy Johnson money, they mean a contract
averaging $13 million a year. Of course, this amount is trumped by
Kevin Brown money, $15 million per.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros were willing to go as high as $11 million for Johnson
because doing so did not involve giving up Christmas. They had
acquired Randy in a midsummer deal for three minor-leaguers, and no
other players would be involved.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Johnson signed with the Diamondbacks, who lost 97
games in their first season. As they say, winning isn't everything.
Randy's home is in Phoenix, and so were the millions. Two out of
three isn't bad.
</P>
<P>
   No team likes to see a big one get away. But Clemens represents
a deeper hurt because he provides more than wins and strikeouts and
box office. Without a doubt, he would have been treated as family,
Nolan Ryan with a temper.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, the year he won his first Cy Young Award, Roger led the
majors with 24 wins, was the winning pitcher in the All-Star Game
and carried the Red Sox into the World Series. In 1990, he became
the first pitcher ever to be ejected from a playoff game when he
expressed his disapproval of a missed call in terms that offended
umpire Terry Cooney.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he was talking to himself, as he often does, letting
off steam. If he cursed, at least initially, he did so in a generic
way. What he said to Cooney, several witnesses testified, was:
``I'm not (expletive deleted) talking to you. Keep your (expletive
deleted) mask on.'' But Cooney jawed back, and the dialogue quickly
went downhill from there.
</P>
<P>
   With a lineup that included Mark McGwire and Jose Canseco, the
Oakland A's swept the Red Sox in four games without hitting a home
run. This is greatness.
</P>
<P>
   After an investigation by the commissioner's office, including
testimony by a lip reader, Roger received a short suspension at the
start of the next season and a $10,000 fine. No one ever denied
that Clemens is a competitor. How sad that he won't be competing in
his hometown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
