<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NO ALTERNATIVE' TO PEACE, CLINTON TELLS YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; JERUSALEM _ President Clinton chose an audience of high school
students to deliver a stern message Sunday on the need for both
Israelis and Palestinians to implement the imperiled peace process.
</P>
<P>
   And in Clintonian fashion, with Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu of Israel listening at his side, he spoke to the young
people in their own language about the benefits of peace.
</P>
<P>
   He began by painting a bleak picture of an Israel under
``permanent siege,'' with a ``gnawing anxiety'' as it ``remains
preoccupied with its very survival.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the students, ``Perhaps you can live with that kind
of future, but you should not accept it unless you are willing to
say _ and I will try to say it properly _ ``ein breirah'' _ there
is no alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hebrew phrase has been a kind of rallying cry that Israeli
leaders have used through decades of conflict with the nation's
Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Then Clinton added, ``But if you are unwilling to give up on
hope with no real gain in security, you must say ``yesh breirah'' _
`yes, there is an alternative.'''
</P>
<P>
   The students, a cross-section of a divided society, burst into
applause. Conservatively dressed religious students from Jerusalem,
secular Israelis with pierced noses and spandex from Tel Aviv, and
neatly dressed youths from the suburbs gave him a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   After the speech, Ohad Shiron, 18, from the sprawling suburban
housing complex of Mevasarett, said: ``It gave us hope and gave us
a way to see that we are the future. If we want peace we have to
change attitudes, not just follow leaders who sign pieces of
paper.''
</P>
<P>
   In the half-hour address to the students at the Jerusalem
Convention Center, Clinton sold the benefits of peace, saying it
would lead to economic prosperity and a secure future for Israelis
and Palestinians. He stressed that ``the United States will always
stand with Israel.'' But Clinton also emphasized that both sides
must live up to the commitments made at the Wye River Plantation in
Maryland in October.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's three-day visit was initially intended to celebrate
the interim land-for-security deal worked out at Wye.
</P>
<P>
   But it has become a personal and historic mission to save the
Wye agreement. Escalating street violence by Palestinian
demonstrators, and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's repeated
assertions that he would unilaterally declare a Palestinian state
in May, prompted Netanyahu to issue an ultimatum suspending an
implementation agreement. Netanyahu has said he would cede no more
West Bank land until Arafat stated that he would not unilaterally
declare a state.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to visit Palestinian Authority-controlled Gaza
today, marking the first time a US president has set foot in
Palestinian territory. He is to oversee a reaffirmation of the 1996
Palestinian National Council vote to annul parts of the founding
charter that call for the destruction of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   As a crush of young people pushed toward Clinton after the
speech, Karen Halperin, 17, who described herself as being from a
``very religious family'' from Jerusalem, said she was inspired by
Clinton's ``beautiful words.''
</P>
<P>
   But as she watched the young people clamoring to shake hands
with Clinton, she said: ``I don't think peace is possible. As long
as they'' _ the Palestinians _ ``are committed to killing us, and
talk about Israel as if it has no right to exist, I don't think we
will see peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's speech stood in stark contrast to a preceding one by
Netanyahu, who adopted a lecturing tone, offering what he called
``an education for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The speeches differed more than in tone. They seemed to
underscore the differences between the two leaders, whose
relationship has been strained in the past. The Clinton
administration openly favored former Prime Minister Shimon Peres in
the 1996 election, which he lost to Netanyahu. And Clinton's visit
Sunday to the grave of the slain prime minister, Yitzhak Rabin,
where he placed a stone from the Wye River, was a reminder of how
closely the two had worked together to achieve the 1993 Oslo
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Netanyahu had warm words Sunday about the ``special
relationship'' between the United States and Israel. But the
political careers of both men are at stake, and to some extent the
further implementation of Wye will affect them in opposite ways.
Success in moving on peace would help Clinton's image back home.
Hard-liners in Netanyahu's coalition are threatening to bring down
his government if he cedes more West Bank land, as called for.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu said that Israel must receive a guarantee that the
Palestinians will live up to their end of the Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In speaking to the students, Netanyahu's phrases about ``our
counterparts,'' as he referred to the Palestinians, were spiked
with images of fear. He described Palestinian textbooks that did
not include the state of Israel in maps of the region. He told the
students: ``Palestinians go to Tel Aviv freely.'' But he asked
them, ominously. ``Can one of you enter Gaza?''
</P>
<P>
   Hani Sand, 17, from Jerusalem, said, ``I think Clinton was
talking to us to help his political future. And I think Netanyahu
was talking to the Knesset to help his political future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 2235EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981213.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7691 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-BREAST-IMPLANTS-     12-13 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BREAST-IMPLANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SCIENCE OF SILICONE IMPLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Dec. 14:
</P>
<P>
   A court-appointed panel of experts has concluded that existing
scientific evidence does not show a link between silicone breast
implants and systemic disease.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Judge Sam Pointer Jr., who is overseeing breast-implant
lawsuits in the federal courts, convened the panel to advise him on
medical evidence surrounding implants. His approach was unusual in
that he sought expert testimony independent of either side in the
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy may also be useful in other complex cases where
juries and judges are forced to choose between battling experts who
may be biased.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers from both sides will now have the opportunity to
question the expert panelists in depositions and to use that
testimony in implant trials. The findings should make trials
somewhat easier to conduct, and may cause more plaintiffs to settle
their claims against the implant manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Well before the panel's report, thousands of cases had been
settled. Last month, Dow Corning Corp., once the leading maker of
silicone implants, and representatives of implant plaintiffs
formally agreed to a plan that will pay some 170,000 claimants $3.2
billion over 15 years for suffering and the costs of implant
removal. Both sides decided that it was better financially to make
a deal than to fight out the science in court.
</P>
<P>
   The new report, which will not affect that settlement, puts
forward solid conclusions based on multiple studies. But the
panel's findings do not represent the last word on implant safety.
A National Cancer Institute study of 13,500 women who have had
implants is looking at the long-term health impacts. Results from
that study will not be available until next year.
</P>
<P>
   A panel convened by the Institute of Medicine, an arm of the
National Academy of Sciences, is also continuing to review the
medical evidence. The report from Pointer's panel shows how much is
known. Other scientists are still researching aspects of implants
that are not yet known.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 2235EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981213.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7692 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-BOS &LR;      12-13 0912
