<SLUG> BC-CONN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT OFFICIALS SAY DEAL REACHED ON PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD _ Moving ever closer to providing a new home for the
New England Patriots, Connecticut Governor John G. Rowland and six
ranking legislative leaders Sunday said they had reached an
agreement on the terms of a $375 million stadium financing deal.
</P>
<P>
   All predicted the General Assembly will approve the deal
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Their renewed confidence hung on new language in the proposal,
which will make it even tougher for the Patriots to leave
Connecticut and decrease the state's exposure on premium seating
guarantees by $4 million annually. After reviewing those details,
Rowland and the legislators emerged from the Governor's Mansion and
said the deal is largely done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all standing here, our bipartisan leadership, in total
agreement on this stadium proposal, in total agreement on the
legislation that we will present,'' Rowland said. ``We all have a
proposal now that we can move forward with, and I think it's going
to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic legislators _ including House Speaker Thomas D.
Ritter of Hartford, Senate President Pro Tem Kevin B. Sullivan of
West Hartford, and even a stubborn skeptic, House Majority Leader
Moira Lyons of Stamford _ echoed the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased with the changes, I think they have been
significant changes,'' said Lyons, making her first announcement
that she will vote in favor of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am usually skeptical about making predictions, but, for the
first time today, I think I feel confident that it will pass in the
Senate,'' said Sullivan. ``I think that what we can say to our
colleagues is that we listened to them, we took their issues back
to the conversation and got results. More importantly, what our
colleagues can say to their constituents is that we listened to
you, too, and we made the changes you need to see in this deal to
make it best for Connecticut.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Patriots owner Robert Kraft and his son Jonathan were
not available for comment Sunday, because of the team's upset loss
to the St. Louis Rams and the beginning of Hanukkah, Rowland said
they were in agreement with the changes.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said the new provisions resulted from ``concessions
and agreements with the Kraft family and the team,'' and that he
had merely informed Robert Kraft of the positive response of
legislators in a 10-minute telephone call to St. Louis Sunday
during the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very pleased with the response of the Krafts in allaying
our concerns,'' Rowland said. ``Many expected us to come to some
movement on the guarantees and we have done so, which makes this
product a lot more palatable to the legislators on Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   In a proposed bill released last week, Kraft and the Patriots
would have been bound to Connecticut for the duration of a 30-year
lease on the new stadium through a legal declaration that moving
the team would have presented an ``irreparable harm'' to the state,
for which it could not be compensated by money or any other means.
Rowland's office and legislative staff saw the so-called exit
provisions as ironclad, essentially laying out a legally
enforceable position from which the Patriots could not withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland and the legislative leaders announced Sunday that the
bill will now call on the Patriots to pay the state for all of the
benefits the team has received and the state has derived from the
stadium if the Krafts ever sell the team or leave the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to make sure that the taxpayers' interest was
protected over the next 30 years should the Patriots decide to
leave, and the exit agreement is very, very stiff,'' Rowland said.
``If they were to leave in any way, shape or form, or sell the
team, the penalty for them would be the total value or total
benefit to the state. So that runs up into the hundreds and
hundreds of million dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill also had formulated state guarantees for luxury boxes
and club seats that would have essentially required the state to
pay for some of the premium seating that the Patriots could not
sell.
</P>
<P>
   The state's maximum exposure over the first 10 years of the
agreement was $17.5 million per year, and Rowland said Sunday that
the Patriots had been provided with language that could have
extended some of the guarantees over the 30 years. Those guarantees
made the deal one of the most lucrative offered to an NFL owner,
and they have been among the provisions most criticized by the
legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland and the legislative leaders said Sunday that they had
agreed with Kraft to lower the total annual exposure to $13
million.
</P>
<P>
   Under the first draft of the bill and the memorandum of
understanding Rowland and Kraft signed on Nov. 19, the state would
have been responsible for 4,000 of the 6,000 club seats at 50
percent of the $5,000 price tag . Connecticut also would have been
responsible for the full cost of 75 of the 125 to 150 luxury
suites, which are to sell at $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   As reported in the Globe Sunday, the final bill will reduce the
cost of the club seats to $4,000. That reduces the state's exposure
by $2 million per year, Rowland and the legislative leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   The state will now guarantee only 50 percent of the cost of the
last 75 to 100 luxury suites for sale, a savings of $2.5 million on
the potential cost of the guarantee, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is going to be very helpful to legislators who
were either on the fence or perhaps wanted to vote for this plan
but felt that the guarantees were too much of a risk for the
state,'' Rowland said.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Patriots could have imposed the guarantees over the
lifetime of the lease, Rowland said, the potential savings to the
state are substantial.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at it over a period of 30 years, if you look at
the inflation and the increase of the ticket prices over 30 years,
that reduces the exposure of the guarantees by as much as $350
million,'' Rowland said.
</P>
<P>
   The legislators met with Rowland and some members of his staff
for about four hours Sunday before announcing the agreement. All
said they will speak to their Democratic and Republican caucuses,
and will push today for approval of the bill in its new form.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 2243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981213.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
