A7704 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-OFFICE-LADN     12-13 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST `TREK' VOYAGE BEAMS INTO FIRST PLACE AT BOX OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- ``Star Trek: Insurrection'' vaporized the
competition at the nation's multiplexes as it dominated the U.S.
box office with an estimated $22.4 million at 2,620 theaters during
the Friday-Sunday period, studio sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The results gave ``Insurrection'' the third-highest opening
among the nine ``Trek'' films, trailing 1996's $30.7 million debut
for ``First Contact'' and 1994's $23 million start for
``Generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Prospects look respectable for the Paramount project, set on a
fountain-of-youth planet with the cast of the ``Star Trek: The Next
Generation'' TV series, with a final gross of $78 million,
according to Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source
service.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Insurrection' will stay in the top 10 for quite a while,''
Bucksbaum said. ``It's getting positive word of mouth, critics
liked it and it has a softer feel so it may draw more women than
usual.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The `Star Trek' franchise is still solid,'' said film industry
analyst Arthur Rockwell. ``I think everyone expected this kind of
opening.''
</P>
<P>
   Paramount distribution chief Wayne Lewellan said
``Insurrection'' was drawing well among men and is well positioned
among upcoming holiday movies, with a majority of the major
releases aimed at families (``The Prince of Egypt,'' ``Mighty Joe
Young'') and women (``You've Got Mail,'' ``Stepmom''). ``You know
with `Star Trek' that you'll have the core audience of fans, so the
task is to go past that,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trek'' films, launched in 1979, have grossed nearly $600
million domestically, led by ``The Voyage Home,'' the fourth
installment, with $112 million in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's fourth weekend of ``A Bug's Life'' finished second with
$11 million at 2,748 theaters as the computer-animated comedy
declined 36 percent from the previous Friday-Sunday. ``Life'' now
has $83.3 million and should continue to draw well through the
holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's other major opening, Warner Bros.' family comedy
``Jack Frost,'' posted lukewarm returns with $6.9 million at 2,152
screens. Bucksbaum said the results, coming amid strong holdover
competition, underscored the overall strength of the family market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows there's plenty of room for family films during the
holiday season,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   A trio of holdovers performed solidly -- Disney's fourth weekend
of ``Enemy of the State'' with $6.5 million at 2,517 sites,
Paramount's fourth weekend of ``The Rugrats Movie'' with $4.5
million at 2,706 theaters and Disney's sixth weekend of ``The
Waterboy'' with $4.3 million at 2,610 locations. ``The Waterboy''
has grossed $136.4 million and ranks 76th on the all-time domestic
box office list after ``Platoon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Disney is just dominating this season,'' Rockwell noted.
</P>
<P>
   Universal continued its dismal performance as its ``Psycho''
remake plunged from second to seventh with $3.8 million at 2,490
theaters, losing an astounding 62 percent of its opening weekend
audience. The thriller looks unlikely to match its estimated $25
million budget.
</P>
<P>
   Two high-priced Universal projects nearly vanished -- the fifth
weekend of ``Meet Joe Black'' with $1.63 million at 1,870 screens
and the third weekend of ``Babe: Pig in the City'' with $1.6
million at 2,240 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe'' has totaled $41.5 million while the ``Babe'' sequel has
reached only $13.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the top 10 was Gramercy's ``Elizabeth'' with $1.3
million at 555 theaters. Universal's parent Seagram Co. acquired
Gramercy last week as part of its $10.4 billion buyout of recorded
music giant PolyGram and has not yet indicated if it will sell
PolyGram's movie operations.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of well-reviewed Academy Award contenders posted solid
openings in limited release -- Paramount's ``A Simple Plan'' with
$400,000 at 31 theaters and Miramax's ``Shakespeare in Love'' with
$215,000 at eight screens.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the box office took in $76 million, down 18 percent
from the same 1997 weekend when ``Scream 2'' opened with $32.9
million. Year-to-date grosses have hit $6.4 billion, up 10 percent
over the same 1997 period, and the outlook is bright for the year's
final 2{ weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The slate is certainly as good as it was a year ago with a lot
of diversity,'' Rockwell said. ``There's something out there for
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum predicted ``The Prince of Egypt'' will open next
weekend with $28 million and take in $120 million overall, adding,
``It's a unique movie that we think is going to open up the field
of animation.'' Warner's comedy ``You've Got Mail'' should open
with $25 million, according to Bucksbaum.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
