<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFENSE SHOWS FIRE, NO POWER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Last week in New Orleans, it was about ``want
to.'' Here yesterday, the Cowboys simply ``couldn't.'' As in win.
</P>
<P>
   On the football manhood scale, there is a large difference in
the two. In the NFL standings, however, both were registered as
L's.
</P>
<P>
   Applaud no team for the act of showing up and playing hard, but
the stark contrast from one week to the next was noticeable, which
makes last week even more shameful.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys in New Orleans were a disgrace to franchise
heritage. As opposed to the Cowboys at Arrowhead Stadium, who were
a struggling, injury-depleted offensive outfit that finally located
the long-lost end zone in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Yanking out a victory after three quarters of despair even
became a reality. But the Cowboys' defense had two different
fourth-quarter chances to make possession stops on the Chiefs, and
couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   KC by 20-17 sent the Cowboys tumbling to their third consecutive
defeat. They are going backward in December, as the record slipped
to 8-6. To the rest of the league, they are a playoff-bound NFC
East joke. At the moment, there is no rebuttal, either.
</P>
<P>
   But first things first. ``We played a lot harder than last week
_ in their hearts, they responded today,'' said coach Chan Gailey,
who was disappointed, yet almost strangely confident in his
postgame demeanor. A week ago, Gailey's mood alternated between
shell shock and anger as he had tried to explain his team's New
Orleans farce.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least we didn't quit like last week,'' admitted fullback
Daryl Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   A media-type mentioned to Johnston that Fox voice John Madden
was on TV labeling the Cowboys as ``too old.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston sat up on his locker-room stool and responded tersely,
``Three weeks ago, after the Minnesota game, everybody was calling
us the hottest offensive team in the league. And we were. So now,
two games later, we're suddenly too old? That doesn't make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Good answer. But for a multitude of other questions, the Cowboys
have few if any answers. This is an offense that went seven
consecutive quarters without a touchdown, and produced six points
in that span.
</P>
<P>
   And what ails the Cowboys at the moment is all about offense. It
was last week in New Orleans, and here again yesterday. The defense
hangs in enough to give Dallas a chance to win, but winning for the
Cowboys, as with most NFL teams of this era, is all about offense.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries are only an offensive excuse, although a legitimate
excuse.
</P>
<P>
   Forget Deion Sanders being out, plus Kevin Smith. Young
replacement corners Charlie Williams and Kevin Mathis did good work
yesterday against a Chiefs offense that had thrown its way to three
consecutive games of 30-plus points.
</P>
<P>
   Where the defense had a breakdown was stopping Bam Morris. He
rumbled along for 137 yards rushing, in the process chewing up the
likes of Leon Lett, who has lost his all-world status.
</P>
<P>
   But still, the Cowboys should be winning games when the
opposition scores 20 points off the defense in two consecutive
games. But the offense has put up 20 combined points in the last
two losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably the most surprised,'' said Gailey when asked
about the offensive woes. Later, he added, ``There is no doubt in
my mind we will get it turned around.''
</P>
<P>
   Not, however, without better health. Michael Irvin missed the
second half yesterday with a back injury. That meant the Cowboys'
top two receivers, Irvin and Ernie Mills, were not available, with
Mills, of course, gone for the season. Add to that list tight end
David LaFleur, who sat out this one after being injured in New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Aikman was missing favorite targets as the fourth-quarter
comeback started. The opposition doesn't have to show normal
respect for the air game, so has that lead to the sudden
ground-game drought? Or is it vice versa?
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith was going nowhere again yesterday, because there
was nowhere to go. Unlike New Orleans, the Chiefs didn't blitz both
Aikman and Emmitt into submission. Kansas City played it basically
straight on defense, and won the line-of-scrimmage battle.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys couldn't establish the run early, and after two
critical second-half turnovers led to a 17-3 deficit, the run went
out of the game plan. Without LaFleur, the Cowboys' ``strong-side''
blocking (the side where the tight end lines up) is almost
nonexistent. This is the bread-and-butter area for a running game.
Yesterday, it wasn't available. The same goes for last week.
</P>
<P>
   Very quietly, LaFleur, who is due back Sunday, had become a key
to both run and pass success. And tight end is the one area of the
team where depth doesn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, however, the Cowboys' offensive line has had its
butt kicked for two weeks. Three weeks if you count the lack of a
ground game against Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Will this change? Will the offense suddenly become productive
again? ``It will,'' predicted Gailey. For now, we'll just have to
take his word for it.
</P>
</TEXT>
