<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ANALYSIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY OFFENSIVE FAILURE DOOMS COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Cowboys finished the game with two
touchdowns in the final 15 minutes yesterday. But it is the first
45 minutes of offense that conspired to send this club to its third
consecutive defeat of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys had as many punts, six, as first downs in the first
three quarters of a 20-17 loss to the Kansas City Chiefs. In the
last two weeks, the Cowboys have averaged 10 points per game. They
averaged 27 points per game over the first 12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably the most surprised to be honest with you,'' Chan
Gailey said. ``I thought things were going well and all of a sudden
we hit a stretch where we couldn't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The absence of blocking tight end David LaFleur, who injured his
knee last week, derailed the running game. Emmitt Smith had few
holes and finished with 42 yards on 14 carries.
</P>
<P>
   The inability of the Cowboys wide receivers to consistently beat
the Chiefs cornerbacks in man-to-man coverage cost them in the
passing game. To be sure, the Cowboys did play the entire second
half without Michael Irvin, who injured his back. But Irvin had
nothing to do with four first half dropped passes, or Troy Aikman's
third quarter interception that put the Cowboys in a two touchdown
hole from which they could never recover.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the third quarter, Aikman had tried to go deep
down the left sideline to Patrick Jeffers, who was covered by Mark
McMillian. Chiefs safety Jerome Woods, however, raced over from the
middle of the field for the interception with 3:34 remaining in the
third quarter. Six plays later, the Chiefs had a 17-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were jamming our guys, getting physical and we saw it and
figured we had to take a shot,'' said Aikman, who was 18 of 35 for
199 yards. ``The safety was in the middle and he made up ground. I
should have tried to hold him up a little better. I didn't think he
could get over and make a play on the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys running game suffered because they could not be
versatile in their play calling. LaFleur's replacement on the
strongside of the Cowboys attack, Hayward Clay, lacks experience as
a run-blocker. The Cowboys ran just three times to the strongside,
running backs coach Clarence Shelmon said. The Chiefs noticed that
the Cowboys were running mainly up the middle or away from Clay's
side and were easily able to load up to hold the Cowboys to 51
yards on 16 carries.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs would not have been able to load up against the run
had the Cowboys passing game provided consistent pressure. With
simple man-to-man coverage Chiefs cornerbacks Dale Carter and James
Hasty held the Cowboys receivers to four receptions for 36 yards
through the game's first 45 minutes. Irvin had just one catch for
nine yards before he was hurt. Patrick Jeffers, Jeff Ogden, and
Eric Bjornson combined to drop four passes in the first 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got good cornerbacks who were just squatting right
where we wanted to make breaks in our routes,'' Jeffers said.
``They were very physical. We needed to take it to them a little
more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys did take it to them in the fourth quarter. Jeffers
and Smith caught touchdown passes. But, said Gailey, ``it was too
little, too late.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
