<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT BRILL'S, MORE LIGHT, LESS `HOMEWORK'  
PRECEDING PRIME TIME WITH INFOMERCIALS  
THE A.P ON LINE RAISES QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, Steven Brill, the chairman and editor in chief of the
media-watchdog monthly Brill's Content, lost his editor, Michael
Kramer, and may have lost some of what even Brill says is the
sometimes overly heavy feel of his magazine, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're basically lightening up a bit on the tone of
everything,'' Brill said last week after he and Kramer decided to
part company _ although the two changes are not related. Brill's
Content has been awfully serious _ dour, even _ in its pursuit of
journalistic hi-jinks.
</P>
<P>
   Even Brill acknowledges that during its first six months it has,
at times, read like ``homework.'' The question he has always had to
answer is: Can his magazine find an audience with nonjournalists?
</P>
<P>
   ``The original rap against this magazine was that this is
interesting for us, but is anyone else going to care? '' Brill
said, the ``us'' being professional journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Is the solution to run some big, splashy, puffy profiles?
</P>
<P>
   No, Brill said. But he said the February issue would be a bit
more reader friendly. ``You will see a difference in the next issue
in the design and pace of the magazine. There are a lot of things
that are shorter.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Brill added, ``there are still a significant number of
pieces about serious stuff. But there's a much better mix so that
the magazine doesn't have the feel of homework that it has had.''
</P>
<P>
   Brill said the cover would be less busy, and he had added a
one-page photo essay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for infomercials, those half-hour plugs for
everything from exercise machines to car wax, to appear on
network-owned television stations, like WCBS-TV in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But it is certainly unusual, if not precedent setting, when they
turn up on a weeknight at 7:30 p.m., directly before prime time
starts.
</P>
<P>
   That is one reason a decision by the executive in charge of the
stations CBS owns, to fill three half-hour blocks this month with
infomercials, raised so many eyebrows in the television industry,
including some inside CBS itself.
</P>
<P>
   The executive, Jonathan Klein, sold time to three companies for
infomercials, displacing such highly rated syndicated shows as
``Entertainment Tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason, several CBS executives said, was a simple desire to
generate extra revenue for the CBS stations before the end of the
calendar year.
</P>
<P>
   The infomercial issue is clearly a sensitive one inside CBS.
Network executives, including Klein, declined to comment on the
decision. Privately, many CBS executives expressed unhappiness with
what they said was the likelihood that the decision would leave the
impression that CBS is desperate for revenue.
</P>
<P>
   This impression would run counter to some promising developments
for CBS, with several prime-time shows demonstrating strong
improvement, including one, ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' moving
toward outright hit status.
</P>
<P>
   Klein, who has long experience with local advertising sales at
network affiliated stations, where it is common to pre-empt network
programs for locally owned programs in an effort to bring in more
advertising revenue, ordered the infomercials played at 7:30 p.m.
on 13 CBS stations.
</P>
<P>
   A click away from many major Internet destinations _ from the
``Today's News'' section of America Online to the front page of the
search engine Yahoo _ _ is a wealth of headlines and articles from
The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   This may seem routine to news consumers, but is a matter of
puzzlement to some newsroom executives, who wonder why an
organization created as a membership cooperative that now includes
1,500 newspapers, is providing material for sites competing _
successfully _ with the newspapers' own online editions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The A.P. is being used on line by search engines in terms that
seem competitively irrational,'' was the way Steve Coll, The
Washington Post's managing editor, put it at the Jupiter
Communications Digital News Forum in Atlanta last week. Web sites
like America Online's AOL.com and Yahoo have no news of their own
to offer, but a Jupiter survey indicates they are among the most
popular destinations for those seeking a quick news fix on line.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's AOL contributing?'' Ron Martin, the editor of The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution asked, picking up Coll's theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or Yahoo?'' Coll added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer is: a lot of money,'' said Wick Temple, the A.P.'s
vice president and director of newspaper membership, when asked
about the issue. On-line fees run in the ``millions of dollars'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   The group's 24-member board, Temple said, voted 12 years ago to
create an online news wire _ offering only the work of the A.P.'s
own journalists _ and sell it to Compuserve, one of the first
online services. If The Associated Press now refused to do business
with America Online or Yahoo, he said, it would simply open the
door for competitors like the Reuters news service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
