<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ROSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLES ROSE, PROSECUTED ORGANIZED CRIME FIGURES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Charles E. Rose, who prosecuted bank robbers,
narcotics traffickers, terrorists and organized-crime figures in 15
years with the U.S. attorney's office for the Eastern District of
New York, died on Saturday at his home in Manhattan. He was 51.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a brain tumor, said his sister, Marilyn Duer.
</P>
<P>
   From 1994 to his death, Rose was a partner in the Manhattan law
firm of De Feis, O'Connell &AMP; Rose, specializing in defense
litigation in white-collar crime and some organized-crime cases.
</P>
<P>
   He was with the federal prosecutor's office from 1979 to 1994
and held the titles of assistant U.S. attorney, deputy chief and
chief of the office's narcotics section, senior litigation counsel
and executive assistant U.S. attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie Rose was the finest prosecutor I ever worked with. He
was smart, dedicated and a cop's prosecutor,'' New York Police
Commissioner Howard Safir said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In Rose's early years in the U.S. attorney's office he
prosecuted bank robbers and worked with the FBI-New York Police
Department joint task force on bank robbery. Later, he shifted to
supervising the prosecution of cases developed by the police
department and the FBI in a task force on terrorism. In that role
he was concerned mainly with a group seeking independence for
Puerto Rico, whose bombing targets included the headquarters of the
police department and the FBI headquarters at Federal Plaza, and
also with an anarchist group, the United Freedom Front. In 1986,
Freedom Front members were tried and convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Rose went on to work on cases involving heroin trafficking in
organized crime. Later, he was prominent in the prosecution of
reputed Mafia figures including Vincent Gigante, who was arrested
in 1990 on federal charges that he conspired with 14 other reputed
gangsters to rig bids and extort payoffs from contractors on
multimillion-dollar bids with the New York City Housing Authority.
</P>
<P>
   A superseding indictment in 1993 accused Gigante of sanctioning
the murders of six mobsters and plotting to kill three others,
including John J. Gotti, the Gambino boss who was his former
archrival.
</P>
<P>
   By early 1997, after Rose had stopped being a prosecutor, all
defendants in the conspiracy case had been convicted or acquitted _
except for Gigante, whose case had been delayed by hearings about
whether he was mentally deranged. Eventually he was tried and
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Rose was born and raised in the Bronx, received a bachelor's
degree in 1968 from Cornell, a master's degree in 1976 in
criminology from the State University of New York at Albany and a
law degree in 1979 from Brooklyn Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his sister, of St. Peter's, Pa., he is survived by his
mother, Marie L. Rose of Hohokus, N.J.; his wife, the former Carol
Mennie, from whom he was long separated; and his fiancee, Elaine
Banar of Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 2254EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
