<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-13 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7726 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERET-PURCHASE-NYT     12-13 0177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERET-PURCHASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAMOUS BERET WEARER BUYS ANOTHER
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ All season, the black beret for sale in the hat
department at the trendy Fred Segal shop in Santa Monica, Calif.,
had been more a conversation piece than a must-have purchase, and a
number of shoppers stopped to make some crack or other about what
they all recognized as ``the Monica Lewinsky beret.''
</P>
<P>
   Then last week, with the Judiciary Committee debating the
consequences of the president's cover-up of his dalliance with Ms.
Lewinsky, who should walk in but the world's most famous former
intern, wearing low-key leggings and huge, movie-star sunglasses?
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Lewinsky purchased the beret, put it on and wore it out
of the store, the sales staff nearly had to be resuscitated _ all
the more so because her credit card took five minutes to clear and
they had to refrain from laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was trying to look totally incognito wearing these big
glasses,'' said a Los Angeles shop owner, ``and then she puts on
the hat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
