<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ About the only thing that will make this Cowboys
game look better is the fact the previous week's game film is still
sitting on a shelf at Valley Ranch.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But for the second consecutive Sunday, the Cowboys were the far
inferior team, this time losing a 20-17 decision to the Kansas City
Chiefs at Arrowhead Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was actually Dallas' third consecutive loss, the other two
coming at the hands of Minnesota and New Orleans. And it was again
a wasted opportunity, with Dallas still needing one victory (or one
Arizona loss) to win the NFC East.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, we're trying,'' running back Emmitt Smith said in
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Like the team that finally wins games after being eliminated
from the playoffs, the Cowboys eventually managed to score
touchdowns on their final two drives to make the score respectable.
But while the numbers weren't as horrendous as the previous week in
New Orleans, the level of play wasn't much better until that final
quarter. Eliminate those two possessions, and the Cowboys spent the
other 45 minutes compiling 106 yards of total offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we could have had that (intensity) the whole game,''
linebacker Randall Godfrey said. ``It's tough to say why we were
flat in the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly not tough to say where. The ground game again
fell upon hard times.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, it was New Orleans' blitz that stymied the run.
Sunday, it was Kansas City's eight-man front. It wasn't as ugly as
last week's eight-yard debacle, but it wasn't a whole lot better.
Smith carried 14 times for 42 yards, his only breakout being one
11-yard dash. Receivers Billy Davis and Michael Irvin each had one
carry to take Dallas' rushing total to 51 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason you see guys in here so disappointed is that we
think we're working hard enough,'' Smith said. ``We know what's
going on. We just can't win a game.''
</P>
<P>
   The air attack was passable but anything but deadly, especially
after the Cowboys lost Irvin to lower-back spasms at the end of the
first half. With Ernie Mills already shelved for the season and
tight end David LaFleur out possibly until the end of the regular
season, quarterback Troy Aikman was searching for targets. Patrick
Jeffers was the big winner with five receptions for 74 yards,
including a 28-yard touchdown. Smith actually fared better in this
stat than on the ground, catching four balls for 41 yards and a TD.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way they were playing us, we probably needed to take it to
them a little more,'' Jeffers said. ``We were able to make
adjustments and move the ball a little better in the second half,
but it wasn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys punted on their first four possessions despite
having three drives begin on their 41-, 34- and 43-yard lines. They
finally got on the board with a field goal but only after seven
plays netted 17 yards. A 35-yard punt return by Tyrone Hughes
allowed Dallas to start on the Kansas City 32. The Chiefs stopped
them at the 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they first started running the ball early in the game,
they weren't going anywhere,'' Chiefs linebacker Donnie Edwards
said. ``Then, we knew they might be in trouble. We got after them
early and stopped the run, and that's what we wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys would have liked to do the same. Though quarterback
Rich Gannon had powered the Chiefs to three consecutive games of 31
points or more with a potent air attack, it was Bam Morris who
caused the most problems Sunday. The former Texas Tech standout
rushed for 137 yards on 27 carries, many of those yards coming
after he shook off a Dallas defender or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 260 pounds. We tried,'' Godfrey said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys repeatedly missed tackles, often laying the initial
hit only a yard or two out only to see Morris escape from their
grasp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bam is huge,'' Dallas safety George Teague said. ``I don't
know how he looks to you guys, but he's very big, and he absorbs
hits very well. He takes a lick and keeps on moving his legs. We
didn't mess him up enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Cowboys' lousy halftime stats _ five first downs and
93 total yards _ the score was tied at 3. But Dallas let things
spin out of control with a series of mistakes in the third quarter.
A fumbled punt return by Hughes gave Kansas City the ball at
midfield. The Chiefs then marched 50 yards, with Morris reaching
the end zone from a yard out.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, Chiefs cornerback James Hasty jumped in front
of Jeffers to snag an interception, returning the ball 28 yards to
the Dallas 35. Gannon scored on a nine-yard run to make it 17-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys were again without cornerback Deion Sanders, who had
missed the previous two games with a sprained big toe but was
expected back. With Irvin out in the second half, the Cowboys were
without two of their biggest emotional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we are better with those players that are hurt,''
Aikman said. ``But you can't dwell on that. You still have to
execute.''
</P>
<P>
   Just three weeks ago, the Cowboys had won four consecutive games
and six of their last seven. They had gotten through a stretch
without Aikman and were looking at an easy finish, with their last
four opponents after the Vikings all under .500.
</P>
<P>
   But that 8-3 mark has quickly become 8-6. They are a mere 2-6
outside of their pitiful division, the only victories coming over
Carolina and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   And now the Cowboys are hearing echoes of last year's 6-10
campaign, which included a winless December as part of a
season-ending five-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you this: It's not going to be the same kind of
December,'' Godfrey said. ``It's right here. We've just got to grab
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
