<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ENID NEMY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   I had arranged to meet my daughter, Tali, on Third Avenue, and
as I approached I could hear police cars screeching to the curb,
sirens blasting and red lights flashing. I spotted my daughter
rushing toward me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look Mom,'' she said, laughing and pointing across the street.
``It's a chicken!''
</P>
<P>
   To my surprise, there was a very alive, very frightened chicken,
the scrawniest creature I had ever seen. The poor chicken was
pacing back and forth on the sidewalk, undoubtedly trying to decide
whether to brave Third Avenue traffic or stay and face the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the police were facing a dilemma of their own. Once
within reach of the chicken, the officers realized they were not
sufficiently equipped to catch it.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, one of the more daring took action. Armed with an old
cardboard box grabbed from a grocery stand, he lunged at the
chicken and managed to scoop the box over it. Now things were back
at stalemate, with the chicken only temporarily confined.
</P>
<P>
   Hunger and the passing of time finally got the better of us. We
decided to leave. At last glance, the police cars were speeding
away, and three anxious police officers were guarding the box. We
passed up the chicken dishes on the lunch menu.
</P>
<P>
   _ SUSANA SEDGWICK
</P>
<P>
   Linda Blum was walking uptown on Madison Avenue on Halloween
when she was mesmerized by a dachshund ambling along on a leash.
His sides were covered by two tan oval cushions and a wavy line of
yellow felt trailed down his back. The dog's owner spotted Ms.
Blum's amused expression and explained. ``It's his Halloween
costume,'' she said. ``He's a hot dog. ''
</P>
<P>
   Requirements listed on a recent ``help wanted'' sign in a bakery
on 17th Street intrigued Norman Oder: Honest, Hard Working,
Engaging or Relatively Engaging, or Appear To Be Relatively
Engaging.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   Having spent most of my 47 years running on Manhattan's
unforgiving sidewalks, I knew to look for dogs, and often a
retractable, impossible-to-see-at-night fish-line leash attached.
</P>
<P>
   This tiny dog was under a car, sniffing a tire, not visible
until it was too late. The owner was, of course, looking in a
window, oblivious to the fact that her leash was like a trip wire
across the entire width of the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Even before I hit the ground hard, bloodying my knees, palms and
head, she was screaming, ``Oh, my God, are you OK? Tell me you're
OK!'' At least she seemed contrite! I muttered, ``Yeah, I'm OK.''
She responded: ``Not you! Biscuit! You could have broken her
neck.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ISAAC S. HERSCHKOPF
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Gerber and Christine Schmidt spotted this sign as they
were traveling through Little Falls, N.J.:
</P>
<P>
   ``Open most days about 9 or 10,
</P>
<P>
   occasionally as early as 7, but
</P>
<P>
   some days as late as 12 or 1.
</P>
<P>
   We close about 5:30 or 6, but
</P>
<P>
   sometimes as late as 11 or 12.
</P>
<P>
   Some days or afternoons
</P>
<P>
   we aren't here at all,
</P>
<P>
   and lately I've been here
</P>
<P>
   just about all the time
</P>
<P>
   except when I'm someplace else,
</P>
<P>
   but I should be here then, too.''
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the Museum of Modern Art, Susan Striker was
savoring the luxury of a members-only opening of the Jackson
Pollock exhibit without being jostled by the usual crowds. She
noted that the overheard conversations were on a level above ``My
3-year-old can paint better than that,'' and that it seemed
everyone was serious about art. Then one elderly woman turned to
another and said, ``The best thing about Jackson Pollock is that
when I look at his paintings I don't see the floater in my eye.''
</P>
<P>
   MERRY CHRISTMAS
</P>
<P>
   Deck the halls with boughs of holly,
</P>
<P>
   Deck the tree with angels, frosted,
</P>
<P>
   Deck the doors with wreaths, and golly,
</P>
<P>
   Deck the couch with me, exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   _ MAUREEN CANNON
</P>
<P>
   Recently, a Queens-bound N train stood at 57th Street with its
doors open. Three minutes grew to five and then 10. Finally, the
driver took to the intercom, explaining that the train was stuck
because the one ahead was experiencing ``passenger interference.''
</P>
<P>
   A short silence ensued as the well-behaved passengers digested
the information. Then one man delivered his opinion. ``Shoot him,''
he suggested. JoAnn C. Gutin noted that he got his laugh, but
another rider stepped in with something more appropriate. ``Nah,''
he said. ``Passenger interference is only a 15-yard penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Simpson was pleased when Eric, her highly active
7-year-old pupil arrived for his piano lesson and greeted her with
enthusiasm. However, she wondered whether she'd be able to hold his
attention that day _ she was going to explain how to count dotted
rhythms, a formidable concept for any child. He sat perfectly
still, eyes glued to her face. ``Oh boy,'' she thought. ``He's
taking it in. We'll be making real progress now.''
</P>
<P>
   She then asked Eric if he had any questions. There was a
thoughtful pause, and he lifted his gaze above her eye level.
Forget dotted rhythms. He had obviously been concentrating on what
he considered a less than perfect coiffure. ``Would you like me to
find you a hairbrush?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gordon Mahler was in Zion National Park, Utah, standing
on the canyon floor admiring the surrounding spectacular mountains,
when a fellow tourist addressed a friend: ``This is just like New
York City. My neck hurts from looking up.''
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOPHOBIA
</P>
<P>
   I'm sick of words like CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   And those old favorites, dot and com.
</P>
<P>
   I hope that I will never see
</P>
<P>
   Another modem or PC.
</P>
<P>
   I much prefer the type of mouse
</P>
<P>
   That's caught by cats inside a house.
</P>
<P>
   I feel that I can do just fine
</P>
<P>
   Without a Windows 99.
</P>
<P>
   Each night and day I pray the Fates
</P>
<P>
   Keep me from products by Bill Gates!
</P>
<P>
   And not, by golly and by gosh,
</P>
<P>
   Cause me to use a Macintosh!
</P>
<P>
   And, sure as shootin', you can bet
</P>
<P>
   I do not need the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In short I hope it's understood
</P>
<P>
   I love my ancient Underwood!
</P>
<P>
   _ ANDRE MOUL ROSS
</P>
<P>
   An amused grandmother reassured her visiting 7-year-old
granddaughter that tooth fairies were everywhere and that the two
teeth under her pillow would be taken care of. Indeed, the next
morning, the tooth fairy had left some money, and also granted the
request in the girl's note: I woold like it if I kod pleas keep my
teeth. ThankU. Love Elaine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
