<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday 12/13/98. Photo clients
will automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or
may download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) REDWOOD CITY, Calif. -- Dec. 13, 1998 --
INTERNET-SPAM-BLACKLIST, 12-13 -- Paul Vixie and his team help
Internet companies and networks shield the individuals they serve
from the unwanted e-mail known as spam. Vixie is the creator and
keeper of the Realtime Blackhole List, a frequently updated list of
Internet service providers and Web-hosting companies that he
concludes are being used to send unsolicited bulk e-mail, or spam.
(Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Dec. 13, 1998 -- AILEY-DANCE-REVIEW, 12-13
-- Glenn Sims lifts Desiree Vlad in ``Ascension'' by the Alvin
Ailey American Dance Theater troupe at the City Center.
``Ascension,'' choreographed by Troy O'Neil Powell has a muscular
wit. The piece offers a punch line, but its winning grace is an
overall polish. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- Dec. 13, 1998 --
FBN-GIANTS-BRONCOS, 12-13 -- The New York Giants Corey Widmer (90)
tackling Terrell Davis (30) en route to a 20-16 Giants victory. The
combination of a swarming defense and an effective offense helped
the Giants end the Broncos' quest for a perfect season -- much to
the relief of the 1972 Dolphins. While there was disappointment in
the Broncos' locker room, most of the players know there is a more
important goal ahead: the playoffs. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) PHILADELPHIA -- Dec. 13, 1998 -- SOFT-WITNESS-PROFILE,
12-13 -- David Farber, a 64-year-old University of Pennsylvania
telecommunications professor, considered an expert on the Internet.
Farber is a main witness for a trial in which the central question
is whether Microsoft tried to monopolize the market in Internet
browser software. ``I am endlessly astonished that all too often
the trials seem not to be interested in extracting the truth,''
says Farber, after a difficult day of cross-examination by
Microsoft's lawyer, Steven Holley. (Marty Katz/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Dec. 13, 1998 -- OBIT-UDALL-B&AMP;W, 12-13 --
Morris Udall in New York in 1976 with Bella Abzug and other
Democrats. Udall of Arizona, a liberal conscience of the House of
Representatives for 30 years and a tireless advocate for
environmental protection and political reform, died late Saturday
in Washington. He was 76. Udall died of complications from
Parkinson's disease, according to the Morris K. Udall Foundation in
Tucson, Ariz. First diagnosed in 1980, the disease led to Udall's
resignation from Congress in 1991. (Don Hogan Charles/The New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEVE SHALOM, Israel -- Dec. 13, 1998 -- MIDEAST-CLINTON,
12-13 -- Hillary Rodham Clinton surrounded by Jewish and Arab
children Sunday during her visit to Neve Shalom on the eve of
Hanukkah. The village founded by Jews and Arabs is named in Hebrew
as the ``Oasis Of Peace.'' President Clinton is engaged in a
critical salvage mission for the faltering peace effort in the
Middle East, and has made himself an indispensable authority figure
in the blood feud between the Israelis and the Palestinians. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo) *Eds: Please note that this photo
has been retransmitted as MIDEAST-HILLARY.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) TALLAHASSEE, Fla. -- Dec. 13, 1998 -- OBIT-CHILES, 12-13
-- Florida Governor Lawton Chiles, left, being sworn in by Florida
Supreme Court Chief Justice Stephen Grimes as Chiles' wife Rhea
looks on during his inauguration. Chiles, a homespun centrist
politician from the middle of Florida, who served three terms as a
Democratic senator and was elected to two terms as governor, died
Saturday at the governor's mansion in Tallahassee. He was 68.
Chiles, who had a history of heart trouble, died from an abnormal
heart rhythm. (Michael Wilson/Lakeland Ledger Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CANTON, Ohio -- Dec. 13, 1998 -- IMPEACH-REACT, 12-13 --
At the News Depot in Canton, Sam Sliman, a co-owner, stacks
newspapers from across the state Sunday, every one with the same
basic lead headline screaming: House Votes Next on Impeachment!
``You know what's funny,'' says Sliman, a registered Republican who
thinks that the House should impeach the president but that he
should not be removed from office. ``I went to two Christmas
parties last night and no one was talking about impeachment. They
were talking about baseball.'' (Scott Heckel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LOS ALAMOS, N.M. -- Dec. 13, 1998 --
IMPEACH-UNDEC-REDMOND, 12-13 -- Rep. Bill Redmond, 44, R-N.M.,
discussing the possible impeachment of President Clinton at the
Daylight Donut Coffeeshop in Los Alamos. Impeachment should not be
decided by opinion polls, cautions Redmond, one of several dozen
representatives who have not announced how they will vote on
impeachment. ``You don't draw all your hypothesis until you have
all the data, and we don't have all the data,'' he says. (Cary
Herz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Dec. 13, 1998 -- DIABETES-CHILDREN, 12-13 --
Tyshon Young, 13, who has Type 2 diabetes, also known as
adult-onset diabetes, and Kira Almeida, a nutritionist, doing a
little comparison shopping at a Fairway supermarket. Many children
with the disease can control their blood glucose levels with weight
loss and diet modification. The spiraling rate of childhood obesity
in America -- declared an epidemic by the U.S. Surgeon General, is
the most significant factor in the rising number of children with
this form of diabetes. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW ORLEANS -- Dec. 13, 1998 --
READERS-PUBLISHERS-MEDIA-2, 12-13 -- One of several instructional
sessions in ``expressive exercises'' offered at Fast Company's
second ``Real Time'' conference. The conference gives Fast Company,
a technology-oriented business magazine targeted to young
entrepreneurs, a chance to interact with and solidify the
relationship with its readers. (Lee Celano/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW ORLEANS -- Dec. 13, 1998 --
READERS-PUBLISHERS-MEDIA-1, 12-13 -- Nan Crawford of Pacific
Playback Theater leading a group in ``expressive exercises'' like
``mechanical sculpture,'' at Fast Company's second ``Real Time''
conference. The conference gives Fast Company employees, a
technology-oriented business magazine targeted to young
entrepreneurs, a chance to interact with and solidify the
relationship with readers. (Lee Celano/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
