<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-CHIEFS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' SKID THREATENS NFC EAST LEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Just as they have the past three games, the
Cowboys found themselves in the downtrodden losers' locker room
yesterday trying to put a spin on a disappointing loss.
</P>
<P>
   One that prevented the Cowboys from clinching the playoffs for
the third consecutive week. One that saw them again play without
injured All-Pro cornerback Deion Sanders. And one that saw their
luster as a legitimate Super Bowl contender further tarnished.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, after yesterday's 20-17 loss to the Chiefs (6-8) at
Arrowhead Stadium, the Cowboys are no longer an absolute certainty
for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, normally talkative receiver Michael Irvin was left
battered and speechless. And usually positive Cowboys coach Chan
Gailey admitted that his team had digressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing we lost three in a row,'' said Irvin, who
was sidelined in the second quarter with a lower back contusion.
``To a man, it's disappointing. We expect to \Rturn it around\S.
...I just don't know what to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Gailey: ``We challenged our team about seven weeks ago to
get on a roll and win a few. We've almost set ourselves back to
that point again. That's not a good feeling. We've got to regroup
and fight our way into the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys (8-6) hold only a one-game lead over the Arizona
Cardinals (7-7) in the NFC East with two games to left. They still
have an easy road _ considering that they need only one victory in
the final two home games against the Philadelphia Eagles (3-11) or
the Washington Redskins (5-9) or a Cardinals loss to clinch the
title.
</P>
<P>
   However, in what appears to be more trend than aberration,
nothing is assured for the Cowboys _ unless you count a suddenly
punchless passing attack, a departed running game and an inability
to mount a consistent pass rush.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Emmitt Smith was a nonfactor on the ground for the
third consecutive week. His 50-yard outing followed 44-yard and
6-yard efforts against the Minnesota Vikings and New Orleans
Saints, respectively. The pass offense fared only slightly better
than last week's poor showing against the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, already handcuffed by the absence of receiver Ernie
Mills, was understandably further troubled without Irvin. He passed
for 199 yards _ but just 66 through the first three quarters, when
the Cowboys squandered solid field position and saw their streak of
quarters without a touchdown extended to seven.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman and the Cowboys broke the goose egg in the fourth quarter
with touchdown passes to former Fort Worth Country Day star Patrick
Jeffers (28 yards) and Smith (8 yards) as the Cowboys tried to
rally from a 17-3 deficit. But as Aikman said, ``it was too little,
too late.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been without a lot of people,'' Aikman said. ``But
that's part of the game. You've still got to execute. We just
didn't play well. We came back, but it wasn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the Cowboys' prowess on offense during the month of
November, which saw them roll up at least 30 points four of the
five contests, their problems on that side of the ball are most
troubling to Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to his dismay against the Chiefs were breakdowns in two
normally strong areas _ run defense and special teams. The Cowboys
had their first punt blocked in 611 tries, dating to 1989 against
the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   And a third-quarter fumble by punt returner Tyrone Hughes helped
the Chiefs break a 3-3 halftime tie and seize the momentum.
</P>
<P>
   That Chiefs' running back Bam Morris rushed for 137 yards and a
touchdown against the Cowboys' seventh-ranked run defense was
blamed on bad tackling. It offset a solid game against the pass by
much-maligned cornerbacks Charlie Williams and Kevin Mathis, who
started for Sanders (sprained toe) and Kevin Smith (back
contusion). Chiefs quarterback Rich Gannon, who passed for six
touchdowns in the past two weeks and led the Chiefs to 31.8 points
per game the past three games, passed for 200 yards and threw no
touchdown passes.
</P>
<P>
   However, in what may be the most indicative trend for the
Cowboys and their playoff chances, the end result was a loss to a
nondivision opponent. They are 2-6 outside the NFC East.
</P>
<P>
   That the Cowboys are 6-0 against their suspect division
opponents gives their playoffs chances a boost going into the final
two games against the Eagles and Redskins. However, their play of
late even has eternally confident Cowboys owner Jerry Jones
part-hopeful and part-confused.
</P>
<P>
   ``My confidence level is a lot higher than it was last year,''
Jones said. Last year the Cowboys ended with a five-game losing
streak, finished 6-10 and missed the playoffs for the first time in
six years. ``But we still have an opportunity,'' he said. ``I see
we are not playing well enough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we have a team that is capable of playing well enough
to win,'' Jones continued. ``I'm certainly not sure we can move the
ball for 30 points a game anymore and without Deion that we've got
enough defense to stop anybody. But I don't know that we can't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
