</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAWYER-LIBEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER LISTED AS `AMBULANCE-CHASER' LOSES CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In 1997, the American Association of University
Women's Legal Advocacy Fund published an updated version of its
directory of lawyers. For all but one of the approximately 275
lawyers listed, the directory's description consisted of a name, an
address and information about areas of expertise and fees.
</P>
<P>
   But for Leonard Flamm, a Manhattan lawyer who specializes in
employment discrimination, the entry in the directory, which lists
lawyers whose services might be useful to the association's
members, included a special note: ``At least one plaintiff has
described Flamm as an `ambulance chaser' with interest only in
`slam-dunk cases.'''
</P>
<P>
   Flamm said he saw red _ and a slam-dunk libel case. He sued in
state court.
</P>
<P>
   The case was transferred to U.S. District Court in Manhattan,
where, last week, Judge Denny Chin dismissed it, ruling that the
statement, as opinion rather than fact, cannot be libelous.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how distasteful'' the description of Flamm was, the
judge wrote, ``it was clearly an expression of opinion protected by
the First Amendment and the New York State Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   The association's lawyer, Laura Handman, said she was not
surprised by the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Flamm said he was ``very unhappy'' with the ruling. He disagreed
with Chin's reasoning, insisting that the phrase ``ambulance
chaser'' was not an opinion phrase. He noted that ``ambulance
chasing,'' the practice of seeking out injured people in the hope
of representing them, is a misdemeanor under New York State law.
``It's like calling me a robber or rapist, because it's a criminal
act, Flamm said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he believes he has a ``slam-dunk'' appeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-13-98 2331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
