A7889 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIANA-STANFORD-NYT     12-13 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIANA-STANFORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANA'S TITLE: FROM UKRAINE WITH LOVE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. _ Indiana was the only team to bring a band and
cheerleaders to the final four of this year's men's soccer
tournament, but more important the Hoosiers also brought the most
efficient group of players.
</P>
<P>
   The Hoosiers won their fourth National Collegiate Athletic
Association title Sunday afternoon by beating Stanford, 3-1, at the
University of Richmond Stadium before a crowd of 15,202 that braved
a steady rain.
</P>
<P>
   The three goals Sunday followed a 4-0 trouncing of Santa Clara
in the semifinals on Friday and made the Hoosiers (23-2) one of the
most productive teams in the finals. The seven goals were the most
scored by a winning team since St. Louis scored 10 in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   The victory also provided some redemption for a team that went
into last year's semifinals as the only undefeated team in the
country and lost to the eventual champion, U.C.L.A. The Hoosiers
kept saying before the semifinals that they learned from last year
and proved it with two marvelous performances this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We exorcised some demons,'' Coach Jerry Yeagley said. ``The
pain we felt from last year was with us for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Dema Kovalenko, Yuri Lavrinenko and Aleksei Korol, the three
Ukrainians who in the last two years have helped Indiana compile a
46-3 record with 148 goals for and 25 against, scored the goals
Sunday afternoon, all in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Kovalenko opened the scoring in the seventh minute with a shot
from 24 yards away after a cross from the right side by Lavrinenko.
The shot in the upper-right corner surprised Adam Zapala, the
Stanford goalkeeper, who was caught about 6 yards away from his
line.
</P>
<P>
   Kovalenko started the second goal with a cross from the right
that reached Korol on the left. Korol touched it into the middle to
Lavrinenko, who pounced on it from close range while the Stanford
defenders raised their hands for an offside call that never came.
</P>
<P>
   The only flaw in Indiana's play was poor distribution out of the
defense, but Stanford (18-5-2) wasn't able to capitalize often
enough. The one time the Cardinal flooded the attacking zone, it
earned a penalty that resulted in a goal in the 22nd minute. Simon
Elliott scored it for his ninth goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty came after Nick Garcia, the Indiana sweeper, who was
voted the tournament's outstanding defensive player, wrestled Corey
Woolfolk down in the penalty area.
</P>
<P>
   That brought the Cardinal to 2-1, but Korol, who was voted the
outstanding offensive player in the tournament, scored his 17th of
the year with 48 seconds left before intermission, pouncing on a
loose ball on the left after it was mis-hit by Indiana's Matt
Fundenberger. The goal brought despair to the Cardinal because it
was the first time all year that Stanford had allowed three goals
in a game, let alone a half.
</P>
<P>
   ``That third goal killed us,'' Stanford Coach Bobby Clark said.
``It's the sign of a great team to have guys with half a chance
that put it away.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
