<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-CATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW EDITOR'S GOAL IS TO BE THE TOP `CATS'
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call it a cat fight. Since September, Jane Reilly has been
editor of Cats magazine, which is published by Primedia Inc., and
the January issue _ that's the one with the proud cover line ``Hero
Cat Saves Family'' _ is the first one that is a product entirely of
her editorial vision.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Reilly's mission: to enter into a mewling, scratching battle
with the behemoth of the cat magazines, Cat Fancy, which is
published by Fancy Publications.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Reilly says that she feels she has enough power behind her
to wrestle Cat Fancy into that great litter box in the sky. Her
father is William Reilly, the chairman and chief executive of
Primedia.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the job at Cats came up, I thought, `It's a cat magazine.
Do I want to edit a cat magazine?' '' Ms. Reilly said. ``But I am
passionate about cats.'' And she does not feel awkward about
working for her father. ``My dad on some level is so far above this
magazine that I don't feel his presence,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cats magazine had an average circulation of 118,127 for the
six-month period that ended in June, according to the Audit Bureau
of Circulations, while Cat Fancy had 272,870. Both bimonthly
magazines are priced at $2.95.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Cat Fancy does a good job,'' Ms. Reilly said. ``But we
are going to take the reader farther.''
</P>
<P>
   Cat Fancy's publisher, Norman Ridker, said: ``They're a
billion-and-half-dollar company. Sure they can take us on.'' Ridker
added that Fancy Publications had filed a $12 million lawsuit in
Federal court in Los Angeles against Cats for a variety of
copyright infringements.
</P>
<P>
   A Primedia spokesman, David Adler, said that Primedia was not
concerned about the lawsuit. ``They are trying to use the courts to
stifle fair competition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Ms. Reilly is concerned about other matters.
She said there was only one potential downside to editing Cats.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my friends say, `You'll never have a date again,''' Ms.
Reilly said. ``There's this terrible stigma about single women and
cats.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
