r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUARD-GOOD-DEED-LADN     12-13 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUARD-GOOD-DEED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARALYZED GUARD DOESN'T REGRET TRYING TO SAVE SUICIDAL WOMAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Calling him a hero, hundreds of strangers and
friends have written Conrad Buchanan and visited him in the
hospital in the month since he broke his neck trying to catch a
woman who jumped six stories from a parking garage.
</P>
<P>
   Although the critical injuries have devastated his family,
Buchanan and some of his relatives said he has no regrets that he
tried to save a life.
</P>
<P>
   One of Buchanan's deeply moved visitors was Jon Light, the son
of the 68-year-old suicidal woman who leaped from the garage of the
Sherman Oaks Galleria in the suburban San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In the eight days after his cancer-stricken mother carried out
her death wish, Light said he was drawn to Buchanan's bedside to
see what he could do to acknowledge the split-second decision for
self-sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   ``After my mom died, that was hard. I just wanted to see how he
was doing,'' said Light, a 41-year-old attorney from Camarillo,
Calif., in neighboring Ventura County. ``I feel terrible for the
guy. He tried to do a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   They sat together for several hours. Buchanan is now paralyzed
from the neck down and has difficulty speaking. But his sister said
Light's visits have been good for the 26-year-old security guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother likes him,'' Melva Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   She said trying to help others is so characteristic of her
brother that his family was not surprised by his selfless act.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was the right thing to do. I think he would have
been traumatized if he had just sat there and not done anything,''
she said. ``He doesn't have any regrets. That was something that he
had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Light has helped Buchanan's family set up a trust fund for
Buchanan's wife and two daughters, 5 years old and 8 months old.
Light said he and his family plan to contribute thousands of
dollars to the fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just feel like we should do something,'' Light said.
</P>
<P>
   Since his first visit, Light has returned twice to see Buchanan
at Northridge Hospital Medical Center and calls the Buchanan family
for updates regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he got hurt would have devastated my mother. She
helped people all the time. It just would have been a nightmare for
her, I'm sure,'' Light said.
</P>
<P>
   Light's family held a memorial Sunday at his sister's house to
reflect on Julie Light's life.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime Sherman Oaks resident, she appeared regularly during
the 1950s as an actress in Hallmark Hall of Fame commercials. More
recently, she became severely depressed because of cancer and the
death in 1997 of her husband, Robert Light, 85, a former actor and
president of the Southern California Broadcasters Association.
</P>
<P>
   It all became too much for her to bear. On Nov. 15, she climbed
to the top of the parking garage, looked down and tried to warn
those below her to move out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, making his rounds as a security guard, refused to
move.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a caring person,'' his sister said. ``He's always
helping other people. If someone is down and under and they need
him to do something, he's always there. That's how he is. You could
always ask him to do favors.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who grew up and lives in downtown Los Angeles, would
never turn his back on somebody in danger, even if he knew he would
be risking his own life, his sister explained.
</P>
<P>
   As Light plummeted, Buchanan positioned himself to break her
fall from the top level of the parking structure, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The impact broke Light's back and Buchanan's neck. She died
later that night at a hospital, and police found a suicide note in
her car saying she was suffering great pain from cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan underwent neck surgery last week and is now in stable
condition and recovering, his sister said. Doctors are unsure
whether he will be paralyzed for life, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll just have to wait and see how he reacts,'' she said.
``He's alert. It's just rough for him.''
</P>
<P>
   She said her brother is capable of making decisions for himself
and can communicate.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's neighbor Gabrielle Stewart-Eastland, who went to
church with him and his family almost daily, said he is a devoted
husband and father whose smile always won friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an incredible person,'' she said. Just a week before the
tragedy, he saw her putting antifreeze into her car and routinely
stopped his car to see if she was having trouble, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the type of person he is. . . . He wanted to make
sure everything was OK,'' Stewart-Eastland said.
</P>
<P>
   She said he has a reputation for being a good neighbor. Many
tenants from his apartment complex have visited him in the
hospital, and ministers from his church have prayed with his family
at his bedside, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow guards and mall merchants and employees also visit, she
said, with gifts and toys for his children.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us feel terrible. . . . He's had a lot of visitors, a
lot of care, a lot of expressions of hope,'' Stewart-Eastland said.
</P>
<P>
   Her brother appreciates the community support, Melva Buchanan
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to thank everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The family has asked that anyone wishing to make donations to
Buchanan and his family write to Conrad Buchanan Donations, P.O.
Box 7362, Los Angeles, CA 90007.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
