<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-DOLPHINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS DEFEAT DOLPHINS, 21-16 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In their 30th game of the Bill Parcells regime, the New
York Jets became a playoff team on Sunday night. It had been seven
years since they last saw post-season play.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did they guarantee themselves a playoff spot with a
21-16 breathtaking victory over the Dolphins, punctuated by an
action-packed final quarter, but the Jets positioned themselves
grandly for their first division title since 1969.
</P>
<P>
   The victory lifted the Jets' record to 10-4 and put them alone
in first place in the American Football Conference East as the
Dolphins fell to 9-5. If the Jets win one of their final two games
_ at Buffalo and in the Meadowlands against the Patriots _ they
will take the division title.
</P>
<P>
   They are also in a good position to earn a first-round bye with
their 10 victories, the first time since 1986 the Jets have
produced a double-digit season.
</P>
<P>
   After the Jets had taken a 14-3 lead, the teams played a furious
final period.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Marino brought the Dolphins to the Jets' 10-yard line but
then was intercepted by Victor Green, who returned the ball 87
yards to the Miami 9.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' victory seemed assured. Fans even started to stream
out, prompting a Miami die-hard to yell, ``How can you people
leave!''
</P>
<P>
   But Green's big play was one of several to come before this game
would end.
</P>
<P>
   For Vinny Testaverde was intercepted in the end zone by Terrell
Buckley. Buckley was guarding Keyshawn Johnson, who had scored
against him the first time these teams met.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley returned the ball 61 yards to the Jets' 41. From there,
Marino launched a touchdown drive that ended with a 3-yard scoring
pass to O.J. McDuffie. The extra point made it 14-10.
</P>
<P>
   Now it really got interesting. The Dolphins' Olindo Mare
delivered an onside kick that Miami recovered. But Marino could not
get anything going, failing on a fourth-down pass. The Jets took
over and appeared secure, with Testaverde running for a pair of
first downs. But the Jets' top runner, Curtis Martin, fumbled the
ball back.
</P>
<P>
   Not for long, though. Ernie Logan produced the fifth Jets' sack
of Marino _ the most times he had been knocked down by them in his
career _ and the ball popped loose.
</P>
<P>
   Along came Chad Cascadden, who has a photograph of himself
sacking Marino in the first game this season. The linebacker picked
up the ball and returned it 23 yards for the crushing score.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins scored in the final seconds, and then the Jets fell
on another onside kick.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Jimmy Johnson asked the Dolphins' fans to cheer extra
loud on Sunday night. At times, the Jets' supporters nearly drowned
them out, south Florida having always had a huge New York sports
following.
</P>
<P>
   It was a raucous crowd, dominated by Dolphins fans, at the start
of the game. But often they were quieted by what was happening on
the field as the Jets took a 7-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins, 6-0 at home coming in, weren't accustomed to this
sort of disrespectful behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde and Wayne Chrebet generated several long plays in the
opening half, including a 52-yarder in the first period. On the
next play, Testaverde hooked up with Chrebet again on a 12-yard
touchdown pass, as the receiver was able to get into one-on-one
coverage with the hefty linebacker Robert Jones. That score more
than offset Olindo Mare's 24-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bryan Cox created some excitement in his first game
back here as Jet. He sacked Marino on a solo tackle and then teamed
with Cascadden to dump him again. Cox, who left here after the 1995
season with Jimmy Johnson's arrival, also knocked down a Marino
pass.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde also had a homecoming. The Heisman Trophy winner from
the University of Miami collaborated with Kyle Brady on the tight
end's s longest career catch, a 35-yarder, in the third period.
That set up a 9-yard Curtis Martin run, helped by blocks from his
wide receivers, for a 14-3 edge.
</P>
</TEXT>
