<HEADLINE>
OFF THE WALL: WELL, BUST MY BILLFOLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; Got a tiny piece of AD-vice for small-minded, short-sighted and
short-changed San Diego Padres owner John Moores, and it won't cost
nothin':
</P>
<P>
   Quit dodgin' the real issue here.
</P>
<P>
   Your rent-to-own deal with Kevin Brown expired, and you
unfortunately lost him to The Most Powerful Man in Sports who needs
to save face and happens to own a private jet.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't a small-market-vs.-big-market situation. If !ital!you
had the resources to sign him, you'd have pulled it off yourself
(see: Phoenix, cross reference Colangelo).
</P>
<P>
   It's not ``a truly tragic day for baseball.'' That would be
something along the lines of blackmailing the city's citizens to
fund your new stadium during the euphoria of a league title.
</P>
<P>
   And this doesn't confirm your worst fears about what would
happen if you let Rupert Murdoch buy the Dodgers. Your worst fear
already happened: You lost your money starter to an NL West foe
after allowing Ken Caminiti and Steve Finley to slip away, and
watching defected pitching coach Dave Stewart lure Joey Hamilton to
Toronto in a deal that doesn't include Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   (At least you got John Vander Wal locked in!)
</P>
<P>
   Just hand over the pink slip and call yourself prudent for not
giving $100 mil to someone who's !ital!arguably the best at what he
does.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get swept up in Rupert-bashing as you got swept in the
Series against the Yankees. Go clip your coupons and trade in your
pop bottles and invest in a few hungry players. (Hey, wait, what
day is today? Oh, darn, you missed the 39-cent cheeseburger deal at
McDonalds again). . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ P.S.: You owe Randy Myers about $12 million over the next two
years. Maybe convert him into a starter?
</P>
<P>
   __ P.S.S.: Still wanna pull the trigger on that Greg Vaughn
deal?. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ More than 80 percent of the 23,000-plus voters on an ESPN.com
insta-poll declared Brown isn't worthy of being the first baseball
player to earn $100 million. Who is? Don't know. It was just a
yes-or-no question. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ By the way, by Forbes magazine's recent guestimation, the
Dodgers franchise was worth $236 million _ about $100 mil more than
what Murdoch shelled out for 'em last spring. See a trend there? .
. .
</P>
<P>
   __ Brown is 6-0 lifetime against San Francisco with an ERA of
less than 0.60, including a no-hitter against them in '97. Barry
Bonds' lifetime average against him is .143 (3 for 21). . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Another Brown stat to gnaw on: Over the last four years, his
record in September is 12-4 with a 2.20 ERA. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Gary Sheffield is 7 for 14 with six RBI lifetime against
Brown. As if that matters. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Back to the latest 100 Most Powerful People in Sports list
released by The Sporting News, which placed Murdoch on top as he
was in '94 and '95: Chase Carey, the Dodgers' top dog and CEO of
Fox TV, followed Murdoch's coattails by jumping from No. 30 last
year to No. 6 this time. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Meanwhile, NBC Sports chief Dick Ebersol and Time Warner VP
Ted Turner, scheming to form a new pro football league, continue to
slip from the pedestal where once they stood. Ebersol, No. 1 in
'96, dropped to No. 10; Turner, No. 1 in '94, settled in at No. 13.
. . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Everyone knows the Giants are better than the Broncos. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Sunday's quote of the day came from Fox NFL studio
straight-man Howie Long. After Terry Bradshaw went off on a rant
about how he doesn't favor instant replay _ ``I just don't believe
in a perfect game . . . we need controversy'' _ Long replied, ``How
do you feel about indoor plumbing and electricity?'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Chicago wants a second NFL team and mayor Richard Daley says
the Raiders are welcomed to come over and use Comiskey Park.
Somehow, Al Davis and the Windy City seem like a perfect match.
</P>
</TEXT>
